INSERT INTO `items` VALUES (17,NULL,'Canadian Hunger Foundation in the classroom','<p><em>Contributed by the Canadian Hunger Foundation</em></p>\r\n<p>Ms. Lafond balances the curriculum of her World Issues class with hands-on activities that empower her grade 12 students to make a difference in the world. &ldquo;It\'s a better formula than just learning about sad or corrupt situations and feeling helpless,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n<p>While learning about the challenges facing families in developing countries and other global issues, Ms. Lafond&rsquo;s students at Osgoode Township High School are also taking action, with the help of Canadian Hunger Foundation&rsquo;s guest speakers and online resources. While exposing her students to the topic of international aid and the importance of giving assets to communities in need, her class raised close to $1,000 for local and overseas communities.</p>\r\n<p>As for Canadian Hunger Foundation, Ms. Lafond&rsquo;s class organized a week-long bake and smoothie sale at their school &mdash; which proved a welcome change from cafeteria food. &ldquo;Teenagers love baked goods and smoothies, let me tell you!&rdquo; says Ms. Lafond.</p>\r\n<p>After their week-long bake drive, her students enjoyed looking through Canadian Hunger Foundation&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://www.giftsthatmatter.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Gifts That Matter</a> catalogue and deciding what to buy with the $482 they raised. As they learned the importance of clean water, farming training and resiliency, the students opted to buy Gifts That Matter items like Mango Fruit Trees, Chickens, Farming Tool Kits, Safe Water Supplies as well as a Holiday Hamper &mdash; which is a little bit of all of the above.</p>\r\n<p>This is just the latest in a long string of contributions from the students at Osgoode Township. The school donated to Canadian Hunger Foundation for the first time in 1986 and has now donated well over $10,000 to help some of the world&rsquo;s poorest to build better lives for themselves and their families.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection questions</strong></p>\r\n<p>The reality of this situation is that many communities around the world are in need of financial resources, just like the one connected to Ms. Lafond&rsquo;s class. However, we ask:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How did Ms. Lafond go beyond just providing financial resources for a community?</li>\r\n<li>How did the students at Osgoode Township School benefit from this project? What might they have learned?</li>\r\n<li>What are other ways that this project could have been done to benefit both the givers and receivers of financial assistance?</li>\r\n<li>How does this approach and execution of a project align with the principles of good practices outlined here?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 02:39:43','2013-09-05 16:22:36',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p><em>Texte produit par la Canadian Hunger Foundation</em></p>\r\n<p>Mme Lafond &eacute;quilibre le programme de son cours sur les Probl&egrave;mes mondiaux par des activit&eacute;s pratiques qui permettent &agrave; ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 12e ann&eacute;e de changer les choses. &laquo; C&rsquo;est une meilleure approche que de se contenter de s&rsquo;informer des trag&eacute;dies et de la corruption en se sentant d&eacute;sempar&eacute;s &raquo;, dit-elle.</p>\r\n<p>Tout en s&rsquo;informant des probl&egrave;mes que doivent affronter les familles dans les pays en d&eacute;veloppement et d&rsquo;autres enjeux mondiaux, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de Mme Lafond &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole secondaire Osgoode Township passent &agrave; l&rsquo;action, avec l&rsquo;aide de conf&eacute;renci&egrave;res et de conf&eacute;renciers et de ressources en ligne de la <em>Canadian Hunger Foundation</em>. Sensibilis&eacute;s au th&egrave;me de l&rsquo;aide internationale et de l&rsquo;importance de fournir des ressources aux collectivit&eacute;s dans le besoin, ils ont recueilli pr&egrave;s de mille dollars pour des collectivit&eacute;s ici et &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger.</p>\r\n<p>Pour la <em>Canadian Hunger Foundation</em>, la classe de Mme Lafond a organis&eacute; pendant une semaine une vente de g&acirc;teaux et de smoothies &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole &ndash; changement fort bien accueilli par rapport au menu de la caf&eacute;t&eacute;ria. &laquo; Les ados adorent les p&acirc;tisseries et les smoothies, je vous assure! &raquo;, d&rsquo;ajouter Mme Lafond.</p>\r\n<p>Apr&egrave;s leur semaine de vente, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves ont &eacute;t&eacute; heureux de feuilleter le catalogue de la <em>Canadian Hunger Foundation</em> <a href=\"http://www.giftsthatmatter.ca/\" target=\"_blank\">Gifts That Matter</a> pour choisir ce qu&rsquo;ils ach&egrave;teraient avec les 482 $ r&eacute;colt&eacute;s. En d&eacute;couvrant l&rsquo;importance d&rsquo;une eau propre, de la formation en agriculture et de la r&eacute;silience, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves ont opt&eacute; pour des cadeaux comme des manguiers, des poulets, des outils agricoles, de l&rsquo;approvisionnement en eau potable et des paniers des F&ecirc;tes &ndash; qui regroupaient un peu de tout ce qui pr&eacute;c&egrave;de.</p>\r\n<p>Ce n&rsquo;est l&agrave; que la derni&egrave;re d&rsquo;une longue s&eacute;rie de contributions des &eacute;l&egrave;ves d&rsquo;Osgoode Township. L&rsquo;&eacute;cole a fait son premier don &agrave; la <em>Canadian Hunger Foundation</em> en 1986 et elle a maintenant donn&eacute; au-del&agrave; de 10 000 $ pour aider certaines des personnes les plus pauvres au monde &agrave; am&eacute;liorer leur vie et celle de leur famille.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion</strong></p>\r\n<p>Le fait est que de nombreuses collectivit&eacute;s dans le monde ont besoin de ressources financi&egrave;res, au m&ecirc;me titre que celles que rejoint la classe de Mme Lafond. Mais demandons-nous :</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>En quoi Mme Lafond a-t-elle fait plus que simplement fournir des ressources financi&egrave;res &agrave; une collectivit&eacute;?</li>\r\n<li>Quel profit les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de l&rsquo;&eacute;cole Osgoode Township retirent-ils de ce projet? Qu&rsquo;ont-ils pu apprendre?</li>\r\n<li>Y aurait-il d&rsquo;autres fa&ccedil;ons de faire qui auraient b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute; &agrave; la fois aux donateurs et donatrices et aux donataires de l&rsquo;aide financi&egrave;re?</li>\r\n<li>En quoi cette approche et la mise en &oelig;uvre du projet correspondent-elles aux principes de bonne pratique d&eacute;crits ici?</li>\r\n</ul>','La Canadian Hunger Foundation en classe','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(18,NULL,'‘Stories of hope’ inspire action on water issues','<p><em>Contributed by CAWST&rsquo;s Youth Wavemakers program</em></p>\r\n<p><em>The Centre for Affordable Water and Sanitation Technology (CAWST) Youth Wavemakers Program uses &lsquo;stories of hope,&rsquo; like the one below, to empower youth in Canada to become global citizens. The stories that are shared have inspired youth to take action in their own communities and schools to reduce water consumption and waste while connecting them to other global communities doing the same thing.</em></p>\r\n<p>One way to engage youth in global water issues is to collect stories from children in developing countries who have lived through challenges such as having contaminated well water or lacking access to a toilet. Through their stories, these kids show not just the problems, but creative solutions that their communities have used to overcome challenges and improve health and the environment.</p>\r\n<p>One such story is about a ten-year-old girl named Tikho who lives in Zambia. In April 2010, a Calgary educator met Tikho and asked her to share her story. With a digital camera, Tikho began to take photos and videos of her daily life, particularly as it related to water, sanitation and hygiene. Unfortunately, her community water source was badly contaminated and as a result Tikho&rsquo;s town was named <em>Chipulukusu</em>, or Cursed, because people were frequently getting sick and dying from waterborne diseases.</p>\r\n<p>How then, did the town become renamed to <em>Mapolo</em> or Blessed? Education. Once the community of Chipulukusu understood why they were getting sick, they began to take action, installing hand-washing stations (called tippy taps) and using biosand filters to clean their drinking water. Tikho is now fortunate enough to have a toilet as well: local residents learned how to build latrines in order to contain contamination and reduce disease transmission.</p>\r\n<p>A great way to engage young people in water and sanitation issues is to share stories similar to Tikho&rsquo;s. CAWST has found that when elementary students watch Tikho&rsquo;s video of her friends collecting water from the well, learn why people were getting sick and the actions they took to gain access to safe drinking water, the become inspired to make behaviour changes in their own use of water. Most children are shocked by the overuse of water in North America compared to Tikho&rsquo;s community. Many stop running the tap when they brush their teeth or start taking shorter showers. They also ask: &ldquo;what can we do in our own community?&rdquo; This becomes a stepping stone towards global citizenship. For example, as one grade 9 Calgary student explained:</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;People in Zambia use less than 20 litres of water per day while Calgarians use in excess of 300. This made us ask, could we use less? If so, why don&rsquo;t we?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>As her global leadership class began to look at various ways they could conserve water at home, they sent home leaky toilet testers to increase awareness about water wastage at home. Then, after realizing their school&rsquo;s urinals flushed every six minutes, they lobbied the school board to install sensors in order to reduce water consumption.</p>\r\n<p>Taking action on global and local water issues allows North American youth to follow Tikho&rsquo;s example by recognizing local and global water challenges while looking for solutions. One grade nine teacher believes that participation in an action project has allowed his students to feel that there is hope in dealing with some of the world&rsquo;s seemingly insurmountable issues: &ldquo;They get to feel a part of something bigger &ndash; and to realize they are not alone in fighting to make the world a better place.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection questions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What does this case study tell us about the nature of a successful school partnership?</li>\r\n<li>How does this case study achieve some of the benefits listed above?</li>\r\n<li>How did each partner benefit from this project?</li>\r\n<li>What are some issues that your students are studying right now that may connect with larger global issues? What are issues that your students are interested in? How might you use that to inform your next partnership or project?</li>\r\n<li>How might you inspire direct action and positive change through the projects you undertake?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 02:44:31','2013-09-05 16:12:01',1,'tall','','',NULL,'<p><em>Texte produit par le programme Youth Wavemakers du CAWST</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Le programme &laquo; Youth Wavemakers &raquo;[Les jeunes font des vagues] du Centre for Affordable Water and Sanitation Technology[Centre pour une technologie hydrique et sanitaire abordable](CAWST) utilise des &laquo; r&eacute;cits d&rsquo;espoir &raquo; comme celui-ci pour aider les jeunes au Canada &agrave; devenir des citoyennes et des citoyens du monde. Les r&eacute;cits partag&eacute;s de la sorte ont pouss&eacute; des jeunes &agrave; passer &agrave; l&rsquo;action dans leur collectivit&eacute; et dans leur &eacute;cole afin de r&eacute;duire la consommation et le gaspillage d&rsquo;eau, et &agrave; nouer des liens avec d&rsquo;autres collectivit&eacute;s qui font la m&ecirc;me chose.</em></p>\r\n<p>Une fa&ccedil;on d&rsquo;engager les jeunes par rapport aux enjeux mondiaux relatifs &agrave; l&rsquo;eau, c&rsquo;est de recueillir dans des pays en d&eacute;veloppement des t&eacute;moignages d&rsquo;enfants qui ont d&ucirc; composer avec des d&eacute;fis comme de voir leur puits contamin&eacute; ou de n&rsquo;avoir pas acc&egrave;s &agrave; des toilettes. Par leurs r&eacute;cits, ces enfants ne font pas que confier leur probl&egrave;me: ils racontent aussi la cr&eacute;ativit&eacute; dont a fait preuve leur collectivit&eacute; pour surmonter les d&eacute;fis et am&eacute;liorer son environnement.</p>\r\n<p>Prenez Tikho, fillette de dix ans qui vit en Zambie. En avril 2010, une enseignante de Calgary a rencontr&eacute; Tikho et lui a demand&eacute; de raconter son histoire. Avec une cam&eacute;ra num&eacute;rique, Tikho a commenc&eacute; &agrave; prendre des photos et des vid&eacute;os de sa vie quotidienne, en particulier de ce qui avait trait &agrave; l&rsquo;eau et &agrave; l&rsquo;hygi&egrave;ne. Malheureusement, la source d&rsquo;eau de sa collectivit&eacute; &eacute;tait gravement contamin&eacute;e et le village de Tikho fut appel&eacute; <em>Chipulukusu</em>, le village maudit, parce que ses habitants &eacute;taient souvent malades et mouraient de maladies d&rsquo;origine hydrique.</p>\r\n<p>Comment le village en est-il donc venu &agrave; recevoir le nom de <em>Mapolo</em>, le village b&eacute;ni? Gr&acirc;ce &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation. Quand la collectivit&eacute; de Chipulukusu eut compris d&rsquo;o&ugrave; venaient les maladies, les gens sont pass&eacute;s &agrave; l&rsquo;action: ils ont install&eacute; des robinets o&ugrave; se laver les mains et des filtres au bio-sable pour assainir leur eau. Tikho a maintenant la chance d&rsquo;avoir des toilettes &agrave; proximit&eacute;: les habitants ont appris &agrave; se servir de latrines pour contenir la contamination et r&eacute;duire la transmission des maladies.</p>\r\n<p>Une bonne fa&ccedil;on d&rsquo;engager les jeunes en lien avec les probl&egrave;mes d&rsquo;eau et d&rsquo;hygi&egrave;ne, c&rsquo;est de leur pr&eacute;senter des r&eacute;cits comme celui de Tikho. Le CAWST a observ&eacute; que lorsque des &eacute;l&egrave;ves du primaire regardent la vid&eacute;o de Tikho montrant ses amis en train de puiser de l&rsquo;eau au puits, quand ils apprennent pourquoi les gens deviennent malades et quelles d&eacute;cisions le village a prises pour avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave; une eau s&eacute;curitaire, ils se sentent pouss&eacute;s &agrave; changer leur comportement face &agrave; l&rsquo;eau. La plupart des enfants sont choqu&eacute;s par le gaspillage de l&rsquo;eau en Am&eacute;rique du Nord, en regard de ce que vit la collectivit&eacute; de Tikho. Plusieurs arr&ecirc;tent de laisser couler l&rsquo;eau quand ils se brossent les dents ou commencent &agrave; prendre des douches plus courtes. Ils se demandent aussi : que pouvons-nous faire dans notre propre collectivit&eacute; ? C&rsquo;est un pas vers la citoyennet&eacute; globale. Comme l&rsquo;explique, par exemple, une &eacute;tudiante de 9e ann&eacute;e de Calgary,</p>\r\n<p>Les gens en Zambie utilisent moins de 20 litres d&rsquo;eau par jour tandis qu&rsquo;ici, &agrave; Calgary, nous en consommons plus de 300. Cela nous am&egrave;ne &agrave; nous demander: pourrions-nous en utiliser moins? Et pourquoi ne le faisons-nous pas ?</p>\r\n<p>Quand sa classe a commenc&eacute; &agrave; examiner diff&eacute;rentes fa&ccedil;ons de conserver l&rsquo;eau, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves ont rapport&eacute; &agrave; la maison de quoi tester les toilettes qui fuient, histoire de sensibiliser les m&eacute;nages au gaspillage d&rsquo;eau &agrave; la maison. Puis, quand ils ont d&eacute;couvert que la chasse d&rsquo;eau des urinoirs &eacute;tait d&eacute;clench&eacute;e automatiquement aux six minutes, ils ont fait pression sur le conseil scolaire pour qu&rsquo;on installe des d&eacute;tecteurs afin de r&eacute;duire la consommation d&rsquo;eau.</p>\r\n<p>En passant &agrave; l&rsquo;action sur des enjeux locaux et mondiaux reli&eacute;s &agrave; l&rsquo;eau, les jeunes d&rsquo;Am&eacute;rique du Nord peuvent suivre l&rsquo;exemple de Tikho, identifier les probl&egrave;mes et chercher des solutions. Un enseignant de 9e ann&eacute;e estime que la participation &agrave; un projet d&rsquo;action a permis &agrave; ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves de comprendre qu&rsquo;il y a de l&rsquo;espoir et qu&rsquo;on peut composer avec certains probl&egrave;mes mondiaux apparemment insurmontables: &laquo; Ils sentent qu&rsquo;ils font partie de quelque chose de plus grand &ndash; et ils comprennent qu&rsquo;ils ne sont pas seuls &agrave; lutter pour am&eacute;liorer la situation. &raquo;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Que nous dit cette &eacute;tude de cas sur ce qui fait le succ&egrave;s d&rsquo;un partenariat scolaire?</li>\r\n<li>En quoi cette &eacute;tude de cas procure-t-elle certains des avantages &eacute;num&eacute;r&eacute;s ci-dessus?</li>\r\n<li>Comment chacun des partenaires a-t-il b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute; du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Quels sont les probl&egrave;mes qu&rsquo;&eacute;tudient actuellement vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves et qui pourraient se rattacher &agrave; des enjeux mondiaux? Quels sont les probl&egrave;mes auxquels s&rsquo;int&eacute;ressent vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves? Comment pourriez-vous partir de l&agrave; pour b&acirc;tir votre prochain partenariat ou votre prochain projet?</li>\r\n<li>Comment pourriez-vous inspirer une action concr&egrave;te ou un changement positif par les projets que vous lancez?</li>\r\n</ul>',' Des « récits d’espoir » poussent à l’action sur la question de l’eau','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,NULL,'Active citizenship for sustainable communities','<p>Laurel LaBar-Ahmed, a junior high school teacher in Saskatchewan, has been working on an innovative and ongoing action project that began with her 2011-2012 grade 8 Class. Entitled <em>Active Citizenship for Sustainable Communities,</em> it involves the creation of a three-part DVD series and teacher&rsquo;s manual.</p>\r\n<p>The project is directly connected to required curriculum:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It employs the interdisciplinary, inquiry-based learning approach promoted by Saskatchewan curricula. Education for sustainability explores issues that are real-life, authentic, and purposeful.</li>\r\n<li>It teaches sustainability concepts such as learning about the natural world; learning how nature sustains life; nurturing healthy communities; recognizing the implications of the ways we feed and provision ourselves; and knowing well the places where we live, work, and learn. These concepts are all contained within the language of the Ministry&rsquo;s cross-curricular competencies (thinking, identity and interdependence, literacies, and social responsibility).</li>\r\n<li>The three Broad Areas of Learning (sense of self, community, and place; lifelong learners; and engaged citizens) identified by the Saskatchewan Ministry of Education (2010) also encompass sustainability concerns.</li>\r\n<li>Grade 8 students used reading and writing skills to research sustainability issues and to write &rsquo;zine articles and stories, used technology skills to create short videos, studied water in Grade 8 Science, worked cooperatively in Art and Language Arts (English and French), practiced public speaking in Art (drama) and Language Arts, participated in outdoor activities (Physical Education), and focused on healthy living and connections to community.</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 02:50:35','2013-09-05 16:10:37',1,'large','24, 32','',NULL,'<p>Laurel LaBar-Ahmed, enseignante au premier cycle du secondaire en Saskatchewan, travaille &agrave; un projet d&rsquo;action novateur et continu qui a d&eacute;but&eacute; avec sa classe de 8e ann&eacute;e de 2011-2012. Intitul&eacute; <em>Une citoyennet&eacute; active pour des collectivit&eacute;s durables</em>, il comprend la cr&eacute;ation d&rsquo;une s&eacute;rie de DVD en trois parties et d&rsquo;un manuel de l&rsquo;enseignant-e.</p>\r\n<p>Le projet suit de pr&egrave;s le programme obligatoire:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Il applique l&rsquo;approche interdisciplinaire d&rsquo;apprentissage par investigation que pr&ocirc;nent les programmes d&rsquo;enseignement de la Saskatchewan. L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation pour un avenir viable explore des enjeux concrets, authentiques et qui d&eacute;bouchent sur un objectif.</li>\r\n<li>Il enseigne les grandes notions li&eacute;es &agrave; la durabilit&eacute;: d&eacute;couvrir le monde de la nature, apprendre comment la nature soutient la vie, cultiver des collectivit&eacute;s en sant&eacute;, reconna&icirc;tre les cons&eacute;quences de nos fa&ccedil;ons de nous alimenter et de nous &eacute;quiper, bien conna&icirc;tre les lieux o&ugrave; nous vivons, o&ugrave; nous travaillons et o&ugrave; nous &eacute;tudions. Ces notions correspondent toutes au vocabulaire des comp&eacute;tences transversales du minist&egrave;re de l&rsquo;&Eacute;ducation: la pens&eacute;e, l&rsquo;identit&eacute; et l&rsquo;interd&eacute;pendance, les litt&eacute;racies et la responsabilit&eacute; sociale.</li>\r\n<li>Les grands domaines de l&rsquo;apprentissage (sens du soi, de la collectivit&eacute; et du milieu; &eacute;ducation permanente; citoyens et citoyennes engag&eacute;s) cern&eacute;s par le minist&egrave;re de l&rsquo;&Eacute;ducation de la Saskatchewan (2010) recoupent &eacute;galement les enjeux de durabilit&eacute;.</li>\r\n<li>Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 8e ann&eacute;e ont appliqu&eacute; leurs comp&eacute;tences en lecture et en &eacute;criture pour des recherches sur la durabilit&eacute; et pour la r&eacute;daction d&rsquo;articles de fanzine, appliqu&eacute; leurs comp&eacute;tences en technologie pour cr&eacute;er de courtes vid&eacute;os, &eacute;tudi&eacute; l&rsquo;eau dans le programme de sciences de 8e ann&eacute;e, collabor&eacute; au sein du programme d&rsquo;arts et langues (anglais et fran&ccedil;ais), pratiqu&eacute; l&rsquo;art de parler en public dans les programmes d&rsquo;art (th&eacute;&acirc;tre) et d&rsquo;arts et langues, particip&eacute; &agrave; des activit&eacute;s en plein air (&eacute;ducation physique) et cultiv&eacute; des habitudes de vie saines et les liens avec la collectivit&eacute;.</li>\r\n</ul>','Une citoyenneté active pour des collectivités durables','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(20,NULL,'Food for thought: Teaching food issues in a grade 8 classroom','<p><em>Contributed by Laurel Labar-Ahmed</em></p>\r\n<p>At the start of this academic year, I was faced with the daunting task of how to actively engage 37 grade 8 Social Studies students while meeting the required curriculum outcomes and indicators. I had already begun preparations months before and knew that I wanted to begin the year by examining food-related issues from various perspectives.</p>\r\n<p>I used several current magazine and newspaper articles, relevant case studies and discussion activities to begin the unit. One excellent source of such materials is <em>Rethinking Globalization: Teaching for Justice in an Unjust World.</em> Once I had the class actively thinking about food issues, I introduced the Canadian Council for International Co-operation&rsquo;s (CCIC) 2002 &ldquo;<a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_deliberation_food_guide.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Food for Thought: Talking about What Matters in International Trade of Food</a>&rdquo; public deliberation guide.The three different approaches to food trade from the guide were discussed briefly and then I divided the class into six groups whose task was to become an expert on one of the approaches.</p>\r\n<p>Once the groups were comfortable with the pros and cons of their assigned approach, I then had two members from each group join with members of the other two groups as part of a jigsaw teaching activity. These new groups, six in total, then taught each other about the various approaches and continued to discuss the same. This part of the unit then concluded with a discussion with the entire class. At all times, students were strongly encouraged to keep an open mind and to note any unanswered questions that arose while examining the three approaches.</p>\r\n<p>Following the re-examination of food trade issues within the larger group format, the class began actively researching inquiry topics on a food related issue. Students were allowed to work alone, in partners or in groups of three. To help guide the process for exploring such issues, I provided a series of questions adapted from Manitoba&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://www.edu.gov.mb.ca/k12/cur/socstud/global_issues/inquiry_approach.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Citizenship and Sustainability Grade 12 Global Issues Pilot Course</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Without exception, the students were able to choose and find topics of personal interest. Students were highly motivated and engaged in their research projects. Various references were sourced including books, articles, relevant websites and videos, as well as personal interviews with local resource people, which was a project requirement. It is to be noted that finding people to interview can sometimes be challenging, but well worth the effort. Students then had to present their findings orally and in writing.</p>\r\n<p>Concurrently with the above, I also involved the students in Regina&rsquo;s fall &ldquo;Field to Fork Festival,&rdquo; a screening of the food documentary &ldquo;Hijacked Future&rdquo; at the University of Regina, and an &ldquo;Organic Connections&rdquo; youth conference on food issues. All three of these outings were made possible via the supportive community network that I have carefully nurtured over the years. Such support is vital to the success of the global education classes that I teach. Moreover, it provides additional perspectives on pertinent issues and helps foster critical thinking skills.</p>\r\n<p>Last, but not least, I ensured that my class experienced an Action Project component, which in this case was our Food for Thought Youth Conference. We partnered with the Saskatchewan Council for International Co-operation (SCIC) for conference ideas and facilitation support, which was a great way to seed the conference. After that, the overall conference was planned by members of our class and included such things as the lunch preparation, giving and planning some of the workshops, booking all needed venues and equipment, contacting and working with the media, and much more. Two of the grade 8s coordinated everything, and there were many different subcommittees and jobs, which kept all students involved in some form or another. One drawback from such deep involvement meant that grade 8 students parachuted in and out of workshops and other aspects of the conference, as they were needed elsewhere; nonetheless, everyone agreed that the conference was a great success and experience.</p>\r\n<p>In terms of assessment, I cannot stress enough that it needs to be ongoing. I used the following format:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Inquiry Process</strong> (Jigsaw activities, discussions, topic selection and questions generated, peer and self assessments) <strong>25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Final Products</strong> (Oral presentations, written research projects) <strong>25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Critical Understanding Tasks</strong> (Thesis statements, comparative analysis, responses to teacher-generated questions, etc.)<strong> 25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Action Project Component</strong> (Planning of Food for Thought Conference, implementation, peer and self assessments, community and participant evaluations, etc.) <strong>25%</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>For further assessment ideas, I would highly recommend reading Manitoba&rsquo;s &ldquo;Grade 12 Global Issues: Citizenship and Sustainability Suggested Assessment and Evaluation Model&rdquo; which is <a href=\"http://www.edu.gov.mb.ca/k12/cur/socstud/global_issues/assessment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">currently in draft form</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection Questions</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Why do you think this project was so successful? What elements contributed to that?</li>\r\n<li>Is it possible to get the local community involved in projects that you might undertake? Is that important?</li>\r\n<li>What might be some of the longer-term learning effects this Food for Thought project had on students?</li>\r\n<li>How did all of the participants involved benefit from this project?</li>\r\n<li>Do you think this project was a good example of global citizenship education, even though it did not involve partners from overseas? Why or why not?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 03:04:17','2013-09-05 16:23:15',1,'large','','',NULL,'<p><em>Texte produit par Laurel Labar-Ahmed</em></p>\r\n<p>Au d&eacute;but de l&rsquo;ann&eacute;e scolaire, j&rsquo;avais le d&eacute;fi d&rsquo;engager activement 37 &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 8e ann&eacute;e en &eacute;tudes sociales tout en satisfaisant aux r&eacute;sultats et aux indicateurs du programme. J&rsquo;avais commenc&eacute; &agrave; me pr&eacute;parer plusieurs mois auparavant et je savais que je voulais commencer l&rsquo;ann&eacute;e en abordant de diff&eacute;rents points de vue les enjeux li&eacute;s &agrave; l&rsquo;alimentation.</p>\r\n<p>Pour commencer le cours, j&rsquo;ai utilis&eacute; plusieurs articles r&eacute;cents de magazines et de journaux, des &eacute;tudes de cas pertinentes et des activit&eacute;s de discussion. J&rsquo;ai trouv&eacute; une bonne source documentaire dans <em>Rethinking Globalization: Teaching for Justice in an Unjust World</em>. Une fois la classe engag&eacute;e dans une r&eacute;flexion sur les questions de justice alimentaire, j&rsquo;ai pr&eacute;sent&eacute; un texte publi&eacute; en 2002 par le Conseil canadien de coop&eacute;ration internationale (CCCI) &laquo; Pour alimenter la r&eacute;flexion : Parler de ce qui importe en mati&egrave;re de commerce international des aliments &raquo;, qui est un guide pour les d&eacute;lib&eacute;rations publiques.Nous avons regard&eacute; bri&egrave;vement les trois approches qu&rsquo;utilise ce guide pour analyser le commerce des aliments, apr&egrave;s quoi j&rsquo;ai divis&eacute; la classe en six groupes qui devaient devenir des experts sur l&rsquo;une de ces approches.</p>\r\n<p>Une fois que les groupes eurent apprivois&eacute; les arguments pour et contre de leur approche, j&rsquo;ai demand&eacute; &agrave; deux membres par groupe de se joindre &agrave; des membres des deux autres groupes dans le cadre d&rsquo;une activit&eacute; d&rsquo;apprentissage crois&eacute;. Ces nouvelles &eacute;quipes, six en tout, se sont expliqu&eacute; les diff&eacute;rentes approches et ont poursuivi la discussion. Cette &eacute;tape s&rsquo;est conclue par une discussion avec toute la classe. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves &eacute;taient r&eacute;guli&egrave;rement invit&eacute;s &agrave; garder un esprit ouvert et &agrave; noter les questions qui leur venaient en &eacute;tudiant les trois approches.</p>\r\n<p>Apr&egrave;s l&rsquo;examen en pl&eacute;ni&egrave;re des probl&egrave;mes relatifs au commerce des aliments, la classe s&rsquo;est mise &agrave; creuser des sujets d&rsquo;enqu&ecirc;te sur les enjeux alimentaires. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves pouvaient travailler seuls, avec un-e partenaire ou en groupe de trois. Pour les aider dans leur d&eacute;marche, je leur ai fourni une s&eacute;rie de questions adapt&eacute;es d&rsquo;un projet pilote manitobain, le <a href=\"http://www.edu.gov.mb.ca/k12/cur/socstud/global_issues/inquiry_approach.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Citizenship and ustainability Grade 12 Global Issues Pilot Course</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Tous les &eacute;l&egrave;ves sans exception ont pu trouver un sujet qui les int&eacute;ressait personnellement. Toutes et tous se sont montr&eacute;s tr&egrave;s motiv&eacute;s et tr&egrave;s engag&eacute;s dans leur projet de recherche. Diff&eacute;rentes r&eacute;f&eacute;rences ont &eacute;t&eacute; mises &agrave; contribution: livres, articles, sites Web et vid&eacute;os pertinentes, ainsi que des entrevues personnelles avec des personnes ressources de l&rsquo;endroit, ce qui &eacute;tait une exigence du projet. On notera qu&rsquo;il peut parfois &ecirc;tre difficile de trouver des personnes &agrave; interviewer, mais &ccedil;a vaut le coup. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves devaient ensuite pr&eacute;senter leurs travaux oralement et par &eacute;crit.</p>\r\n<p>Parall&egrave;lement, j&rsquo;ai fait participer mes &eacute;l&egrave;ves au festival d&rsquo;automne <em>&laquo; Field to Fork &raquo;</em> de Regina, au visionnement du documentaire<em> &laquo; Hijacked Future &raquo;</em> sur l&rsquo;alimentation, pr&eacute;sent&eacute; &agrave; l&rsquo;Universit&eacute; de Regina, et au congr&egrave;s-jeunesse <em>&laquo; Organic Connections &raquo;</em> sur les enjeux alimentaires. Ces trois sorties ont &eacute;t&eacute; rendues possibles par le r&eacute;seau de soutien que j&rsquo;ai pu b&acirc;tir avec les ann&eacute;es au sein de la collectivit&eacute;. Un tel appui est essentiel &agrave; la r&eacute;ussite des classes d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation plan&eacute;taire que je donne. En outre, il apporte d&rsquo;autres points de vue sur les probl&egrave;mes &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tude et aide &agrave; cultiver la pens&eacute;e critique.</p>\r\n<p>Un dernier point, mais non le moindre, c&rsquo;est que j&rsquo;ai veill&eacute; &agrave; ce que ma classe vive une composante d&rsquo;action, en l&rsquo;occurrence, notre congr&egrave;s jeunesse &laquo; Pour alimenter la r&eacute;flexion &raquo;. Nous avons travaill&eacute; en partenariat avec <em>le Saskatchewan Council for International Co-operation</em> (SCIC) pour la conception et l&rsquo;animation du congr&egrave;s, ce qui a permis de bien penser l&rsquo;&eacute;v&eacute;nement. Apr&egrave;s quoi, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves ont planifi&eacute; le congr&egrave;s et vu &agrave; la pr&eacute;paration du repas de midi, donn&eacute; ou planifi&eacute; certains des ateliers, r&eacute;serv&eacute; les locaux et l&rsquo;&eacute;quipement, pris contact avec les m&eacute;dias, et fait bien d&rsquo;autres choses encore. Deux &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 8e ann&eacute;e ont vu &agrave; la coordination de l&rsquo;ensemble, et il y avait nombre de sous-comit&eacute;s et de mandats, ce qui a permis d&rsquo;impliquer tous les &eacute;l&egrave;ves. Un inconv&eacute;nient d&rsquo;une participation aussi intense, c&rsquo;est que des &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 8e ann&eacute;e se voyaient parachut&eacute;s d&rsquo;un atelier ou d&rsquo;une t&acirc;che &agrave; l&rsquo;autre pour r&eacute;pondre aux besoins. N&eacute;anmoins, tout le monde a &eacute;t&eacute; d&rsquo;accord pour dire que le congr&egrave;s avait &eacute;t&eacute; une r&eacute;ussite et une exp&eacute;rience formidable.</p>\r\n<p>Si on pense &eacute;valuation, je ne saurais trop souligner qu&rsquo;elle doit &ecirc;tre permanente. J&rsquo;ai eu recours &agrave; la grille que voici:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Processus d&rsquo;enqu&ecirc;te</strong> (apprentissage crois&eacute;, discussion, choix des sujets et questions provoqu&eacute;es, auto&eacute;valuation et &eacute;valuation par les pairs)<strong> 25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Produit final</strong> (pr&eacute;sentations orales, travaux &eacute;crits) <strong>25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>T&acirc;ches d&rsquo;analyse critique</strong> (&eacute;nonc&eacute; des th&egrave;ses, analyse comparative, r&eacute;ponses aux questions venant de l&rsquo;enseignante, etc.) <strong>25%</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Volet du projet d&rsquo;action</strong> (Planification du congr&egrave;s &laquo; Pour alimenter la r&eacute;flexion &raquo;, mise en &oelig;uvre, auto&eacute;valuation et &eacute;valuation par les pairs, &eacute;valuation par la collectivit&eacute; et les participant-e-s, etc.)<strong> 25%</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Pour d&rsquo;autres id&eacute;es sur l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation, je recommande fortement de lire le manuel manitobain &laquo; <em>Grade 12 Global Issues: Citizenship and Sustainability Suggested Assessment and Evaluation Model</em> &raquo;,<a href=\"http://www.edu.gov.mb.ca/k12/cur/socstud/global_issues/assessment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">actuellement &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tat d&rsquo;&eacute;bauche</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pourquoi pensez-vous que ce projet a eu autant de succ&egrave;s? Quels sont les &eacute;l&eacute;ments qui ont contribu&eacute; &agrave; sa r&eacute;ussite?</li>\r\n<li>Serait-il possible de faire participer votre collectivit&eacute; &agrave; des projets que vous lanceriez? Est-ce important?</li>\r\n<li>Pour les &eacute;l&egrave;ves, quels seraient certains des apprentissages &agrave; long terme du projet &laquo; Pour alimenter la r&eacute;flexion &raquo;?</li>\r\n<li>Comment les personnes qui ont particip&eacute; &agrave; ce projet en ont-elles toutes b&eacute;n&eacute;fici&eacute;?</li>\r\n<li>Pensez-vous que ce projet soit un bon exemple d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, m&ecirc;me s&rsquo;il ne faisait pas appel &agrave; des partenaires de l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger? Pourquoi?</li>\r\n</ul>','«Pour alimenter la réflexion »: les problèmes alimentaires dans une classe de 8e année','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(21,NULL,'Human Rights Day (a student’s perspective)','<p>This year at St. James elementary/junior high, the grade 9 Global Leadership class held our very own Human Rights Day. The Global Leadership class worked extremely hard, and everyone dedicated their time to making this day a success. After three months of planning and organizing, it was game time.</p>\r\n<p>Every student voluntarily arrived at school several hours early to make sure we were one hundred percent prepared. A few hours later, fourteen schools were with us in person, and five more schools participated virtually. Schools from Mali, Jamaica, and Grenada created their own videos to show the different ways water was used in their country and how they value it in their culture. With 500 students there in person, our knowledge on human rights and on water was tested. Our class showed excellence through this project, and knew what they were doing. Of course we all made mistakes but easily improvised to solve any problems that came up.</p>\r\n<p>We had 15 different presenters throughout the school from many different organizations, including CAWST, United Nations Association of Canada, our own Mr. Robinson, and many more. At the start of the day each visitor received a coupon telling them which country they represented. Based on this coupon, they would receive, zero, one or two cookies. Some kids got no cookies at all. They were to come up with a solution to this crisis. If the two-cookie people gave the zero-cookie people one of their cookies, we would all be equal.</p>\r\n<p>Along with the cookies were also water privileges. There were several water jugs set up in different areas around the school, and based on your &ldquo;country&rdquo; you would have to go to certain jugs for your water. As an example, if you were from a poor country, you would need to walk all the way down the hall to get a small cup of water while two-cookie people could fill up their large cups at any of the water fountains in the school. This was to represent the distances people in developing countries walk to get water for their families.</p>\r\n<p>The day turned out to be a huge success, and everyone left the building with stronger knowledge on human rights.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 03:09:15','2013-09-05 16:23:30',1,'wide','','',NULL,'<p>Cette ann&eacute;e &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole St. James (primaire et premier cycle du secondaire), la classe de leadership mondial de 9e ann&eacute;e a organis&eacute; sa propre Journ&eacute;e des droits de la personne. La classe a travaill&eacute; tr&egrave;s fort et tout le monde a donn&eacute; de son temps pour assurer le succ&egrave;s de la journ&eacute;e. Au terme de trois mois de planification et d&rsquo;organisation, ce fut toute une journ&eacute;e.</p>\r\n<p>Chaque &eacute;l&egrave;ve a accept&eacute; d&rsquo;arriver &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole plusieurs heures plus t&ocirc;t pour que tout soit pr&ecirc;t &agrave; cent pour cent. Quelques heures plus tard, quatorze &eacute;coles venaient nous rejoindre en personne, et cinq autres participaient de mani&egrave;re virtuelle. Des &eacute;coles du Mali, de la Jama&iuml;que et de la Grenade ont cr&eacute;&eacute; leur propre vid&eacute;o pour illustrer de quelle fa&ccedil;on l&rsquo;eau &eacute;tait utilis&eacute;e dans leur pays et la valeur qu&rsquo;on lui attribue dans leur culture. Avec 500 &eacute;l&egrave;ves sur place, nous avons pu mettre &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;preuve nos connaissances sur l&rsquo;eau et les droits de la personne. Notre classe a fait preuve d&rsquo;excellence dans la r&eacute;alisation de ce projet : nous savions ce que nous faisions. Bien s&ucirc;r, nous avons fait des erreurs, mais nous avons su improviser pour trouver une solution aux probl&egrave;mes qui ont surgi.</p>\r\n<p>Nous avions &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole 15 conf&eacute;renci&egrave;res et conf&eacute;renciers de diff&eacute;rentes organisations, dont le <em>Centre for Affordable Water and Satitation Technology</em> (CAWST), l&rsquo;Association canadienne pour les Nations Unies, notre propre M. Robinson, et plusieurs autres. Au d&eacute;but de la journ&eacute;e, chaque visiteuse ou visiteur recevait un coupon l&rsquo;avisant du pays qu&rsquo;elle ou il repr&eacute;sentait. Ce coupon d&eacute;cidait du nombre de biscuits qu&rsquo;elle ou il allait recevoir : z&eacute;ro, un ou deux. Certains n&rsquo;en ont re&ccedil;u aucun. Il fallait trouver une solution &agrave; la crise. Si ceux et celles qui avaient deux biscuits acceptaient d&rsquo;en donner un &agrave; ceux et celles qui n&rsquo;en avaient pas, tout le monde serait sur le m&ecirc;me pied.</p>\r\n<p>En plus des biscuits, il y avait des privil&egrave;ges pour l&rsquo;eau. Diff&eacute;rentes fontaines &eacute;taient install&eacute;es &agrave; diff&eacute;rents endroits de l&rsquo;&eacute;cole et, en fonction de votre &laquo; pays &raquo;, vous deviez vous rendre &agrave; certaines fontaines. Par exemple, si vous veniez d&rsquo;un pays pauvre, vous deviez vous rendre &agrave; l&rsquo;autre bout du corridor pour recevoir une petite tasse d&rsquo;eau tandis que les d&eacute;tenteurs de deux biscuits pouvaient remplir leur grande tasse &agrave; l&rsquo;une des fontaines de l&rsquo;&eacute;cole. Ceci pour repr&eacute;senter la distance que doivent franchir les gens de pays en d&eacute;veloppement pour fournir leur famille en eau.</p>\r\n<p>La journ&eacute;e s&rsquo;est av&eacute;r&eacute;e un grand succ&egrave;s, et tout le monde en est reparti mieux inform&eacute; des droits de la personne.</p>','La Journée des droits de la personne (point de vue d’un-e élève)','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,NULL,'School twinning between Calgary and Grenada','<p><em>Contributed by the Alberta Council for Global Cooperation</em></p>\r\n<p>Bill Robinson is one of those fearless and motivated teachers who actively pursues education for global citizenship in his teaching. A teacher at St. James in Calgary, Bill is dedicated to sharing his knowledge, questions and reflections surrounding global citizenship with his students on a daily basis.</p>\r\n<p>One of the projects Bill&rsquo;s class is currently working on is a twinning project with a school in Grenada. As Bill works with a teacher in Grenada who teaches a class similar to his Global Leadership option in Calgary, they are creating a cultural exchange where their students will learn from each other. Students in Grenada will share information about coastal and coral reef erosion (as well as information about the island as a whole), while students at St. James will share information about watersheds (and Alberta and Canada). Eventually, the goal over the next two years will be to learn a great deal about and from each other through video conferencing and mutually developed wikis.</p>\r\n<p>The second stage to the project will be to identify ways in which students can help and empower each other. Bill&rsquo;s Global Leadership Class looks forward to working with their new partners in Grenada to improve their lives with support. The first idea will be for Bill&rsquo;s class to do a book drive to help improve the selection the Grenada students currently have in their library.</p>\r\n<p>This project is being carried out in conjunction with the Canadian International Development Agency, which has provided a grant to facilitate the project. By building this connection with people in another country, Bill hopes to foster improved understanding of life in Grenada: &ldquo;they don\'t need our charity, rather they need our assistance to foster opportunity.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Bill encourages his students to remain active in international development by motivating them to become involved in global issues that are important to them. He provides them the opportunity to take this knowledge and translate it into real action through volunteering for different organizations across Alberta. Bill&rsquo;s students are reminded daily to think about what it means to be a global citizen.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection questions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How does this twinning project go beyond just providing financial resources?</li>\r\n<li>How did the students at St. James benefit from this project? How did the students from Grenada benefit from this project?</li>\r\n<li>Why is it important that the students in Grenada learn about Albertan issues?</li>\r\n<li>How does the approach and execution of this project align with the principles of good practice outlined in this guide?</li>\r\n<li>What are some other ways that St. James and Grenada might mutually support one another in their learning and in this project?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-04 03:13:12','2013-09-05 16:23:45',1,'tall','','',NULL,'<p><em>Texte produit par l&rsquo;Alberta Council for Global Cooperation</em></p>\r\n<p>Bill Robinson est l&rsquo;un de ces enseignants courageux et motiv&eacute;s qui, dans son enseignement, cultive l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale. &Agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole St. James de Calgary, Bill s&rsquo;emploie chaque jour &agrave; partager &agrave; ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves ses connaissances, ses questions et ses r&eacute;flexions sur la citoyennet&eacute; plan&eacute;taire.</p>\r\n<p>Un des projets auxquels travaille pr&eacute;sentement la classe de Bill, c&rsquo;est un jumelage avec une &eacute;cole en Grenade. Bill travaille avec un enseignant en Grenade qui donne un cours analogue &agrave; son cours optionnel de leadership global &agrave; Calgary, et ils ont d&eacute;velopp&eacute; un &eacute;change culturel qui permet &agrave; leurs &eacute;l&egrave;ves d&rsquo;apprendre les uns des autres. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves grenadiens vont parler de l&rsquo;&eacute;rosion du littoral et du r&eacute;cif de corail (et &eacute;galement de leur &icirc;le dans son ensemble) alors que les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de St. James vont traiter des bassins versants (et de l&rsquo;Alberta et du Canada). L&rsquo;objectif, sur deux ans, s&rsquo;est d&rsquo;en apprendre beaucoup les uns des autres et les uns sur les autres &agrave; coups de visioconf&eacute;rences et de wikis d&eacute;velopp&eacute;s conjointement.</p>\r\n<p>La deuxi&egrave;me &eacute;tape du projet consistera &agrave; identifier des fa&ccedil;ons pour les &eacute;l&egrave;ves d&rsquo;acc&eacute;der &agrave; plus d&rsquo;autonomie, mais en s&rsquo;entraidant. La classe de leadership global de Bill compte travailler avec ses nouveaux partenaires de Grenade pour am&eacute;liorer leur vie en leur offrant son appui. Une premi&egrave;re &eacute;tape sera de ramasser des livres pour enrichir la biblioth&egrave;que que les &eacute;l&egrave;ves grenadiens ont &agrave; leur disposition.</p>\r\n<p>Ce projet est r&eacute;alis&eacute; avec l&rsquo;Agence canadienne de d&eacute;veloppement international, qui a accord&eacute; une subvention pour faciliter le projet. En nouant des liens avec des gens d&rsquo;un autre pays, Bill esp&egrave;re favoriser une meilleure compr&eacute;hension de la vie en Grenade: &laquo; ils n&rsquo;ont pas besoin de notre charit&eacute;, mais plut&ocirc;t de notre aide pour augmenter leurs chances &raquo;.</p>\r\n<p>Bill encourage ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; rester activement engag&eacute;s en d&eacute;veloppement international et il les incite &agrave; s&rsquo;impliquer sur des enjeux mondiaux importants pour eux et pour elles. Il leur donne l&rsquo;occasion de s&rsquo;informer et de transformer ces connaissances en gestes concrets en faisant du travail b&eacute;n&eacute;vole pour diverses organisations de l&rsquo;Alberta. Chaque jour, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de Bill se font rappeler de penser &agrave; ce que cela signifie d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre une citoyenne ou un citoyen du monde.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Comment ce projet de jumelage d&eacute;passe-t-il le simple octroi de ressources financi&egrave;res?</li>\r\n<li>En quoi les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de St James profitent-ils de ce projet? En quoi les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de la Grenade profitent-ils de ce projet?</li>\r\n<li>Pourquoi est-il important que les &eacute;l&egrave;ves grenadiens apprennent les probl&egrave;mes qui se posent en Alberta?</li>\r\n<li>Comment l&rsquo;approche et la r&eacute;alisation de ce projet correspondent-elles aux principes de bonne pratique d&eacute;crits dans le pr&eacute;sent guide?</li>\r\n<li>Y aurait-il d&rsquo;autres fa&ccedil;ons pour St James et de la Grenade de s&rsquo;appuyer mutuellement dans l&rsquo;apprentissage et dans la mise en &oelig;uvre de ce projet?</li>\r\n</ul>','Jumelage scolaire entre Calgary et la Grenade','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,NULL,'Global citizenship education in context','<p>In a fast-changing and globalized reality, there are many who believe that education can, and should, help young people to meet the challenges they will confront now and in the future, and that educating for global citizenship is now more important and urgent than ever before. Upon reflection back over this decade of work, however, there is an indication that not a lot of progress has been made in expanding education for global citizenship (Schulz, 2007; Canadian Council for International Cooperation, 2004).</p>\r\n<p>In the early 1990s, with the financial assistance of the Canadian International Development Agency and inspired by visions of global solidarity, Canadian schools and community organizations joined together in efforts to educate students on global society, though since then funding has been cut drastically, and coordinated efforts across sectors have decreased, as schools and NGOs face their own budget cuts.</p>\r\n<p>In a recent poll conducted by VisionCritical and the Inter-Council Network of Provincial and Regional Councils for Global Cooperation, it was found that one third of Canadians rank global poverty (hunger in the world) among the first, second and third most concerning issues to them globally. Moreover, the majority of Canadians believe there is a human rights obligation to reduce global poverty, and believe there are significant benefits to doing so, including improving Canada&rsquo;s international reputation, reducing global conflict, and reducing risks of pandemics.</p>\r\n<p>Global Citizenship Education is essential for the following reasons:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Education for Global Citizenship gives young people access to the knowledge, understanding, skills, and values that they need to participate fully in ensuring their own and others&rsquo; well-being, and to make a positive contribution both locally and globally.</li>\r\n<li>Global Citizenship Education involves children and youth fully in their own learning through the use of a range of activities and participatory learning methods. This engages the learner, but also develops confidence, self-esteem, and skills of critical thinking, communication, cooperation and conflict resolution.</li>\r\n<li>Current use of the world&rsquo;s resources is inequitable and unsustainable. As the gap between the rich and the poor widens, poverty continues to deny millions of people around the world their basic human rights. Education is a powerful tool for changing the world because tomorrow&rsquo;s adults are the children and youth we are educating today.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>For teachers interested in promoting global citizenship, the next and most immediate question is<em> how</em>: How can I integrate and teach global citizenship education when I have so many other pressing curriculum requirements to get through with my students? How does Global Citizenship Education relate to English Language Arts or Physical Education? This toolkit seeks to provide information on how global citizenship education can be integrated into many areas of the curriculum, offer some tools and methods by which to do so, and present some illustrative case studies to provide inspiration and guidance.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Education for Global Citizenship is....</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Asking questions and developing critical thinking skills</li>\r\n<li>Equipping young people with knowledge, skills and values to participate as active citizens</li>\r\n<li>Acknowledging the complexity of global issues</li>\r\n<li>Revealing the global as part of everyday life, whether in a small village or a large city</li>\r\n<li>Understanding how we relate to the environment and to each other as human beings.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Education for Global Citizenship is not...</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Too difficult for young children to understand</li>\r\n<li>Mostly or all about other places and peoples</li>\r\n<li>Telling people what to think and do</li>\r\n<li>Providing simple solutions to complex issues</li>\r\n<li>An extra subject to cram into a crowded curriculum</li>\r\n<li>About raising money for charity.</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-04 03:23:53','2013-09-05 16:24:25',1,'tall','18,20,21,22','',NULL,'<p>Dans un contexte mondialis&eacute; et qui &eacute;volue rapidement, bien des gens estiment que l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation peut et doit aider les jeunes &agrave; relever les d&eacute;fis qu&rsquo;ils doivent et devront affronter, et que l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; une citoyennet&eacute; plan&eacute;taire est aujourd&rsquo;hui plus importante et plus urgente que jamais. Mais si on fait le point sur dix ann&eacute;es de travail, il semble qu&rsquo;on ne soit pas encore parvenu &agrave; diffuser l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; plan&eacute;taire (Schulz, 2007; Conseil canadien pour la coop&eacute;ration internationale, 2004).</p>\r\n<p>Au d&eacute;but des ann&eacute;es 1990, avec l&rsquo;aide financi&egrave;re de l&rsquo;Agence canadienne de d&eacute;veloppement international et inspir&eacute;es par des perspectives de solidarit&eacute; mondiale, des &eacute;coles et des organisations communautaires canadiennes ont uni leurs efforts pour sensibiliser des &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; la soci&eacute;t&eacute; mondiale, mais depuis lors les subventions ont subi de lourdes compressions et les efforts intersectoriels ont diminu&eacute; puisque les &eacute;coles et les ONG ont d&ucirc; composer avec leurs propres restrictions budg&eacute;taires.</p>\r\n<p>Un sondage effectu&eacute; r&eacute;cemment par VisionCritical et le R&eacute;seau de coordination des conseils provinciaux et r&eacute;gionaux de coop&eacute;ration internationale a r&eacute;v&eacute;l&eacute; que le tiers des Canadiennes et des Canadiens rangent la pauvret&eacute; mondiale (la faim dans le monde) parmi l&rsquo;un des trois probl&egrave;mes qui les inqui&egrave;tent le plus. Par ailleurs, la majorit&eacute; des Canadiennes et des Canadiens estiment que le respect des droits de la personne nous oblige &agrave; r&eacute;duire la pauvret&eacute; mondiale et qu&rsquo;il y a de grands avantages &agrave; le faire tant pour am&eacute;liorer la r&eacute;putation du Canada sur le plan international que pour r&eacute;duire le risque de pand&eacute;mie ou de conflit plan&eacute;taire.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale est essentielle pour les raisons suivantes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale donne aux jeunes les connaissances, la compr&eacute;hension, les comp&eacute;tences et les valeurs qu&rsquo;il leur faut pour contribuer pleinement &agrave; leur propre bien-&ecirc;tre et &agrave; celui des autres et pour am&eacute;liorer la situation tant sur le plan local qu&rsquo;&agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle mondiale.</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale engage pleinement les enfants et les jeunes dans leur propre formation gr&acirc;ce &agrave; tout un &eacute;ventail d&rsquo;activit&eacute;s et de m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;apprentissage fond&eacute;es sur la participation. Elle engage l&rsquo;apprenant-e, mais d&eacute;veloppe &eacute;galement la confiance, l&rsquo;estime de soi, et la pens&eacute;e critique ainsi que l&rsquo;art de la communication, de la coop&eacute;ration et du r&egrave;glement des diff&eacute;rends.</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;utilisation faite actuellement des ressources mondiales est in&eacute;quitable et n\'est pas viable. &Agrave; mesure que se creuse le foss&eacute; entre riches et pauvres, la mis&egrave;re continue de violer les droits fondamentaux de millions de personnes dans le monde. L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation est un outil puissant pour changer le monde parce que les adultes de demain sont les enfants et les jeunes que nous &eacute;duquons aujourd&rsquo;hui.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Pour les enseignantes et les enseignants int&eacute;ress&eacute;s &agrave; promouvoir la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, la question qui se pose tout de suite est celle du <em>comment</em>: comment vais-je pouvoir int&eacute;grer &agrave; mon enseignement l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale alors que le programme m&rsquo;impose d&eacute;j&agrave; tant de mati&egrave;re et de contraintes? Comment faire le lien entre l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale et l&rsquo;enseignement du fran&ccedil;ais ou de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation physique? Notre bo&icirc;te &agrave; outils cherche &agrave; expliquer comment int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale &agrave; plusieurs domaines du programme, propose des outils et des m&eacute;thodes pour le faire et illustre le tout par des &eacute;tudes de cas susceptibles de vous inspirer et de vous orienter.</p>\r\n<p><strong>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, c&rsquo;est....</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Poser des questions et cultiver la pens&eacute;e critique</li>\r\n<li>Fournir aux jeunes les connaissances, les comp&eacute;tences et les valeurs qui feront d&rsquo;eux des citoyennes et des citoyens actifs et engag&eacute;s</li>\r\n<li>Reconna&icirc;tre la complexit&eacute; des enjeux mondiaux</li>\r\n<li>Montrer que les enjeux mondiaux font partie de notre quotidien, et ce, que nous habitions un petit village ou une grande ville</li>\r\n<li>Comprendre notre rapport &agrave; l&rsquo;environnement et aux autres &ecirc;tres humains.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, ce n&rsquo;est pas...</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Trop difficile pour que de jeunes enfants puissent comprendre</li>\r\n<li>Se m&ecirc;ler de ce qui se passe ailleurs et qui concerne les autres</li>\r\n<li>Dire aux gens ce qu&rsquo;ils doivent penser et ce qu&rsquo;ils doivent faire</li>\r\n<li>Proposer des solutions simples &agrave; des probl&egrave;mes complexes</li>\r\n<li>Une mati&egrave;re de plus &agrave; faire entrer dans un programme d&eacute;j&agrave; charg&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Ramasser de l&rsquo;argent pour des &oelig;uvres de bienfaisance.</li>\r\n</ul>','L’éducation à la citoyenneté globale mise en contexte','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Ben Walker','Ben Walker',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,NULL,'Incorporate global citizenship education everywhere','<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;With my Grade 1 students I have tried to create opportunities to engage reflexively by focusing on themes of identity, difference, power, and relationship. I use a great deal of critical multicultural children&rsquo;s literature to initiate discussion on these themes, and I emphasize the informal curriculum in terms of intervening in the ways that students relate to one another as primary learning material for engaging these themes.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Dr. Angela MacDonald, Ontario Teacher</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Integrating Global Citizenship Education into curriculum requires thoughtful planning and networking. In order to keep it fresh and effective, I have to be very open to learning alongside my students. I bring in as many voices as possible so that different points of view can be heard and considered. Many of these voices come from the non-profit sector in the community.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Laurel Labar-Ahmed, Saskatchewan teacher</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>The scope of global citizenship education is wider than a single scheme of work or subject. It is more than simply looking at social issues in World Issues, or teaching about some distant locality in Geography, or sending school kits to a small village in Mozambique. It is relevant to all areas of the curriculum, all abilities, all age ranges. It can be introduced at any point in a teaching career, from pre-service training to near retirement. There is no pre-set method on how you should teach it.</p>\r\n<p>Education for global citizenship encourages children and young people to explore, develop, and express their own values and opinions, while listening to others&rsquo; points of view. It uses participatory teaching and learning methodologies that are well established as best practice in education. In an ideal world, global citizenship education would encompass the work of the whole school because it is a perspective on the world shared within an institution; it can manifest not only in what is taught in the classroom, but in everything the school does.</p>\r\n<p>The outcomes of good global citizenship education, in terms of the knowledge, skills and attitudes conveyed, can be described as follows:</p>\r\n<p><img id=\"docs-internal-guid-10f5a4d9-e702-aaaf-fc08-037d552ca9bb\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/2SLjAfdPMgU294JKNwwXx58mkW4sFPL9wChuQqd3jytT4iaNqg77EVoktuzbctDy-ImKt15A_kcMwA-9n5m63lmxK2RKxeRjkiehVIK9TGs3uXinLg2WuPpf\" alt=\"\" width=\"631px;\" height=\"347px;\" /></p>','',0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-04 03:39:15','2013-09-05 16:22:20',1,'wide','','',NULL,'<blockquote>\r\n<p>&laquo; Avec mes &eacute;l&egrave;ves de 1re ann&eacute;e, j&rsquo;ai essay&eacute; de cr&eacute;er des occasions de r&eacute;flexion en abordant les th&egrave;mes de l&rsquo;identit&eacute;, de la diff&eacute;rence, du pouvoir et des relations. Je recours abondamment &agrave; de la litt&eacute;rature pour enfants multiculturelle et critique pour amorcer la discussion sur ces th&egrave;mes, et je tire parti du programme d&rsquo;enseignement informel en partant des interactions entre les &eacute;l&egrave;ves : les rapports entre eux deviennent le mat&eacute;riel p&eacute;dagogique dont je me sers pour aborder ces questions. &raquo;</p>\r\n<p><em>&ndash;Dre Angela MacDonald, enseignante en Ontario</em></p>\r\n<p>&laquo; Pour int&eacute;grer au programme l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, il faut une planification minutieuse et un bon r&eacute;seau. Pour que la question conserve sa fra&icirc;cheur et son attrait, je dois &ecirc;tre dispos&eacute;e &agrave; apprendre avec mes &eacute;l&egrave;ves. Je fais intervenir le plus de personnes ressources possible afin qu&rsquo;on puisse entendre et prendre en compte diff&eacute;rents points de vue. Plusieurs de ces personnes proviennent du secteur &agrave; but non lucratif. &raquo;</p>\r\n<p><em>&ndash;Laurel Labar-Ahmed, enseignante en Saskatchewan</em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale a une port&eacute;e qui d&eacute;borde un travail ou un sujet. Elle ne consiste pas seulement &agrave; regarder la dimension sociale des probl&egrave;mes mondiaux, &agrave; faire d&eacute;couvrir la g&eacute;ographie de pays &eacute;loign&eacute;s, ou &agrave; envoyer du mat&eacute;riel scolaire dans un village du Mozambique. Elle concerne tous les secteurs du programme, toutes les comp&eacute;tences et tous les &acirc;ges. On peut l&rsquo;inclure &agrave; n&rsquo;importe quelle &eacute;tape d&rsquo;une carri&egrave;re d&rsquo;enseignement, qu&rsquo;on soit stagiaire ou &agrave; la veille de la retraite. Il n&rsquo;y a pas de m&eacute;thode pr&eacute;&eacute;tablie pour l&rsquo;enseigner.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale invite les enfants et les jeunes &agrave; explorer, &agrave; d&eacute;velopper et &agrave; exprimer leurs propres valeurs et leurs propres opinions tout en &eacute;tant &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;coute du point de vue des autres. Elle applique des m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;enseignement et d&rsquo;apprentissage participatives, qui sont des pratiques reconnues en p&eacute;dagogie. Id&eacute;alement, l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale embrasserait tout ce qui se fait &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole, car il s&rsquo;agit d&rsquo;une fa&ccedil;on de voir le monde largement partag&eacute;e au sein d&rsquo;un &eacute;tablissement ; elle peut s&rsquo;exprimer non seulement dans ce qui est enseign&eacute; en classe, mais dans tout ce qui se fait &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole.</p>\r\n<p>On peut d&eacute;crire comme suit les r&eacute;sultats de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale en termes de connaissances, de comp&eacute;tences et d&rsquo;attitudes transmises:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Connaissances et compr&eacute;hension</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Justice sociale et &eacute;quit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Mondialisation et interd&eacute;pendance</li>\r\n<li>D&eacute;veloppement durable</li>\r\n<li>Paix et conflit</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Comp&eacute;tences</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pens&eacute;e critique</li>\r\n<li>Savoir discuter de mani&egrave;re efficace</li>\r\n<li>Savoir contester l&rsquo;injustice et les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</li>\r\n<li>Respecter les personnes et les choses</li>\r\n<li>Coop&eacute;ration et r&egrave;glement des diff&eacute;rends</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Valeurs et attitudes</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sens de l&rsquo;identit&eacute; et estime de soi</li>\r\n<li>Empathie</li>\r\n<li>Engagement pour la justice sociale et l&rsquo;&eacute;quit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Respect de la diversit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Souci de l&rsquo;environnement et engagement pour le d&eacute;veloppement durable</li>\r\n<li>Conviction que les personnes peuvent changer les choses</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Intégrer partout l’éducation à la citoyenneté mondiale','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Illustration: Frits Ahlefeldt','Illustration: Frits Ahlefeldt',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,NULL,'Move beyond a charitable approach to global citizenship education','<blockquote>\r\n<p>&ldquo;It is a natural response for communities to want to offer &lsquo;help&rsquo; to their partners in the form of money and some partners may expect it. However, successful partnerships depend on equality and mutuality, and such charity can actually hinder development. The importance of reciprocity or &lsquo;mutual exchange&rsquo; must be recognized.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Toolkit for Learning, UKOWLA 2006</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Take every penny you have set aside in aid for Tanzania and spend it explaining to people the facts and causes of poverty.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Julius Nyerere, President of Tanzania, 1961-1985</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Often the question of financial aid and charity-based projects comes up when looking for a partnership or project opportunity for your students and school. Sometimes, even the way global citizenship education is presented and framed can reinforce and perpetuate a certain stereotype that charity is the only way that rich North American folks can help. This is not the case.</p>\r\n<p>In this section, we take a look at why a strictly charitable approach can be detrimental to students and recipients alike, and how you as an educator can augment your projects to ensure a rich breadth and depth of learning experience for your students.</p>\r\n<p>Sometimes charitable aims can be detrimental because they:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Focus on finance at the expense of other activities to which both partners or groups can contribute equally (mutual learning and reciprocity)</li>\r\n<li>Put financial inequalities centre stage and divert attention from other imbalances that ought to be addressed</li>\r\n<li>Make the partner receiving the aid dependant on this income</li>\r\n<li>Patronize the partner receiving the aid.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Charitable aims can also undermine educational opportunities by:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reinforcing, rather than challenging, stereotypes of rich, powerful, and independent communities in the North and poor, weak, and dependent communities in the South</li>\r\n<li>Perpetuating narrow views on poverty and development</li>\r\n<li>Hindering critical thinking about underlying injustices and causes of poverty, and thereby encouraging an acceptance of aid as a longterm solution.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Often, partner organizations want and need financial support. This can be a difficult issue to address because often schools want to express their support this way, and organizations may request it. However, there is a big difference between raising funds as a part of a diverse set of learning activities, and just attending an event or raising and donating money in an isolated, one-off type event.</p>\r\n<p>There are so many great learning opportunities when embarking on global citizenship education: there are unique projects, partnership opportunities, events, and lessons. With a little time, effort, and creativity, global citizenship education can be a great and equitable experience for all.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-04 03:47:18','2013-09-05 17:10:09',1,'small','','',NULL,'<blockquote>\r\n<p>C&rsquo;est une r&eacute;action naturelle pour une collectivit&eacute; que de vouloir offrir &laquo; de l&rsquo;aide &raquo; &agrave; ses partenaires et certains partenaires s&rsquo;y attendent peut-&ecirc;tre. Mais les partenariats fructueux se fondent sur l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; et la mutualit&eacute;, alors qu&rsquo;une certaine charit&eacute; peut freiner le d&eacute;veloppement. Il faut reconna&icirc;tre l&rsquo;importance de la r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute; et des &laquo; &eacute;changes mutuels &raquo;.</p>\r\n<p><em>&ndash;Toolkit for Learning</em>, UKOWLA 2006</p>\r\n<p>Prenez le moindre sou que vous avez mis de c&ocirc;t&eacute; pour aider la Tanzanie et d&eacute;pensez-le pour expliquer aux gens la r&eacute;alit&eacute; et les causes de la pauvret&eacute;.</p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Julius Nyerere, pr&eacute;sident de la Tanzanie, 1961-1985</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>La question de l&rsquo;aide financi&egrave;re et des projets d&rsquo;ordre caritatif se pose souvent lorsqu&rsquo;on envisage un partenariat ou un projet possible pour les &eacute;l&egrave;ves et pour l&rsquo;&eacute;cole. Il arrive parfois que la fa&ccedil;on dont on pr&eacute;sente ou dont on situe l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale vienne renforcer l&rsquo;id&eacute;e re&ccedil;ue selon laquelle la charit&eacute; est la seule fa&ccedil;on d&rsquo;aider pour de riches Nord-Am&eacute;ricains. Ce n&rsquo;est pas le cas.</p>\r\n<p>Dans cette section, nous examinons pourquoi une approche exclusivement caritative peut nuire aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves comme r&eacute;cipiendaires et comment l&rsquo;enseignant-e peut enrichir ses projets et permettre &agrave; ses &eacute;l&egrave;ves d&rsquo;&eacute;largir leurs perspectives et de vivre une exp&eacute;rience plus profonde.</p>\r\n<p>Il arrive que des objectifs caritatifs soient n&eacute;fastes parce qu&rsquo;ils:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mettent l&rsquo;accent sur l&rsquo;aspect financier plut&ocirc;t que sur d&rsquo;autres activit&eacute;s auxquelles les deux partenaires ou les deux groupes peuvent contribuer &eacute;galement (apprentissage mutuel et r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute;)</li>\r\n<li>Attirent l&rsquo;attention sur les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s financi&egrave;res et d&eacute;tournent l&rsquo;attention des d&eacute;s&eacute;quilibres qu&rsquo;il faudrait corriger</li>\r\n<li>Fait que le partenaire qui re&ccedil;oit l&rsquo;aide d&eacute;pend de ce revenu</li>\r\n<li>Cr&eacute;e une attitude paternaliste &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;gard du partenaire qui re&ccedil;oit l&rsquo;aide.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Les objectifs caritatifs peuvent aussi miner les possibilit&eacute;s d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation en:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Renfor&ccedil;ant, au lieu de les contester, le st&eacute;r&eacute;otype de collectivit&eacute;s riches, puissantes et ind&eacute;pendantes dans le Nord, en face de pauvres, faibles et d&eacute;pendantes dans le Sud</li>\r\n<li>Perp&eacute;tuant des conceptions &eacute;troites sur la pauvret&eacute; et le d&eacute;veloppement</li>\r\n<li>Freinant la pens&eacute;e critique sur les injustices sous-jacentes et sur les causes de la pauvret&eacute;, et en incitant &agrave; penser que l&rsquo;aide puisse &ecirc;tre une solution &agrave; long terme.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Souvent les organisations partenaires veulent de l&rsquo;argent et ont besoin d&rsquo;aide. Cela peut cr&eacute;er une situation d&eacute;licate, car les &eacute;coles veulent souvent exprimer leur appui de cette fa&ccedil;on et il arrive que les organisations demandent de l&rsquo;argent. Mais il y a une grande diff&eacute;rence entre le fait d&rsquo;organiser une collecte de fonds parmi plusieurs autres activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;apprentissage et le fait d&rsquo;assister &agrave; un &eacute;v&eacute;nement-b&eacute;n&eacute;fice ou de donner de l&rsquo;argent de mani&egrave;re isol&eacute;e, sans que la chose ait de suites.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;engagement dans l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale offre de tr&egrave;s nombreuses occasions d&rsquo;apprendre : des projets uniques, des occasions de partenariat, des &eacute;v&eacute;nements et des le&ccedil;ons de vie. Avec un peu de temps, d&rsquo;effort et de cr&eacute;ativit&eacute;, l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale peut devenir pour tout le monde une exp&eacute;rience aussi emballante qu&rsquo;&eacute;quitable.</p>','Dépasser l’approche caritative pour éduquer à la citoyenneté mondiale','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,NULL,'Partner with NGOs to promote global citizenship','<p>In addition to incorporating global citizenship education in your classroom and lesson plans, there are also other great ways to involve your students in experiential education through partnerships that employ a global lens. School partnerships and projects are a great way to interact with the larger development community and can be a way for students to take a very hands-on approach to global citizenship education.</p>\r\n<p>That being said, it is important to be very <em>thorough</em> and <em>thoughtful</em> as you select a project or an organization. Bigger isn&rsquo;t always better &ndash; look for an organization or project that reflects the interests of your students, provides an exceptional and interesting educational opportunity, and adheres to good, sound, ethical principles.</p>\r\n<p>Projects and partnerships can take a variety of different forms. For example, students or teachers can select a particular non-governmental organization (NGO) that they like and propose or participate in a project that is suited to the interests of the students. These projects do not have to simply involve raising funds for a particular cause or issue; schools can participate in a variety of different ways and with a variety of different methods.</p>\r\n<p>A good starting point in choosing a classroom project or partnership is to identify themes that are common to young people&rsquo;s lives &ndash; for example, water, food, transport, farming, land use, trade, homes, school, waste, conflict, and play. This approach has the advantage of focusing students&rsquo; minds on the things they share with young people around the world, before considering how these aspects of life are experienced differently.</p>\r\n<p>For example, a school can commit to raising community awareness about the right to clean drinking water, using the resources and knowledge from their partnering NGO. Or students might want to look at a social issue that exists within their community and organize a project with a local community organization. Middle and high school students may consider working with a local NGO or international organization to learn about examples of international incidents and the global response.</p>\r\n<p>These are just a few of examples of how you may want to approach a school project that focuses on global citizenship education.</p>\r\n<p>Tips for selecting partners:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Look local first. Involving the local community is a great way to support greater engagement and active citizenship right at home.</li>\r\n<li>Be picky. The biggest organizations aren&rsquo;t always the best. Look for a project that suits your educational interests and outcomes.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t be afraid to ask questions. Talk to Executive Directors, project managers, or other employees of the organization you&rsquo;re thinking of partnering with!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>There are many benefits to be gained from participating in a school project. At their best, projects can:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Generate enthusiasm and motivation for learning;</li>\r\n<li>Cultivate an openness to new thinking and new ideas;</li>\r\n<li>Inspire a desire for positive change, locally and globally;</li>\r\n<li>Connect the local to the global;</li>\r\n<li>Inspire kids to think about their actions in a more direct way.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Projects can help students develop:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Self-awareness;</li>\r\n<li>Respect for others;</li>\r\n<li>An appreciation of diversity;</li>\r\n<li>A sense of injustice and a commitment to fighting it.</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-04 03:54:13','2013-09-05 17:19:14',1,'tall','','',NULL,'<p>En plus d&rsquo;incorporer l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale &agrave; vos activit&eacute;s en classe et &agrave; votre plan de cours, il existe d&rsquo;autres excellentes fa&ccedil;ons de faire vivre &agrave; vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves des exp&eacute;riences p&eacute;dagogiques de partenariat dans une perspective plan&eacute;taire. Les partenariats et les projets d&rsquo;&eacute;cole sont une bonne fa&ccedil;on d&rsquo;entrer en interaction avec la communaut&eacute; du d&eacute;veloppement et peuvent offrir aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves l&rsquo;occasion de vivre un engagement pratique et concret.</p>\r\n<p>Cela dit, il est important de proc&eacute;der de mani&egrave;re <em>minutieuse</em> et <em>r&eacute;fl&eacute;chie</em> quand vient le temps de choisir un projet ou une organisation. Les plus gros ne sont pas toujours les meilleurs. Recherchez un projet ou une organisation qui corresponde aux int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts de vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves, qui offre une exp&eacute;rience p&eacute;dagogique exceptionnelle, int&eacute;ressante, et qui suive de solides principes &eacute;thiques.</p>\r\n<p>Les projets et les partenariats peuvent prendre diff&eacute;rentes formes. Par exemple, les &eacute;l&egrave;ves ou les enseignant-e-s peuvent choisir une organisation non gouvernementale (ONG) qu&rsquo;ils aiment bien ou participer &agrave; un projet qui correspond aux int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts des &eacute;l&egrave;ves. Ces projets n&rsquo;ont pas &agrave; se limiter &agrave; la collecte d&rsquo;argent pour une cause ou un probl&egrave;me particulier; les &eacute;coles peuvent participer de diff&eacute;rentes fa&ccedil;ons et selon diff&eacute;rentes m&eacute;thodes.</p>\r\n<p>Un bon point de d&eacute;part pour choisir un partenaire ou un projet de classe, c&rsquo;est de cerner des th&egrave;mes qui rejoignent la vie des jeunes: par exemple, l&rsquo;eau, la nourriture, le transport, la vie agricole, l&rsquo;utilisation des terres, le commerce, la vie &agrave; la maison, l&rsquo;&eacute;cole, le gaspillage, les conflits, le jeu. Cette approche pr&eacute;sente l&rsquo;avantage d&rsquo;amener les &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; se concentrer sur ce qu&rsquo;ils ont en commun avec les jeunes ailleurs dans le monde plut&ocirc;t que sur ce qu&rsquo;ils vivent autrement.</p>\r\n<p>C&rsquo;est ainsi qu&rsquo;une &eacute;cole peut s&rsquo;engager &agrave; sensibiliser la collectivit&eacute; au droit &agrave; l&rsquo;eau potable, en utilisant les ressources et les connaissances d&rsquo;une ONG partenaire. Ou alors les &eacute;l&egrave;ves peuvent examiner un probl&egrave;me social de leur collectivit&eacute; et organiser un projet avec un organisme communautaire local. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de la fin du primaire et du secondaire peuvent envisager de travailler avec une ONG locale ou une organisation internationale pour s&rsquo;informer de certains probl&egrave;mes internationaux et de la r&eacute;action qu&rsquo;on a eue &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle mondiale.</p>\r\n<p>Voici quelques exemples qui illustrent la fa&ccedil;on d&rsquo;approcher un projet d&rsquo;&eacute;cole ax&eacute; sur l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale.</p>\r\n<p>Suggestions pour le choix des partenaires:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Regardez d&rsquo;abord au niveau local. Faire participer la collectivit&eacute; est une excellente fa&ccedil;on de soutenir l&rsquo;engagement et la participation citoyenne autour de soi.</li>\r\n<li>Soyez exigeant-e-s. Les organisations les plus grosses ne sont pas toujours les meilleures. Cherchez un projet qui corresponde &agrave; vos int&eacute;r&ecirc;ts et &agrave; vos objectifs p&eacute;dagogiques.</li>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;ayez pas peur de poser des questions. Parlez &agrave; la direction g&eacute;n&eacute;rale, aux charg&eacute;-e-s de projet, &agrave; d&rsquo;autres membres du personnel de l&rsquo;organisation avec laquelle vous songez &agrave; &eacute;tablir un partenariat!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Il y a de nombreux avantages &agrave; participer &agrave; un projet d&rsquo;&eacute;cole. Dans le meilleur des cas, les projets permettent de:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>G&eacute;n&eacute;rer l&rsquo;enthousiasme et la motivation pour l&rsquo;apprentissage;</li>\r\n<li>Favoriser l&rsquo;ouverture &agrave; de nouvelles id&eacute;es et de nouvelles fa&ccedil;ons de penser;</li>\r\n<li>Inspirer le d&eacute;sir d&rsquo;un changement positif, au plan local ou mondial;</li>\r\n<li>Relier le niveau local au niveau mondial;</li>\r\n<li>Amener les jeunes &agrave; r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir aux gestes qu&rsquo;ils posent.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Les projets peuvent aider les &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; cultiver:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>La conscience de soi;</li>\r\n<li>Le respect de l&rsquo;autre;</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;appr&eacute;ciation de la diversit&eacute;;</li>\r\n<li>Le sens de la justice et l&rsquo;engagement pour la d&eacute;fendre.</li>\r\n</ul>','Travailler en partenariat avec des ONG pour promouvoir l’éducation à la citoyenneté mondiale','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(27,NULL,'Practice fair and equitable partnerships','<p>Before you embark on a project, partnership, or global citizenship educational event, it is important to take a few moments to consider whether or not you are participating in something that is meaningful, equitable, and just for <em>all</em> parties involved (students, teachers, partnering organization, recipients). The accompanying questions and checklist were created to promote consideration of some crucial components to all global citizenship education projects, partnerships, and events. It is has been our experience that teachers and students alike should partake in this exercise to ensure the best, richest, and most meaningful experience for all involved.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-04 03:57:32','2013-09-05 17:23:48',1,'large','','',NULL,'<p>Avant de vous lancer dans un projet, un partenariat, une activit&eacute; d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, il est important de prendre quelques instants pour vous demander si vous participez vraiment &agrave; quelque chose qui a du sens, qui est &eacute;quitable et juste pour<em> toutes les parties</em> en cause (&eacute;l&egrave;ves, enseignant-e-s. organisme partenaire, donataires). Les questions et la liste de contr&ocirc;le ci-apr&egrave;s ont &eacute;t&eacute; con&ccedil;ues pour faire r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir &agrave; des &eacute;l&eacute;ments essentiels &agrave; tout projet, partenariat ou &eacute;v&eacute;nement d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale. L&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience nous a appris qu&rsquo;enseignant-e-s et &eacute;l&egrave;ves devraient faire cet exercice pour permettre &agrave; toutes les personnes en cause de vivre l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience la plus riche et la plus porteuse de sens possible.</p>','Vivre des partenariats justes et équitables','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,NULL,'Additional resources on education for global citizenship','<p><a href=\"http://www.acgc.ca/pages.php?pg=1007&amp;sec=2031\" target=\"_blank\">Development in a Box (Alberta Council for Global Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>Designed to be an educational kit to be used by educators, Development in a Box aids in the incorporation of global issues into the curriculum and classroom for grades 1 through 12. Kits include lesson plans, hands-on activities and supplies, as well as connections to local organizations who are working internationally. The kits are available to Alberta classrooms free of charge. Lessons address many global issues and are linked to curriculum objectives in the Alberta Program of Studies.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=18432\" target=\"_blank\">BC Teacher&rsquo;s Federation Social Justice Action Groups</a></p>\r\n<p>The BCTF&rsquo;s province-wide social justice network includes six social justice action groups. Each action group is composed of four members from the provincial <a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/uploadedFiles/Public/SocialJustice/CASJ-flyer.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Committee for Action on Social Justice</a> (CASJ), and they are all classroom teachers.</p>\r\n<p>The purpose of the action groups is to provide information, lesson ideas, and professional support for classroom teachers. Each action group creates discrete web pages covering the areas for which they are responsible.</p>\r\n<p>The action groups are listed below and include links to their web pages:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6308\" target=\"_blank\">Antipoverty</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=17632\" target=\"_blank\">Antiracism</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=22000&amp;libID=21990\" target=\"_blank\">Environmental Justice</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6106\" target=\"_blank\">Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Questioning (LGBTQ)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=6214\" target=\"_blank\">Peace and Global Education</a></li>\r\n<li>The global education page features the <a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6218\" target=\"_blank\">Global Classroom</a>, a joint BCTF and CIDA project, which contains unit plans designed for teachers, by teachers.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6282\" target=\"_blank\">Status of Women</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.chf.ca/global-education/educational-resources\" target=\"_blank\">Global Education Program (Canadian Hunger Foundation)</a></p>\r\n<p>CHF is a non-profit organization dedicated to enabling poor rural communities in developing countries to attain sustainable livelihoods. (For more info, check out <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fpzg3akWq_A&amp;feature=player_embedded\" target=\"_blank\">their video</a>.)</p>\r\n<p>CHF began their popular Global Education Program (GEP) in Canada in 1991 to support the development of global citizens and increase awareness about the realities faced by rural communities in developing countries. The Global Education Program is now one of the pillars of CHF and they support thousands of teachers, students, volunteers and other organizations across the country to shape the way young Canadians see the world and their place in it.</p>\r\n<p>CHF&rsquo;s international programming efforts make the Global Education Program unique in Canada because of the intimate and direct connection the program has to actual projects taking place around the world. The result is a program that inspires Canada&rsquo;s youth to embrace cultural diversity in their communities and to become active global citizens.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://wavemakers.cawst.org/index.php/educator-resources\" target=\"_blank\">Youth Wavemakers (Centre for Affordable Water and Sanitation Technology)</a></p>\r\n<p>CAWST\'s Youth Wavemakers is a unique water education program that informs, engages, encourages action, and celebrates the impact that youth are having on local and global water and sanitation issues.Contains tonnes of interactive social justice water-themed lesson plans.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://ebeat.sasktelwebhosting.com/get_involved/teachers.php\" target=\"_blank\">WorldBeat project (Saskatchewan Council for International Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>If you\'re a teacher or educator, and you\'d like to add more international or environmental awareness to your classroom or school, the WorldBeat project has resources for you! A collection of lesson plans and other classroom activities are compiled by teachers and distributed through electronic mail outs on an ongoing basis. Topics range from HIV and AIDS to globalization, health and sustainability. In-classroom workshops are also available.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/global-citizenship/global-citizenship-guides\" target=\"_blank\">Global Citizenship Guides (Oxfam)</a></p>\r\n<p>Oxfam is a non-governmental organization and a global movement for change &ndash; it is a network that empowers individuals, communities and organizations to build a future free from the injustice of poverty where the rights of women and girls are promoted and respected.</p>\r\n<p>Aimed at teachers in all subjects, and across all age groups, Oxfam&rsquo;s global citizenship guides introduce the key elements of Oxfam\'s Curriculum for Global Citizenship, as well as providing case studies outlining best practice in the classroom, activities that can be adapted for use in many curriculum areas, and resources for further reading.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.videa.ca/index.php?pageid=135\" target=\"_blank\">Victoria International Development Association (VIDEA)</a></p>\r\n<p>VIDEA was established as a non-profit organization in 1977 to &ldquo;inspire thought and action on global issues.&rdquo; Based in Victoria, VIDEA actively involves youth, educators, and community partners in the development and implementation of international development, global education and youth and community engagement initiatives.</p>\r\n<p>This resource contains a range of globally focused learning resources covering topics from global warming to access to education, to the future of our forests to gender equity.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://generatingmomentum.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Generating Momentum (Manitoba Council for International Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>Generating Momentum is a branch of MCIC&rsquo;s public engagement work. It focuses specifically on engaging Manitoba&rsquo;s middle school and high school students on issues related to fair trade, food security, gender, Millenium Development Goals, and water. It also provides educational resources to teachers and opportunities for workshops, partnership, youth conferences, and more.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'resources','2013-09-04 04:13:19','2013-09-05 17:32:23',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p><a href=\"http://www.acgc.ca/pages.php?pg=1007&amp;sec=2031\" target=\"_blank\">Development in a Box (Alberta Council for Global Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Le d&eacute;veloppement en bo&icirc;te. Conseil albertain pour la coop&eacute;ration mondiale]</p>\r\n<p>Con&ccedil;u pour offrir aux enseignant-e-s une trousse p&eacute;dagogique, &laquo; Development in a Box &raquo; aide &agrave; incorporer les enjeux mondiaux aux programmes et aux activit&eacute;s en classe de la 1re &agrave; la 12e ann&eacute;e. Les trousses comprennent des plans de cours, des activit&eacute;s pratiques et des fournitures, ainsi que des liens aux organisations locales qui travaillent &agrave; l&rsquo;international. Les trousses sont offertes gratuitement aux classes de l&rsquo;Alberta. Les le&ccedil;ons abordent des enjeux mondiaux en lien avec les objectifs du programme du minist&egrave;re de l&rsquo;&Eacute;ducation de l&rsquo;Alberta.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=18432\" target=\"_blank\">BC Teacher&rsquo;s Federation Social Justice Action Groups</a></p>\r\n<p>[Groupes d&rsquo;action pour la justice sociale. F&eacute;d&eacute;rations des enseignant-e-s de C.-B.]</p>\r\n<p>Le r&eacute;seau provincial de justice sociale de la BCTF comprend six groupes d&rsquo;action pour la justice sociale. Chaque groupe compte quatre membres du <a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/uploadedFiles/Public/SocialJustice/CASJ-flyer.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Committee for Action on Social Justice</a> (CASJ), qui sont tous des enseignantes et des enseignants en activit&eacute;.</p>\r\n<p>Les groupes d&rsquo;action ont pour but de fournir de l&rsquo;information, des suggestions p&eacute;dagogiques et un appui professionnel aux enseignantes et aux enseignants. Chaque groupe d&rsquo;action produit des pages Web couvrant la mati&egrave;re dont il est responsable.</p>\r\n<p>Voici les groupes d&rsquo;action avec un lien &agrave; leurs pages Web:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6308\" target=\"_blank\">Antipoverty</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=17632\" target=\"_blank\">Antiracism</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=22000&amp;libID=21990\" target=\"_blank\">Environmental Justice</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6106\" target=\"_blank\">Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Questioning (LGBTQ)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/SocialJustice.aspx?id=6214\" target=\"_blank\">Peace and Global Education</a></li>\r\n<li>La page sur l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation plan&eacute;taire pr&eacute;sente le projet&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6218\" target=\"_blank\">Global Classroom</a>, soutenu conjointement par la BCTF et l&rsquo;ACDI, qui contient des plans de cours con&ccedil;us par des enseignant-e-s pour des enseignant-e-s.</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bctf.ca/WorkArea/linkit.aspx?LinkIdentifier=id&amp;ItemID=6282\" target=\"_blank\">Status of Women</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.chf.ca/global-education/educational-resources\" target=\"_blank\">Global Education Program (Canadian Hunger Foundation)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Programme d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation plan&eacute;taire. Fondation canadienne pour la faim dans le monde]</p>\r\n<p>La CHF est une organisation &agrave; but non lucratif vou&eacute;e &agrave; aider les collectivit&eacute;s rurales des pays en d&eacute;veloppement &agrave; assurer leur subsistance. (Pour de plus amples renseignements, voir leur <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fpzg3akWq_A&amp;feature=player_embedded\" target=\"_blank\">video</a>.)</p>\r\n<p>La CHF a lanc&eacute; son populaire Global Education Program (GEP) au Canada en 1991 pour soutenir le d&eacute;veloppement de citoyennes et de citoyens mondiaux et les sensibiliser &agrave; la situation des collectivit&eacute;s rurales dans les pays en d&eacute;veloppement. Le Global Education Program est l&rsquo;un des piliers de la CHF, qui appuie des milliers d&rsquo;enseignant-e-s, d&rsquo;&eacute;l&egrave;ves, de b&eacute;n&eacute;voles et d&rsquo;autres organisations au pays &agrave; influencer la fa&ccedil;on dont les jeunes au Canada voient le monde et leur place dans le monde.</p>\r\n<p>La programmation internationale de la CHF fait du Global Education Program une entreprise unique au Canada &agrave; cause du lien &eacute;troit et direct entre le programme et des projets concrets qui se r&eacute;alisent &agrave; travers le monde. D&rsquo;o&ugrave; un programme qui pousse les jeunes &agrave; embrasser la diversit&eacute; culturelle dans leurs collectivit&eacute;s et &agrave; devenir des citoyennes et des citoyens du monde activement engag&eacute;s.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://wavemakers.cawst.org/index.php/educator-resources\" target=\"_blank\">Youth Wavemakers (Centre for Affordable Water and Sanitation Technology)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Les jeunes font des vagues. Centre pour une technologie hydrique et sanitaire abordable]</p>\r\n<p>Youth Wavemakers est un programme unique d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation au probl&egrave;me de l&rsquo;eau, qui informe, engage, pousse &agrave; l&rsquo;action et c&eacute;l&egrave;bre l&rsquo;impact qu&rsquo;ont les jeunes &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle locale et au niveau mondial sur les questions relatives &agrave; l&rsquo;eau et &agrave; l&rsquo;hygi&egrave;ne. Il contient des tas de plans de cours interactifs sur le probl&egrave;me social de l&rsquo;eau.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://ebeat.sasktelwebhosting.com/get_involved/teachers.php\" target=\"_blank\">WorldBeat project (Saskatchewan Council for International Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Au rythme du monde. Conseil saskatchewannais pour la coop&eacute;ration internationale]</p>\r\n<p>Vous enseignez, vous faites de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation et vous souhaitez accro&icirc;tre la sensibilit&eacute; internationale ou environnementale de votre classe ou de votre &eacute;cole, alors le projet WorldBeat a des ressources &agrave; vous offrir. Une s&eacute;rie de plans de cours et d&rsquo;autres activit&eacute;s en classe, compil&eacute;e par des enseignant-e-s et diffus&eacute;e r&eacute;guli&egrave;rement par courrier &eacute;lectronique. Les sujets vont du VIH-sida &agrave; la mondialisation, de la sant&eacute; &agrave; la viabilit&eacute;. Il y a aussi des ateliers en classe.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/global-citizenship/global-citizenship-guides\" target=\"_blank\">Global Citizenship Guides (Oxfam)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Guides pour la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale. Oxfam]</p>\r\n<p>Oxfam est une organisation non gouvernementale et un mouvement mondial pour le changement; c&rsquo;est un r&eacute;seau qui permet aux individus, aux collectivit&eacute;s et aux organisations de construire un avenir lib&eacute;r&eacute; de l&rsquo;injustice de la pauvret&eacute; et o&ugrave; soient promus et respect&eacute;s les droits des femmes et des filles.</p>\r\n<p>Destin&eacute;s aux enseignant-e-s de toutes les disciplines et pour tous les groupes d&rsquo;&acirc;ge, les Guides pour la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale d&rsquo;Oxfam pr&eacute;sentement les grands &eacute;l&eacute;ments du Programme de citoyennet&eacute; mondiale d&rsquo;Oxfam en plus de fournir des &eacute;tudes de cas qui illustrent les meilleures pratiques en classe, des activit&eacute;s qu&rsquo;on peut adapter &agrave; diff&eacute;rents programmes scolaires et des ressources pour continuer de lire sur le sujet.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.videa.ca/index.php?pageid=135\" target=\"_blank\">Victoria International Development Association (VIDEA)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Association pour le d&eacute;veloppement international de Victoria]</p>\r\n<p>La VIDEA a &eacute;t&eacute; cr&eacute;&eacute;e comme organisation &agrave; but non lucratif en 1977 dans le but de &laquo; stimuler la pens&eacute;e et l&rsquo;action sur les enjeux mondiaux &raquo;. &Eacute;tablie dans la ville de Victoria, la VIDEA fait participer activement des jeunes, des &eacute;ducatrices et des &eacute;ducateurs et des partenaires communautaires &agrave; la conception et &agrave; la mise en &oelig;uvre du d&eacute;veloppement international, de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation plan&eacute;taire et d&rsquo;initiatives d&rsquo;engagement communautaire et d&rsquo;engagement jeunesse.</p>\r\n<p>Cet outil contient diverses ressources d&rsquo;apprentissage abordant dans une perspective plan&eacute;taire des th&egrave;mes comme le r&eacute;chauffement climatique, l&rsquo;acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation, l&rsquo;avenir de nos for&ecirc;ts et l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://generatingmomentum.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Generating Momentum (Manitoba Council for International Cooperation)</a></p>\r\n<p>[Nouvel &eacute;lan. Conseil manitobain pour la coop&eacute;ration internationale]</p>\r\n<p>Generating Momentum est une division du secteur d&rsquo;engagement du public du MCIC. Le programme vise pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment &agrave; engager les &eacute;l&egrave;ves manitobains de la fin du primaire et du secondaire sur des enjeux reli&eacute;s au commerce &eacute;quitable, &agrave; la s&eacute;curit&eacute; alimentaire, &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes, aux objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement, et &agrave; l&rsquo;eau. Il fournit aussi des ressources p&eacute;dagogiques aux enseignant-e-s et des possibilit&eacute;s d&rsquo;ateliers, de partenariat, de congr&egrave;s jeunesse, et plus encore.</p>','Ressources additionnelles sur l’éducation à la citoyenneté mondiale','ressources','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,NULL,'Checklist for effective partnerships','<p><strong>Signs of a good partnership</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mutual exchange;</li>\r\n<li>Active participation and decision making by students;</li>\r\n<li>An openness to learning from, as well as about, life in a distant place;</li>\r\n<li>A commitment to exploring both similarities and differences in the lives of people in different communities around the world;</li>\r\n<li>An examination of one&rsquo;s own assumptions, attitudes, and values - and a safe space which this can happen;</li>\r\n<li>An exploration of different forms of wealth;</li>\r\n<li>A commitment to learning about the wider global issues that impact different communities across the globe;</li>\r\n<li>A willingness to think critically about one&rsquo;s own culture;</li>\r\n<li>A readiness to explore sensitive and controversial issues in the classroom, in a safe, respectful environment.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Signs of problems ahead</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A focus on the symptoms of poverty with no exploration of its causes;</li>\r\n<li>A focus on financial aid instead of rights and justice;</li>\r\n<li>A failure to engage with issues of power and (in)equality;</li>\r\n<li>An assumption that simply exposing children and young people to different cultures and ways of life will challenge stereotypes and prejudice;</li>\r\n<li>An emphasis on showing students &lsquo;how lucky they are&rsquo;;</li>\r\n<li>A focus on differences without acknowledging important similarities, leading to &lsquo;us and them&rsquo; thinking;</li>\r\n<li>A belief that respect for other cultures means learning about them uncritically;</li>\r\n<li>A belief that a northern partner has more to give to a partnership than to receive from it, in terms of either resources or learning;</li>\r\n<li>A reluctance to explore sensitive and controversial issues in the classroom.</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-04 04:17:24','2013-09-05 17:48:10',1,'large','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Les indices d&rsquo;un bon partenariat</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Il y a &eacute;change de part et d&rsquo;autre;</li>\r\n<li>Il y a participation active et prise de d&eacute;cision par les &eacute;l&egrave;ves;</li>\r\n<li>On est dispos&eacute; &agrave; apprendre de la vie &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger, au lieu de seulement s&rsquo;informer &agrave; son sujet;</li>\r\n<li>On s&rsquo;engage &agrave; explorer les ressemblances et les diff&eacute;rences dans la vie des gens de diff&eacute;rentes collectivit&eacute;s &agrave; travers le monde;</li>\r\n<li>On accepte de revenir sur ses pr&eacute;jug&eacute;s, ses attitudes et ses valeurs &ndash; parce qu&rsquo;on dispose d&rsquo;un lieu o&ugrave; cela puisse se faire en s&eacute;curit&eacute;;</li>\r\n<li>On explore diff&eacute;rentes formes de richesse;</li>\r\n<li>On s&rsquo;engage &agrave; d&eacute;couvrir les grands enjeux qui ont un impact sur diff&eacute;rentes collectivit&eacute;s &agrave; travers le monde;</li>\r\n<li>On accepte de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir de fa&ccedil;on critique &agrave; sa propre culture;</li>\r\n<li>On est dispos&eacute; &agrave; explorer en classe des sujets d&eacute;licats et controvers&eacute;s, parce que le climat y est s&eacute;curitaire et respectueux.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Les indices de probl&egrave;mes &agrave; l&rsquo;horizon</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>On s&rsquo;arr&ecirc;te aux sympt&ocirc;mes de la pauvret&eacute; sans en examiner les causes;</li>\r\n<li>On parle d&rsquo;aide financi&egrave;re, et non de droits et de justice;</li>\r\n<li>On n&rsquo;arrive pas &agrave; aborder en profondeur les questions de puissance et d&rsquo;(in)&eacute;galit&eacute;;</li>\r\n<li>On suppose qu&rsquo;il suffit d&rsquo;exposer les enfants et les jeunes &agrave; des cultures et &agrave; des modes de vie diff&eacute;rents pour contrer les st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes et les pr&eacute;jug&eacute;s;</li>\r\n<li>On insiste pour montrer aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves &laquo; la chance qu&rsquo;ils ont &raquo;;</li>\r\n<li>On souligne les diff&eacute;rences sans faire ressortir les ressemblances importantes, ce qui aboutit &agrave; penser en mode &laquo; eux autres/nous autres &raquo;;</li>\r\n<li>On pense que le respect des autres cultures consiste &agrave; s&rsquo;en informer en renon&ccedil;ant &agrave; toute pens&eacute;e critique;</li>\r\n<li>On croit que le partenaire du Nord a plus &agrave; donner qu&rsquo;&agrave; recevoir, en mati&egrave;re de ressources ou d&rsquo;apprentissage;</li>\r\n<li>On est r&eacute;ticent &agrave; aborder en classe les sujets d&eacute;licats et controvers&eacute;s.</li>\r\n</ul>','Liste de contrôle pour des partenariats efficaces','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,NULL,'Ideas for global citizenship school projects','<p>(for grades 7-12)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have students work with a local or international NGO to study cases of international incidents and the global response. What were the challenges? What were the successes? Who are the stakeholders, how are decisions made, and what were the short term and long term results of international interventions?</li>\r\n<li>Simulate an international event like a conflict over land or resources or a natural incident like an earthquake. Role play the stakeholders creating an action plan or have students design the stages of responding to the event with a model. Bring in experts from the community to answer student questions or raise further questions for students to think about. Bring in a field expert who could relay their own experience. Look for blogs or journals online that give first-hand accounts of the dynamics of dealing with a global issue.</li>\r\n<li>Take a tradition from the school like collecting jackets in the winter for those in need or collecting food for the food bank during the holidays, and redesign it for greater impact and understanding. Look at the statistics in your city for homelessness or usage of the food bank. Call the local groups in charge and ask questions, or have them come in and give a presentation. Students will generate questions of their own, like: \"Why do people need food banks? What happens when people visit the food bank? Who works at the food bank and who uses the food bank? How many kids use the food bank? Expand the questions to be more national and then international. Let the students become experts on their city and the food that comes into the city. Let them start to ask questions about food security in their country and then in the world. Allow the tradition of collecting food during the holidays to become a school-wide search for understanding about food security. Break down stereotypes that surround hunger in countries that experience issues around food security. Have the students call international agencies that deal with food security or experts from the local colleges or universities for further answers to questions.</li>\r\n<li>Take students on field trips to various parts of the city or rural areas outside the city to experience different cultures and subcultures.</li>\r\n<li>Pretend to shut the water off in the school for 15 or 30 minutes. Ask the students how life would change if the water disappeared? Ask them to design a plan of what we would do to go about accessing water if our city\'s water source was not available? What would cause the water to not be available? What questions would they be asking? Who could help? How would we reach out for help? Ask how we are helping people to access clean water around the world? Contact an NGO or international organization to help create a school-wide or class project to help others access clean water.</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-04 04:20:04','2013-09-05 18:22:21',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p>(de la 7e &agrave; la 12e ann&eacute;e)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Faire travailler les &eacute;l&egrave;ves avec une ONG locale ou internationale sur des &eacute;tudes de cas d&rsquo;incidents internationaux et la r&eacute;action mondiale qui a suivi. Quelles &eacute;taient les difficult&eacute;s? Qu&rsquo;est-ce qu&rsquo;on a r&eacute;ussi &agrave; faire? Qui &eacute;taient les parties prenantes, comment les d&eacute;cisions ont-elles &eacute;t&eacute; prises et quels ont &eacute;t&eacute; les r&eacute;sultats &agrave; court et &agrave; long terme des interventions internationales?</li>\r\n<li>Simuler un &eacute;v&eacute;nement international comme un conflit sur des ressources ou sur un territoire, ou un cataclysme comme un tremblement de terre. Faire un jeu de r&ocirc;les o&ugrave; les parties prenantes devront concevoir un plan d&rsquo;action ou demander aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves de penser les &eacute;tapes de la r&eacute;action &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;v&eacute;nement en s&rsquo;inspirant d&rsquo;un mod&egrave;le. Faire venir des expert-e-s de la collectivit&eacute; pour r&eacute;pondre aux questions des &eacute;l&egrave;ves ou poser d&rsquo;autres questions aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves pour stimuler leur r&eacute;flexion. Faire venir un-e expert-e terrain pour parler de son exp&eacute;rience sur place. Consulter les blogues et les journaux en ligne qui donnent des t&eacute;moignages de premi&egrave;re main sur la r&eacute;action &agrave; un incident d&rsquo;envergure mondiale.</li>\r\n<li>Reprendre une pratique traditionnelle &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole, comme la collecte de manteaux en hiver pour les personnes dans le besoin ou la collecte de nourriture pour la banque alimentaire &agrave; l&rsquo;occasion des F&ecirc;tes, et la repenser pour en accro&icirc;tre l&rsquo;impact et favoriser la prise de conscience. Regarder les statistiques sur l&rsquo;itin&eacute;rance ou le recours aux banques alimentaires dans votre localit&eacute;. Appeler les groupes locaux qui s&rsquo;en occupent et leur poser des questions, ou les faire venir et donner un expos&eacute;. Les &eacute;l&egrave;ves auront g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement leurs propres questions, comme : &laquo; Pourquoi les gens ont-ils besoin de banques alimentaires? Qu&rsquo;est-ce qui arrive quand les gens se pr&eacute;sentent &agrave; la banque alimentaire? Qui travaille &agrave; la banque alimentaire et qui y a recours? Combien y a-t-il d&rsquo;enfants qui ont recours &agrave; la banque alimentaire? &raquo; D&eacute;velopper les questions pour aborder le niveau national puis international. Permettre aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves de devenir des experts sur leur ville et sur la nourriture qui est apport&eacute;e dans leur ville. Les laisser poser des questions sur la s&eacute;curit&eacute; alimentaire au pays puis &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle mondiale. Faire en sorte que la tradition de ramasser de la nourriture &agrave; la veille du cong&eacute; des F&ecirc;tes soit l&rsquo;occasion d&rsquo;une r&eacute;flexion sur la s&eacute;curit&eacute; alimentaire dans toute l&rsquo;&eacute;cole. Amener les &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; appeler les agences internationales qui s&rsquo;occupent de s&eacute;curit&eacute; alimentaire, ou alors des personnes ressources des coll&egrave;ges ou des universit&eacute;s des environs, qui viendraient r&eacute;pondre &agrave; leurs questions.</li>\r\n<li>Faire visiter aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves diff&eacute;rents quartiers de la ville ou diff&eacute;rents secteurs ruraux autour de la ville pour leur faire d&eacute;couvrir diff&eacute;rentes cultures et sous-cultures.</li>\r\n<li>Faire semblant de couper l&rsquo;eau &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole pendant 15 ou 30 minutes. Demander aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves comment leur vie changerait si l&rsquo;eau disparaissait. Leur demander d&rsquo;imaginer un plan concernant ce qu&rsquo;il faudrait faire si on ne pouvait plus avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;eau du service d&rsquo;aqueduc municipal? Quelles questions poseraient-ils? Qui pourrait aider? Comment irions-nous chercher de l&rsquo;aide? Demander ensuite comment nous aidons les gens &agrave; avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;eau potable &agrave; travers le monde. Prendre contact avec une ONG ou une agence internationale pour mettre sur pied un projet de classe ou d&rsquo;&eacute;cole visant &agrave; aider d&rsquo;autres personnes &agrave; avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;eau potable.</li>\r\n</ul>','Idées pour des projets scolaires en citoyenneté planétaire','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,NULL,'KSA exercise for moving beyond a charitable approach','<p>When you take a narrowly focused charitable approach to education for global citizenship, the outcomes with your students may be very similar to the Knowledge, Skills, and Attitudes of a fundraiser.</p>\r\n<p><strong>KSAs of Fundraising</strong></p>\r\n<p><img id=\"docs-internal-guid-16b6fc97-e735-984b-cf51-5b79be597c72\" src=\"https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/QHp6KnQYA_d9PvvkvZjKBqX1rvY2PtxG6fDAhToZ7J_F3nfNlZKVFZqHMx1yS6wheSMMYxiZAHCYxigNQSJTnhfJe8HAAI7xmc8VplUJu6_4kDezOnMcSUB6\" alt=\"\" width=\"631px;\" height=\"347px;\" /></p>\r\n<p>VS</p>\r\n<p>When financial aid is coupled with a variety of different educational and participatory learning experiences that challenge existing stereotypes and compel critical thought in students, the Knowledge, Skills, and Attitudes may closer resemble that of a global citizen.</p>\r\n<p><strong>KSAs of Global Citizenship Education</strong></p>\r\n<p><img id=\"docs-internal-guid-16b6fc97-e734-1201-0a25-0daef69410be\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/apxnXSz1ts5-BeC77sPWwSiCe-TiX32eSj-vEKDqeZXBVmYt86zgL9I017tZAipgvZoP2zDSCCOTrXbEx18Wc418vLrN_ce5mYnjPYXwbJ5CjEknRhmNQl2l\" alt=\"\" width=\"631px;\" height=\"347px;\" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection questions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How do these two differ? What implications do these have for how you will construct your partnership?</li>\r\n<li>What are the benefits to moving beyond &lsquo;fundraiser&rsquo; outcomes toward &lsquo;global citizenship&rsquo; outcomes?</li>\r\n<li>How might you change your approach to better reflect and achieve the KSA&rsquo;s of global citizenship education?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-04 04:26:10','2013-09-05 18:29:39',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p>Si vous adoptez une approche &eacute;troitement caritative en &eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale, l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience que feront vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves ressemblera beaucoup &agrave; celle d&rsquo;un sp&eacute;cialiste de la collecte de fonds, en mati&egrave;re de connaissances, de comp&eacute;tences et d&rsquo;attitudes.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Connaissances/comp&eacute;tences/attitudes de la collecte de fonds</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Connaissances et compr&eacute;hension</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Litt&eacute;racie math&eacute;matique et financi&egrave;re</li>\r\n<li>&Eacute;thique des affaires</li>\r\n<li>Autonomisation financi&egrave;re</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Comp&eacute;tences</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Vente de produits</li>\r\n<li>Service &agrave; la client&egrave;le</li>\r\n<li>Traitement des commandes / tenue des dossiers</li>\r\n<li>Gestion du temps</li>\r\n<li>Manipulation de l&rsquo;argent</li>\r\n<li>Livraison de marchandises</li>\r\n<li>Sourire</li>\r\n<li>Garder le contact visuel</li>\r\n<li>S&rsquo;exprimer clairement</li>\r\n<li>Savoir se pr&eacute;senter</li>\r\n<li>Parler d&rsquo;une cause/passion</li>\r\n<li>Marketing</li>\r\n<li>Publicit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Promotions</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Valeurs et attitudes</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Avoir une attitude positive</li>\r\n<li>Travail d&rsquo;&eacute;quipe</li>\r\n<li>Concurrence</li>\r\n<li>Gratification personnelle</li>\r\n<li>Parler d&rsquo;une cause/passion</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;argent, seul d&eacute;terminant de la richesse</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Lorsque l&rsquo;assistance financi&egrave;re s&rsquo;allie &agrave; diverses autres exp&eacute;riences p&eacute;dagogiques et &agrave; des apprentissages participatifs qui mettent en question les st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes et stimulent la pens&eacute;e critique chez les &eacute;l&egrave;ves, leurs connaissances, comp&eacute;tences et attitudes ressembleront davantage &agrave; celles d&rsquo;un-e citoyen-en plan&eacute;taire.</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Connaissances/comp&eacute;tences/attitudes de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Connaissances et compr&eacute;hension</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Justice sociale et &eacute;quit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Diversit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Mondialisation et interd&eacute;pendance</li>\r\n<li>D&eacute;veloppement durable</li>\r\n<li>Paix et conflit</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Comp&eacute;tences</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Pens&eacute;e critique</li>\r\n<li>Savoir discuter de mani&egrave;re efficace</li>\r\n<li>Savoir contester l&rsquo;injustice et les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</li>\r\n<li>Respect des personnes et des choses</li>\r\n<li>Coop&eacute;ration et r&egrave;glement des diff&eacute;rends</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Valeurs et attitudes</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sens de l&rsquo;identit&eacute; et estime de soi</li>\r\n<li>Empathie</li>\r\n<li>Engagement pour la justice sociale et l&rsquo;&eacute;quit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Appr&eacute;ciation et respect de la diversit&eacute;</li>\r\n<li>Souci pour l&rsquo;environnement et engagement envers le d&eacute;veloppement durable</li>\r\n<li>Conviction que les personnes peuvent changer les choses</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>En quoi les deux approches sont-elles diff&eacute;rentes? Quelles cons&eacute;quences ont-elles pour vous au moment de b&acirc;tir un partenariat?</li>\r\n<li>Quels avantages y a-t-il &agrave; d&eacute;passer l&rsquo;approche de la collecte de fonds pour rechercher les objectifs de la citoyennet&eacute; plan&eacute;taire?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Comment pourriez-vous modifier votre approche pour mieux refl&eacute;ter et mieux atteindre les connaissances/comp&eacute;tences/attitudes de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale?</p>','Exercice pour dépasser l’approche caritative','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(32,NULL,'Methods for integrating global citizenship education in the classroom','<p>Global Citizenship Education can utilize a multitude of participatory teaching and learning methodologies. These can include: discussion and debate; role-play; ranking exercises; and communities of enquiry. These methods are now established as best practices in education, and are not unique to Global Citizenship Education. However, when used in conjunction with a global perspective, they can help young people to learn how decisions made by people in other parts of the world affect our lives, just as our decisions affect the lives of others.</p>\r\n<p>Tips for global citizenship education integration:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Use inquiry-based and experiential teaching and learning tasks.</li>\r\n<li>Ask students to become the experts. Let them be the researchers and design the questions they would like to answer.</li>\r\n<li>Ask students what they would need to become experts in this field: where can they access information and expertise; whose voices need to be heard in order to get the facts on the issues?</li>\r\n<li>Give students the tools and the opportunity to go find out the answers to the questions on their own.</li>\r\n<li>If possible, get students out of the classroom to experience aspects of the globe they are studying.</li>\r\n<li>Have students determine what global citizenship is and what it is not.</li>\r\n<li>Introduce students to words like &ldquo;empowerment,&rdquo; &ldquo;solidarity,&rdquo; and &ldquo;equity.&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>Have students challenge the picture of reality that is shown to them in the media: is what they are looking at true? Does it represent the whole truth? Whose perspectives can help us get a fuller picture of the truth?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Where can Education for Global Citizenship be incorporated into curriculum?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>English Language Arts (multi-literacy practices &ndash; reading, writing, oral communication, media literacy);</li>\r\n<li>Social Studies (human relationships, human-earth relationships);</li>\r\n<li>Sciences (environmental issues and sustainability; conflicts of values &ndash; religious, political, economic);</li>\r\n<li>Health (global health issues, migration, food);</li>\r\n<li>Business and Economics (globalization, trade, global finance networks and institutions);</li>\r\n<li>Math (substituting x, y, z for real world variables; learning math through social justice);</li>\r\n<li>Art (visual culture, photography, dance, drama, music);</li>\r\n<li>Physical Education (outdoor activities, appreciating the outdoor environment)</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-04 04:29:14','2013-09-05 21:57:26',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p>L&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale peut utiliser diverses m&eacute;thodes participatives d&rsquo;enseignement et d&rsquo;apprentissage. Entre autres : la discussion et le d&eacute;bat, le jeu de r&ocirc;les, les exercices de priorisation, et les groupes d&rsquo;enqu&ecirc;te. Ces m&eacute;thodes sont maintenant reconnues comme des pratiques exemplaires en &eacute;ducation, et elles ne sont pas propres &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale. Cependant, lorsqu&rsquo;on les utilise en lien avec un point de vue plan&eacute;taire, elles peuvent aider les jeunes &agrave; comprendre comment des d&eacute;cisions prises par des gens ailleurs dans le monde ont un impact sur notre vie, tout comme nos propres d&eacute;cisions influencent la vie des autres.</p>\r\n<p>Suggestions pour l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Utiliser une approche fond&eacute;e sur l&rsquo;enqu&ecirc;te, et sur l&rsquo;enseignement et l&rsquo;apprentissage &agrave; partir de l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience.</li>\r\n<li>Demander aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves de devenir des expert-e-s. Les laisser faire la recherche, et penser les questions auxquelles ils voudront donner une r&eacute;ponse.</li>\r\n<li>Demander aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves de quoi ils auraient besoin pour devenir des expert-e-s en ce domaine; o&ugrave; ils devraient chercher pour avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;information et &agrave; la comp&eacute;tence voulues; qui ils devraient consulter pour obtenir les faits sur les enjeux en cause.</li>\r\n<li>Donner aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves les outils et l&rsquo;occasion de trouver les r&eacute;ponses aux questions qu&rsquo;ils ont formul&eacute;es.</li>\r\n<li>Si possible, faire sortir les &eacute;l&egrave;ves de la salle de classe pour leur permettre de faire l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience de certaines des r&eacute;alit&eacute;s qu&rsquo;ils &eacute;tudient.</li>\r\n<li>Faire d&eacute;finir aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves ce qu&rsquo;est la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale et ce qu&rsquo;elle n&rsquo;est pas.</li>\r\n<li>Pr&eacute;senter aux &eacute;l&egrave;ves des mots comme autonomisation (empowerment), solidarit&eacute; et &eacute;quit&eacute;.</li>\r\n<li>Amener les &eacute;l&egrave;ves &agrave; contester l&rsquo;image de la r&eacute;alit&eacute; que leur proposent les m&eacute;dias: ce qu&rsquo;on leur montre est-il vrai? Est-ce que cela repr&eacute;sente toute la r&eacute;alit&eacute; ? Quels sont les points de vue qui nous aident &agrave; nous faire une image plus compl&egrave;te de la v&eacute;rit&eacute;?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>O&ugrave; dans le programme peut-on int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Fran&ccedil;ais (pratiques de litt&eacute;racie multiple: lecture, &eacute;criture, communication orale, utilisation des m&eacute;dias);</li>\r\n<li>&Eacute;tudes sociales (relations humaines; relations avec la Terre);</li>\r\n<li>Sciences (questions environnementales, d&eacute;veloppement durable; conflits de valeurs &ndash; religieuses, politiques &eacute;conomiques);</li>\r\n<li>Sant&eacute; (probl&egrave;mes de sant&eacute; plan&eacute;taire, migrations, alimentation);</li>\r\n<li>Affaires et &eacute;conomie (mondialisation, commerce, les institutions financi&egrave;res internationales et les r&eacute;seaux financiers mondiaux);</li>\r\n<li>Math&eacute;matiques (remplacer x, y, z par des variables mondiales; apprendre les math&eacute;matiques par le truchement de la justice sociale);</li>\r\n<li>Arts (culture visuelle, photographie, danse, th&eacute;&acirc;tre, musique);</li>\r\n<li>&Eacute;ducation physique (activit&eacute;s &agrave; l&rsquo;ext&eacute;rieur, appr&eacute;cier le plein air).</li>\r\n</ul>','Méthodes pour intégrer en classe l’éducation à la citoyenneté mondiale','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,NULL,'Reflection questions for practicing fair and equitable partnerships','<p><strong>Reflection questions for students and teachers:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What are your motivations in establishing the partnership? What are the motivations of your partner organization?</li>\r\n<li>Do the values, goals, and practices of the organization align with the values, goals, and vision of your school?</li>\r\n<li>Have you researched the organization&rsquo;s policies, programs and organizational history? What do other people have to say about this organization?</li>\r\n<li>Does the organization adhere to the Istanbul Principles? (Don&rsquo;t know what the Istanbul Principles are? Find out <a href=\"http://www.cso-effectiveness.org/istanbul-principles,067\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.)</li>\r\n<li>Does the organization embody gender equality and equity while promoting women&rsquo;s and girls&rsquo; rights?</li>\r\n<li>How will accumulated finances and resources be used?</li>\r\n<li>What does each partner contribute to this relationship? Is it reciprocal?</li>\r\n<li>What does this partnership offer you and your students in return for your time and resources?</li>\r\n<li>If children from overseas are involved, how will they benefit from this partnership?</li>\r\n<li>Who is benefitting from this partnership?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Reflection questions for teachers:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What do you hope your students will learn and how does this project or partnership foster and enhance that learning?</li>\r\n<li>Is this a long-term partnership or short-term initiative? What are the advantages and disadvantages of each? How will this affect your learning outcomes?</li>\r\n<li>Does this project primarily support and exemplify mutual reciprocity, or a charitable exchange? What is the difference, and how does each of those impact your partners?</li>\r\n<li>Have you explored the difference between charity and reciprocity with your students?</li>\r\n<li>Are there mechanisms in place to ensure financial and social accountability for both you and your partner?</li>\r\n<li>In what ways does the partnership support critical reflection in your students?</li>\r\n<li>In what ways do you anticipate that the partnership will promote agency among students in relation to international development and global citizenship?</li>\r\n</ul>','',0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-04 04:33:14','2013-09-05 22:09:10',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Questions de r&eacute;flexion pour les &eacute;l&egrave;ves et les enseignant-e-s</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Quelles sont vos motivations pour nouer ce partenariat? Quelles sont les motivations de votre organisme partenaire?</li>\r\n<li>Est-ce que les valeurs, les objectifs et les pratiques de l&rsquo;organisme concordent avec les valeurs, les objectifs et la perspective de votre &eacute;cole?</li>\r\n<li>Avez-vous &eacute;tudi&eacute; les politiques, les programmes et l&rsquo;histoire de l&rsquo;organisme? Qu&rsquo;est-ce qu&rsquo;on dit de cet organisme?</li>\r\n<li>Cet organisme adh&egrave;re-t-il aux Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul? (Vous ne savez pas ce que sont les Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul? V&eacute;rifiezici.)</li>\r\n<li>Cet organisme incarne-t-il l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes tout en en se portant &agrave; la d&eacute;fense des droits des femmes et des filles?</li>\r\n<li>Comment l&rsquo;argent et les ressources seront-ils utilis&eacute;s?</li>\r\n<li>Quel est l&rsquo;apport de chaque partenaire &agrave; cette relation? Y a-t-il r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute;?</li>\r\n<li>Qu&rsquo;est-ce que ce partenariat vous offre, &agrave; vous et &agrave; vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves, en &eacute;change de votre temps et de vos ressources?</li>\r\n<li>Si le partenariat met en cause des enfants &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger, comment ceux-ci vont-ils en b&eacute;n&eacute;ficier?</li>\r\n<li>Qui b&eacute;n&eacute;ficie de ce partenariat?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Questions de r&eacute;flexion pour les enseignant-e-s</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Qu&rsquo;esp&eacute;rez-vous que vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves vont apprendre et en quoi le projet ou le partenariat vont-ils favoriser ou enrichir cet apprentissage?</li>\r\n<li>S&rsquo;agit-il d&rsquo;un partenariat &agrave; long terme ou d&rsquo;une initiative &agrave; court terme? Quels sont les avantages et les inconv&eacute;nients de l&rsquo;un ou l&rsquo;autre? Comment les r&eacute;sultats en seront-ils affect&eacute;s?</li>\r\n<li>Ce projet favorise et illustre-t-il avant tout la r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute; mutuelle, ou un &eacute;change caritatif? Quelle est la diff&eacute;rence, et quel sera l&rsquo;impact de l&rsquo;une ou l&rsquo;autre approche sur vos partenaires?</li>\r\n<li>Avez-vous scrut&eacute; avec vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves la diff&eacute;rence entre la charit&eacute; et la r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute;?</li>\r\n<li>Y a-t-il des m&eacute;canismes en place pour assurer la reddition de comptes sur le plan financier, pour vous comme pour votre partenaire?</li>\r\n<li>De quelles fa&ccedil;ons le partenariat va-t-il favoriser la r&eacute;flexion critique chez vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves?</li>\r\n<li>De quelles fa&ccedil;ons pr&eacute;voyez-vous que le partenariat favorisera l&rsquo;engagement actif de vos &eacute;l&egrave;ves en mati&egrave;re de d&eacute;veloppement international et de citoyennet&eacute; mondiale?</li>\r\n</ul>','Questions de réflexion pour vivre des partenariats justes et équitables','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(34,NULL,'Public engagement policy in context','<p>Policy is sometimes considered to be an umbrella term for guidelines, rules, regulations, laws, principles, framework, standards. But regardless of what you call it, <em>policy guides our actions</em>. It dictates what is done, how it&rsquo;s done, and for whom (or to whom) it is done.</p>\r\n<p>The content of this section of the toolkit aims to highlight the importance of having a public engagement policy for your organization. It provides general questions, a sample policy, and accompanying category-based questions as tools to support organizations interested in developing a public engagement policy that best suits their specific needs and values.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-04 05:50:34','2013-09-04 05:50:34',8,'small','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(35,NULL,'Public engagement policy in context','<p>Policy is sometimes considered to be an umbrella term for guidelines, rules, regulations, laws, principles, framework, standards. But regardless of what you call it, <em>policy guides our actions</em>. It dictates what is done, how it&rsquo;s done, and for whom (or to whom) it is done.</p>\r\n<p>The content of this section of the toolkit aims to highlight the importance of having a public engagement policy for your organization. It provides general questions, a sample policy, and accompanying category-based questions as tools to support organizations interested in developing a public engagement policy that best suits their specific needs and values.</p>','',0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-04 05:50:40','2013-09-04 05:50:40',8,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(36,NULL,'Develop an organizational public engagement policy','<p>Organizational policies are most relevant, realizable and meaningful when they are made explicit in a document that is consulted regularly, with all efforts monitored and evaluated regularly. An effective policy can be put into good practice when enabled by leaders with specific responsibility for the governance, management, and implementation of systems, structures, programs, projects and activities.</p>\r\n<p>The process of developing an organizational public engagement policy can be very useful to board members, executive directors, policy directors, public engagement coordinators, global educators, youth engagement workers, and anyone else who is looking to strengthen their public engagement programming and is looking for tools and resources to help them do so.</p>\r\n<p>What a public engagement policy can do:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ensure organizational values and beliefs are reflected in activities and events;</li>\r\n<li>Establish the guidelines or ground rules of your organization&rsquo;s public engagement work;</li>\r\n<li>Articulate the principles that guide your actions to promote transformational public engagement; and</li>\r\n<li>Clarify the roles and responsibilities for work being done in your organization</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>(Adapted from &ldquo;Rural Communities Impacting Policy&ndash;A Workbook,&rdquo; 2005).</em></p>\r\n<p>Why public engagement policy is important:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It guides and strengthens understanding of the role of public engagement within your organization;</li>\r\n<li>It encourages consistent good practice in the design, implementation, monitoring and evaluation, and reporting of public engagement efforts undertaken by your organization;</li>\r\n<li>It clarifies the financial and human resource decisions related to public engagement;</li>\r\n<li>It can mitigate risk related to public engagement efforts;</li>\r\n<li>It provides your Board of Directors, employees, interns, volunteers, independent consultants, members, partners, and funders with a framework for action that supports them with the job they need to do;</li>\r\n<li>It fosters efficiency by providing one thought-out decision that can be applied to many similar cases;</li>\r\n<li>Current policies do not address public engagement activities and do not enforce good public engagement practices;</li>\r\n<li>Policy can be used as a tool for public engagement quality improvements; and</li>\r\n<li>Without policy and procedures guiding public engagement work, conflict and confusion can result.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><em>(Includes items adapted from Health Communication Unit of the Centre for Health Promotion, University of Toronto, 2004, and from Paul Bullen, <a href=\"http://www.mapl.com.au/policy/tp1.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Management Alternatives for Public Services</a>.)</em></p>','',0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-04 05:57:13','2013-09-06 15:42:54',8,'','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,NULL,'Gender equality in context','<p><strong>What is gender equality?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Gender equality is at the heart of sustainable development, human rights and the fight against poverty. It is a cross-cutting issue that impacts all aspects of development. Empowering women is a precondition for development.</p>\r\n<p>As the Open Forum for CSO Development Effectiveness states, &ldquo;Gender equality refers to the equal rights, responsibilities and opportunities of women and men and girls and boys. Gender equality does not mean that women and men will become the same. It means that women and men enjoy the same status and have equal opportunity to realize their full human rights and potential to contribute to development&rdquo; (Working document no. 6). Gender equality implies an equal access to resources and power. While there is no one model that applies to all societies and cultures, gender equality always implies that women are able to participate in decision making that affects their lives and society as a whole.</p>\r\n<p>Focusing on gender equality aims to:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Encourage the equal participation of women and men in decision making;</li>\r\n<li>Enable women and girls to fully exercise their rights;</li>\r\n<li>Close the gap in women and men&rsquo;s control over resources and power and the benefits that ensue.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Are women and men equal?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Just because they are born female, women and girls are more likely to be poor and to experience discrimination. In addition to gender discrimination, women are exposed to other forms of discrimination based on race, colour, language, religion, opinion, origin and class.</p>\r\n<p>The majority of women in the world still have fewer rights, less access to education and health services, less revenue, less access to resources and less decision making power than men. And although women represent half of the world&rsquo;s population, their full contribution to all spheres of human activity is neither recognized nor valued. To achieve sustainable development, we must raise the status of women, respect their rights and fully recognize their contribution to society.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>100 million women are missing in Asia because of female foeticide and infanticide. [Working Group on the Girl Child (2007). A Girl&rsquo;s Right to Live: Female foeticide and girl infanticide.]</li>\r\n<li>26 percent of primary-school aged girls in sub-Saharan Africa do not attend school. [UN Women (2012). The Millennium Development Goals. Gender Chart 2012]</li>\r\n<li>99 percent of all maternal deaths occur in developing countries. [World Health Organization (2012). Fact sheet No348, Maternal mortality]</li>\r\n<li>Of the total 2.7 million new HIV infections in 2010, close to one million were among young people aged 15-24, of whom more than 60 percent were women. [UN Women. (2012). The Millennium Development Goals. Gender Chart 2012]</li>\r\n<li>Globally, women occupy only 25 percent of senior management positions, and in 2008/2009 were on average paid 23 percent less than men. [UN Women. (2012). The Millennium Development Goals. Gender Chart 2012]</li>\r\n<li>Globally, women average just 9 percent of the police and account for 27 percent of all judges. [UN Women. (2011). Progress of the World&rsquo;s Women 2011-2012: In pursuit of justice]</li>\r\n<li>Women account for approximately 20 percent of all parliamentarians worldwide. [UN Women. (2012). The Millennium Development Goals. Gender Chart 2012]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Is gender equality universal?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Great strides have been made to recognize women&rsquo;s rights internationally since the Convention on the Elimination of all Forms of Discrimination against Women (CEDAW), now ratified by 187 countries, and the Fourth World Conference on Women held in Beijing in 1995. Furthermore, the Millennium Development Goals (MDG) &ndash; the most ambitious global action plan to fight poverty in history &ndash; include goals to advance gender equality and women&rsquo;s empowerment.</p>\r\n<p>Women&rsquo;s issues used to be the prerogative of women&rsquo;s organizations, but today many civil society organizations work on women&rsquo;s rights and women&rsquo;s empowerment. However, gender mainstreaming remains inconsistent and depends on available resources. In the past few years donors and governments appear to have lost interest in gender equality. More than ever, civil society organizations have a fundamental role to play in keeping gender equality on the political and development agenda. Public engagement is a powerful way to do so, given the role of public engagement in shaping public opinion and inspiring people to take action.</p>\r\n<p>People who are sensitized to gender equality are more likely to change their own attitudes, respect human rights and support the struggle for equality.</p>\r\n<p>Civil society organizations have mainstreamed gender equality in their development projects, programs and organizational structures &ndash; but what about in their public engagement work? Very few specific resources are available to assist them to do so.</p>\r\n<p>This module has been designed to fill that gap. It provides an overview of key concepts, tools and best practices and is intended to help public engagement practitioners integrate gender equality in their programs, projects, activities and campaigns.</p>\r\n<p>This module provides public engagement practitioners with tips and advice on how to integrate gender equality throughout the project cycle, from planning to implementation to evaluation. The terminology used is straightforward, and practical tools are provided so that advice and recommendations can be easily applied.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Stand-alone work and gender mainstreaming</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are two ways to integrate gender equality in your public engagement work:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Stand-alone work on gender equality:</strong> A public engagement initiative that has been specifically designed to address inequalities between women and men and to promote women&rsquo;s rights</li>\r\n<li><strong>Gender mainstreaming:</strong> A strategy that aims to integrate gender equality in a public engagement initiative that has a different area of focus (such as food security, environment, private sector development, access to water, etc.).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Gender equality is an objective in its own right. Don&rsquo;t be shy &ndash; you don&rsquo;t have to be an expert to incorporate gender into your public engagement work! It mostly takes commitment, and then skills will follow.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-05 22:17:20','2013-09-05 22:17:20',5,'large','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Qu&rsquo;est-ce que l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes?</strong></p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes est au c&oelig;ur du d&eacute;veloppement durable, de la d&eacute;fense des droits de la personne et de la lutte contre la pauvret&eacute;. Cet enjeu transversal a un impact sur tous les aspects du d&eacute;veloppement. L&rsquo;autonomisation des femmes est une condition pr&eacute;alable au d&eacute;veloppement.</p>\r\n<p>Pour citer le Forum sur l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; des OCS en mati&egrave;re de d&eacute;veloppement, &laquo; l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes d&eacute;signe l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; des droits, des responsabilit&eacute;s et des chances entre les femmes et les hommes, les filles et les gar&ccedil;ons. L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH ne veut pas dire que les femmes et les hommes vont devenir identiques. Elle signifie que les femmes et les hommes jouissent du m&ecirc;me statut et ont la m&ecirc;me chance de r&eacute;aliser leur plein potentiel pour contribuer au d&eacute;veloppement &raquo; (Document de travail n&deg; 6). L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH suppose l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; d&rsquo;acc&egrave;s aux ressources et au pouvoir. M&ecirc;me si aucun mod&egrave;le ne peut s&rsquo;appliquer &agrave; toutes les soci&eacute;t&eacute;s et les cultures, l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH implique toujours que les femmes puissent participer aux d&eacute;cisions qui affectent leur vie et la soci&eacute;t&eacute; dans son ensemble.</p>\r\n<p><strong>L&rsquo;approche de l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes vise &agrave;:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>favoriser la participation &eacute;gale des femmes et des hommes &agrave; la prise de d&eacute;cision;</li>\r\n<li>permettre aux femmes et aux filles d&rsquo;exercer pleinement leurs droits;</li>\r\n<li>r&eacute;duire le foss&eacute; qui s&eacute;pare les femmes et les hommes en ce qui a trait au contr&ocirc;le des ressources, au pouvoir et aux avantages qui en d&eacute;coulent.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Y a-t-il &eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Du seul fait de leur sexe, les femmes et les filles risquent davantage d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre pauvres et victimes de discrimination. Outre la discrimination fond&eacute;e sur le genre, les femmes sont expos&eacute;es &agrave; d&rsquo;autres formes de discrimination, fond&eacute;es sur la race, la couleur, la langue, la religion, l&rsquo;opinion, l&rsquo;origine et la classe sociale.</p>\r\n<p>La majorit&eacute; des femmes dans le monde continuent d&rsquo;avoir moins de droits que les hommes, moins d&rsquo;acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation et aux services de sant&eacute;, de moindres revenus et un acc&egrave;s plus restreint aux ressources et &agrave; la prise de d&eacute;cision. Et m&ecirc;me si les femmes constituent la moiti&eacute; de la population mondiale, leur contribution pleine et enti&egrave;re &agrave; toutes les sph&egrave;res de l&rsquo;activit&eacute; humaine n&rsquo;est ni reconnue ni appr&eacute;ci&eacute;e. Pour r&eacute;aliser des progr&egrave;s humains durables, il faut am&eacute;liorer la condition des femmes, respecter leurs droits et reconna&icirc;tre pleinement leur contribution &agrave; la soci&eacute;t&eacute;.</p>\r\n<p>100 millions de femmes manquent &agrave; l&rsquo;appel en Asie du fait du f&oelig;ticide et de l&rsquo;infanticide f&eacute;minins. [Groupe de travail sur la petite fille (2007). Le droit de vivre des filles : f&oelig;ticide f&eacute;minin et infanticide des filles.]</p>\r\n<p>En Afrique subsaharienne, 26 % des filles en &acirc;ge d&rsquo;aller &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;cole primaire ne sont pas scolaris&eacute;es. [ONU Femmes (2012). Objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement. &Eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes : tableau des progr&egrave;s, 2012]</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>99 % de tous les d&eacute;c&egrave;s maternels surviennent dans des pays en d&eacute;veloppement. [Organisation mondiale de la sant&eacute; (2012). Aide-m&eacute;moire no 348, Mortalit&eacute; maternelle]</li>\r\n<li>Sur les 2,7 millions de nouvelles infections par le VIH enregistr&eacute;es en 2010, pr&egrave;s d&rsquo;un million touchaient des jeunes de 15 &agrave; 24 ans, dont plus de 60 % &eacute;taient des femmes. [ONU Femmes. (2012). Objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement. &Eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes : tableau des progr&egrave;s, 2012]</li>\r\n<li>Au niveau mondial, les femmes occupent seulement 25 % des postes de direction et, en 2008-2009, elles recevaient des salaires de 23 % inf&eacute;rieurs &agrave; ceux des hommes. [ONU Femmes. (2012). Objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement. &Eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes : tableau des progr&egrave;s, 2012]</li>\r\n<li>&Agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle mondiale, les femmes ne constituent que 9 % des corps de police et 27 % de la magistrature. [ONU Femmes. (2011). Le progr&egrave;s des femmes dans le monde 2011-2012: en qu&ecirc;te de justice]</li>\r\n<li>Les femmes repr&eacute;sentent environ 20 % des parlementaires dans le monde [ONU Femmes. (2012). Objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement. &Eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes : tableau des progr&egrave;s, 2012]</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>L&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes est-elle universelle?</strong></p>\r\n<p>La reconnaissance des droits des femmes a beaucoup progress&eacute; sur le plan international, notamment depuis l&rsquo;adoption de la Convention sur l&rsquo;&eacute;limination de toutes les formes de discrimination &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;gard des femmes (CEDEF), aujourd&rsquo;hui ratifi&eacute;e par 187 pays, et depuis la quatri&egrave;me Conf&eacute;rence mondiale sur les femmes, tenue &agrave; P&eacute;kin en 1995. D&rsquo;autre part, les objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement (OMD), qui sont le plan d&rsquo;action international le plus ambitieux de l&rsquo;histoire en mati&egrave;re de lutte &agrave; la pauvret&eacute;, incluent la promotion de l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes et l&rsquo;autonomisation des femmes.</p>\r\n<p>Les questions concernant les femmes ont &eacute;t&eacute; longtemps la pr&eacute;rogative des organisations de femmes, mais aujourd&rsquo;hui les droits des femmes et leur autonomisation forment un domaine d&rsquo;intervention pour beaucoup d&rsquo;organisations de la soci&eacute;t&eacute; civile (OSC). Mais l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH reste souvent pr&eacute;caire et d&eacute;pend des ressources disponibles. Ces derni&egrave;res ann&eacute;es, les bailleurs de fonds et les &Eacute;tats ont sembl&eacute; se d&eacute;sint&eacute;resser de la question de l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes. Tout ceci concourt &agrave; accro&icirc;tre l&rsquo;importance des OSC et de leur r&ocirc;le pour que l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH reste &agrave; l&rsquo;ordre du jour en politique comme pour le d&eacute;veloppement. L&rsquo;engagement du public est un outil important pour informer et fa&ccedil;onner l&rsquo;opinion publique et renforcer la capacit&eacute; d&rsquo;agir des gens.</p>\r\n<p>Un public sensibilis&eacute; &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH est un public susceptible de modifier ses propres attitudes, de respecter les droits de la personne et de soutenir la lutte en ce domaine.</p>\r\n<p>Les OSC ont appliqu&eacute; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH dans leurs projets de d&eacute;veloppement, leur programmation et leurs structures organisationnelles, mais qu&rsquo;en est-il de l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; leur travail d&rsquo;engagement du public? Tr&egrave;s peu de ressources sp&eacute;cifiques sont disponibles pour les aider en ce domaine.</p>\r\n<p>Le pr&eacute;sent module a &eacute;t&eacute; con&ccedil;u pour combler cette lacune. Il offre un aper&ccedil;u des concepts de base, des outils et des meilleures pratiques susceptibles d&rsquo;aider les responsables de l&rsquo;EP &agrave; int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; leurs programmes, leurs projets, leur activit&eacute;s et leurs campagnes.</p>\r\n<p>Ce module propose aux responsables de l&rsquo;EP des conseils pratiques pour int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; toutes les &eacute;tapes du cycle du projet, soit la planification, la mise en &oelig;uvre et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Dans un langage accessible, on propose des outils pratiques qui faciliteront l&rsquo;application des conseils et des recommandations.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Approche sp&eacute;cifique et approche transversale</strong></p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH en EP peut se faire de deux fa&ccedil;ons:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>L&rsquo;approche sp&eacute;cifique</strong> suppose que le projet d&rsquo;EP a &eacute;t&eacute; con&ccedil;u pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment pour aborder les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes et qu&rsquo;il a pour objectif principal de promouvoir l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</li>\r\n<li><strong>L&rsquo;approche transversale</strong> suppose l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration des concepts de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; un autre th&egrave;me, comme la s&eacute;curit&eacute; alimentaire, l&rsquo;environnement, le d&eacute;veloppement du secteur priv&eacute;, l&rsquo;acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;eau, etc.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH est un objectif en soi. Ne soyez pas timides : pas besoin d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre sp&eacute;cialiste pour int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes &agrave; votre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public. Il s&rsquo;agit avant tout de s&rsquo;y mettre : le m&eacute;tier vient avec le temps.</p>','L’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) mise en contexte','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(43,NULL,'Integrate gender equality at the project planning stage','<p>To plan a public engagement initiative, you have to chose a topic and then define your objectives, expected results, indicators and activities. Gender equality should be integrated into all aspects of results-based management. This can be done either with stand-alone work on gender equality or through a gender mainstreaming approach.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing and analyzing your topic</strong></p>\r\n<p>When designing a public engagement initiative, you will usually begin by doing research, gathering statistics and refining your understanding of the topic at hand.</p>\r\n<p>To integrate gender equality, you will need to collect sex-disaggregated data in order to understand how the issue affects men and women differently. This will help you build a narrative around the gender dimensions of your public engagement issue and will help you analyze the causes and consequences of inequalities between women and men.</p>\r\n<p>A <strong>gender analysis</strong> (see &lsquo;Further resources,&rsquo; below)is an exercise by which you collect and analyze sex-disaggregated data. You will need to ask yourself the following questions in relation to your public engagement topic:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do men/boys and women/girls experience the issue in the same way?</li>\r\n<li>Can they each express themselves freely on the issue?</li>\r\n<li>Do they have equal decision-making power?</li>\r\n<li>Do they face the same obstacles, difficulties and discriminations?</li>\r\n<li>Are their activities similar? If not, why?</li>\r\n<li>Do men/boys and women/girls have the same access to resources, opportunities, advantages and services?</li>\r\n<li>Can they exercise their rights equally?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>If you hire an external consultant to conduct background research and analysis, make sure the person has the skills required to do a gender analysis and remember to include it in their terms of reference.</p>\r\n<p>The reason for integrating gender equality in your public engagement work is to show that inequalities between men and women exist, to explain the situation and to encourage people to take action.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Defining your objectives</strong></p>\r\n<p>A public engagement project is never gender neutral. You will need to integrate gender equality into your project objectives to ensure that it does not reinforce gender stereotypes and inequalities between women and men, but rather contributes to advancing gender equality and women&rsquo;s rights.</p>\r\n<p>Your objectives should briefly describe what your project aims to accomplish in the short, medium and long term &ndash; including from the perspective of gender equality. When defining your objectives you will need to take into account the information obtained from your gender analysis and identify specific changes that will contribute to reducing gender inequality.</p>\r\n<p>You can include specific objectives on gender equality, or mainstream gender throughout all of your objectives:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Specific objectives on gender equality:</strong> These objectives are intended to raise awareness about stereotypes or inequalities between women and men.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Mainstreaming gender equality across all objectives:</strong> Gender equality is integrated into the framing of all objectives, regardless of the theme.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The following table illustrates these two options:</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 562px; height: 301px;\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" align=\"left\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><strong>Specifc objectives on gender equality</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Gender equality mainstreamed across all objectives</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Campaign</strong> on agriculture</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Improve the perception of women&rsquo;s role in agriculture</strong> by encouraging a positive portrayal of women farmers in the media and in political discourse by 2020.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>Advocate for legislation to protect farming communities from land grabs, <strong>including specific clauses to strengthen women&rsquo;s right to own and inherit land.</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Public engagement</strong> project on child labour (conferences, public engagement activities, marketing and media campaigns)</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Raise awareness</strong> of how child labour impacts <strong>girls</strong> and <strong>boys</strong> differently, and suggest possible solutions.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Improve understanding of child labour, <strong>including how it affects girls and boys differently.</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing your indicators</strong></p>\r\n<p>Once you have defined your objectives, you will need to develop indicators to measure the results achieved at the end of your public engagement project. It is generally recommended that you use both quantitative and qualitative indicators.</p>\r\n<p>It is important to use sex-disaggregated indicators to be able to assess how the project impacted men and women differently.</p>\r\n<p>Example of indicators:</p>\r\n<p><strong>GENDER-BLIND INDICATORS</strong></p>\r\n<p>Percentage of conference <em>participants</em> who claim to have an improved understanding of child labour issues.</p>\r\n<p><strong>GENDER-SENSITIVE INDICATORS</strong></p>\r\n<p>Percentage of <em>women and men</em> who attended the conference (to measure whether the event was equally accessible to women and men).</p>\r\n<p>Percentage of <em>women and men</em> who attended the conference and who claim to have an improved understanding of child labour issues (to measure whether both women and men benefitted from improved knowledge).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Further resources</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>AQOCI, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2009), Training kit: Gender and Development, p. 29,<a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/guides_2004-03_trainingkitged_2_.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/guides_2004-03_trainingkitged_2_.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li>AQOCI, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2011), Training kit : Promoting Gender Equality from Theory to Practice, p. 49,<a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li>Esplen Emily with Bell Emma, BRIDGE (2007), Gender and Indicators : Supporting Resources Collection,<a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/reports/IndicatorsSRCfrench.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/reports/IndicatorsSRCfrench.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 16:07:50','2013-09-06 16:49:09',5,'small','','',NULL,'<p>Pour planifier un projet d&rsquo;engagement du public (EP), il faut choisir une th&eacute;matique, puis en d&eacute;finir les objectifs, les r&eacute;sultats &agrave; atteindre, les indicateurs et les activit&eacute;s. L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH devrait s&rsquo;int&eacute;grer &agrave; toutes ces composantes de la planification GAR. Ce qui peut se faire selon une approche sp&eacute;cifique ou une approche transversale.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix et l&rsquo;analyse du th&egrave;me</strong></p>\r\n<p>Pour pr&eacute;parer une initiative d&rsquo;engagement du public, il faut g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement commencer par faire la recherche, colliger des statistiques et pr&eacute;ciser la conception du th&egrave;me retenu.</p>\r\n<p>Pour y int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH, il faudra recueillir des donn&eacute;es d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;es par sexe afin de bien voir comment le th&egrave;me affecte les femmes et les hommes. Cela permettra de construire un argumentaire sur les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s touchant les femmes et les hommes relativement &agrave; ce th&egrave;me, et d&rsquo;en analyser les causes et les cons&eacute;quences.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;<strong>analyse de genre</strong> ou analyse comparative entre les sexes (voir ci-apr&egrave;s les &laquo; Ressources additionnelles &raquo;)vous permet de colliger et d&rsquo;analyser ces donn&eacute;es d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;es. Cela vous am&egrave;nera &agrave; vous poser une s&eacute;rie de questions sur le th&egrave;me de votre projet d&rsquo;engagement du public :</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Les femmes/filles et les hommes/gar&ccedil;ons vivent-ils ce probl&egrave;me de la m&ecirc;me fa&ccedil;on?</li>\r\n<li>Peuvent-elles/ils s&rsquo;exprimer librement &agrave; ce sujet?</li>\r\n<li>Ont-elles/ils le m&ecirc;me pouvoir de d&eacute;cision?</li>\r\n<li>Rencontrent-elles/ils les m&ecirc;mes obstacles, difficult&eacute;s, discriminations?</li>\r\n<li>Leurs activit&eacute;s sont-elles semblables? Sinon, pourquoi?</li>\r\n<li>Les femmes/filles et les hommes/gar&ccedil;ons ont-ils &eacute;galement acc&egrave;s aux ressources, aux opportunit&eacute;s, aux avantages et aux services?</li>\r\n<li>Peuvent-ils exercer leurs droits de mani&egrave;re &eacute;gale?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Si vous confiez &agrave; un expert-conseil externe le travail de recherche et d&rsquo;analyse du th&egrave;me, veillez &agrave; ce que cette personne ait la comp&eacute;tence voulue pour proc&eacute;der &agrave; une analyse de genre et n&rsquo;oubliez pas d&rsquo;inclure cette t&acirc;che dans la d&eacute;finition de son mandat.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; votre projet d&rsquo;engagement du public a pour but de faire ressortir les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les sexes, d&rsquo;en exposer les causes et d&rsquo;inciter les gens &agrave; passer &agrave; l&rsquo;action.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des objectifs</strong></p>\r\n<p>Un projet d&rsquo;engagement du public n&rsquo;est pas neutre du point de vue de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH. Il faut int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH aux objectifs du projet pour veiller &agrave; ce que le projet d&rsquo;EP ne vienne pas renforcer les st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes ou les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes, et qu&rsquo;il contribue au contraire &agrave; faire progresser l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH et les droits des femmes.</p>\r\n<p>Vos objectifs devront d&eacute;crire en quelques mots ce que votre projet veut r&eacute;aliser &agrave; court, moyen et long terme &ndash; notamment sur le plan de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH. En d&eacute;finissant vos objectifs, vous devrez tenir compte des informations que vous aura fournies votre analyse de genre et proposer des changements pr&eacute;cis qui contribueront &agrave; r&eacute;duire les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les sexes.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; vos objectifs peut se faire de mani&egrave;re sp&eacute;cifique ou de mani&egrave;re transversale:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Objectifs sp&eacute;cifiques d&rsquo;&Eacute;FH:</strong> Ces objectifs visent &agrave; sensibiliser le public aux pr&eacute;jug&eacute;s ou aux in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Int&eacute;gration transversale de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH aux objectifs:</strong> L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH est int&eacute;gr&eacute;e &agrave; la formulation des objectifs, quel que soit le th&egrave;me.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Le tableau ci-dessous illustre ces deux options:</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 562px; height: 301px;\" border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" align=\"left\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td><strong>Objectifs sp&eacute;cifiques d&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Int&eacute;gration trans-versale de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH aux objectifs</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Campagne</strong> sure l\'agriculture</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Am&eacute;liorer la perception du r&ocirc;le des femmes</strong> dans le secteur agricole gr&acirc;ce &agrave; l&rsquo;image positive des agricultrices dans les m&eacute;dias et le discours politique, d&rsquo;ici 2020.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>Faire du plaidoyer pour une loi qui prot&eacute;gerait les communaut&eacute;s agricoles de l&rsquo;accaparement des terres,<strong> avec des clauses sp&eacute;cifiques pour renforcer le droit des femmes &agrave; poss&eacute;der ou &agrave; h&eacute;riter d&rsquo;une terre.</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Projet d&rsquo;EP&nbsp;</strong>sur le travail des enfants (conf&eacute;rence, activit&eacute;s vari&eacute;es d&rsquo;EP, campagne publicitaire et campagne de presse)</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Sensibiliser &agrave; l&rsquo;impact diff&eacute;rent</strong> du travail impos&eacute; aux <strong>filles</strong> et aux <strong>gar&ccedil;ons</strong>, et proposer des pistes de solution.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Compr&eacute;hension accrue du travail des enfants,<strong> et notamment de leur situation diff&eacute;renci&eacute;e selon leur sexe.</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des indicateurs</strong></p>\r\n<p>Une fois d&eacute;finis vos objectifs, il vous faut formuler des indicateurs afin de pouvoir mesurer les r&eacute;sultats obtenus &agrave; la fin de votre projet d&rsquo;EP. On recommande g&eacute;n&eacute;ralement de se doter d&rsquo;indicateurs quantitatifs et qualitatifs.</p>\r\n<p>Il est important de d&eacute;sagr&eacute;ger ces indicateurs par sexe pour pouvoir &eacute;valuer s&eacute;par&eacute;ment l&rsquo;impact du projet sur les hommes et sur les femmes.</p>\r\n<p>Exemples d&rsquo;indicateurs:</p>\r\n<p><strong>INDICATEURS NON SENSIBLES &Agrave; L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</strong></p>\r\n<p>Pourcentage de <strong>participants</strong> &agrave; la conf&eacute;rence qui font &eacute;tat d&rsquo;une am&eacute;lioration de leur compr&eacute;hension de la probl&eacute;matique &laquo; travail des enfants &raquo;.</p>\r\n<p><strong>INDICATEURS SENSIBLES A L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</strong></p>\r\n<p>Pourcentage de <strong>femmes et d&rsquo;hommes</strong> qui ont particip&eacute; &agrave; la conf&eacute;rence (mesure l&rsquo;&eacute;quit&eacute; dans la participation, le fait que l&rsquo;&eacute;v&eacute;nement soit accessible aux deux sexes).</p>\r\n<p>Pourcentage de <strong>femmes et d&rsquo;hommes</strong> pr&eacute;sents &agrave; la conf&eacute;rence, qui font &eacute;tat d&rsquo;une am&eacute;lioration de leur compr&eacute;hension de la probl&eacute;matique &laquo; travail des enfants &raquo; (mesure l&rsquo;am&eacute;lioration des connaissances par sexe).</p>\r\n<p><strong>Autres ressources</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>AQOCI, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2009), Trousse de formation genre et d&eacute;veloppement, p. 26, franh <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse%20ged.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">ttp://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse ged.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li>AQOCI, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2011), Trousse de formation Promouvoir l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes : la mise en pratique, p. 49, <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vfran-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vfran-2.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li>Esplen Emily et Bell Emma, BRIDGE development gender, UNDP, (2007), Genre et indicateurs, bo&icirc;te a outils, <a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/reports/IndicatorsSRCfrench.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/reports/IndicatorsSRCfrench.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>','Intégrer l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) à l’étape de la planification du projet','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'creating-her-own-way.jpg','image/jpeg',545243,'2013-09-06 16:45:33','Illustration: Frits Ahlefeldt','Illustration: Frits Ahlefeldt',NULL,NULL,NULL,'16',NULL,NULL),(44,NULL,'Integrate gender equality in your communication strategy','<p><strong>Crafting your messages</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your public speaking engagements and the messages you convey are important because they reflect your organization&rsquo;s commitment to gender equality. Regardless of the topic of your project, it is important to speak about the role women play and to recognize that women and men may experience the issue differently. Make sure not to reinforce stereotypes about what women and men can and should do, and always communicate that women and men have equal rights and should have access to the same opportunities and advantages.</p>\r\n<p>Here are some questions to ask yourself:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How do my messages reflect my organization&rsquo;s commitment to gender equality?</li>\r\n<li>Do I have specific messages on the gender dimensions of my project theme?</li>\r\n<li>Do my messages reinforce stereotypes about women and men&rsquo;s roles?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing the right images</strong></p>\r\n<p>Both women and men should appear in your communication materials. Give preference to images of women leaders in active (not passive) situations. A picture is worth a thousand words! Use pictures to show that both women and men make a positive and essential contribution to development.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Using the right words</strong></p>\r\n<p>Your choice of words is important. Give equal visibility to women and men in your texts and never use the masculine form to refer to both women and men. This is particularly important when it comes to writing in French. The Association qu&eacute;b&eacute;coise des organismes de cooperation internationale (AQOCI) produced a Guide to writing with non-sexist language to help its members reflect their commitment to gender equality in their written communications in French.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing your media outlets and promotional materials</strong></p>\r\n<p>Women and men don&rsquo;t always read the same newspapers and magazines, listen to the same radio, watch the same TV shows or have the same access to new technologies. Choose your media outlets according to the audience you are trying to reach and remember that your choice of media may have a greater impact on men or on women.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing your spokespeople</strong></p>\r\n<p>Make sure you invite both men and women to be the public face of your public engagement initiative as spokespeople, panelists, facilitators, etc.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing the journalists you work with</strong></p>\r\n<p>Invite both men and women journalists to cover your activities. Women journalists will not necessarily cover the issue in the same way as their male colleagues. If you train journalists at the outset of the project, make sure to provide them with sex-disaggregated data so they understand that women and men experience the issue differently and that specific work is needed to addresses gender inequalities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Further resources</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>AQOCI</strong>, Guide to writing with non-sexist language (2013) <em>(in French only)</em> <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/spip.php?article331\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/spip.php?article331</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>Vachon-L\'Heureux</strong> Pierretteand <strong>Gu&eacute;nette</strong> Louise (2006) Guide to non-sexist writing <em>(in French only)</em>, <a href=\"http://osez-dare.ainc-inac.gc.ca/tr/guide-fra.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://osez-dare.ainc-inac.gc.ca/tr/guide-fra.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>UNESCO</strong>, Media Development Indicators (2008) <a href=\"http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/communication-and-information/resources/publications-and-communication-materials/publications/full-list/media-development-indicators-a-framework-for-assessing-media-development/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/communication-and-information/resources/publications-and-communication-materials/publications/full-list/media-development-indicators-a-framework-for-assessing-media-development/</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>Conseil r&eacute;gional de l&rsquo;&Icirc;le de France</strong>, Gender and communication (2008) <em>(in French only)</em> <a href=\"http://www.iledefrance.fr/fileadmin/contrib_folder/Doc/Communication_genree.08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.iledefrance.fr/fileadmin/contrib_folder/Doc/Communication_genree.08.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 17:02:32','2013-09-06 17:04:34',5,'large','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Le choix des messages</strong></p>\r\n<p>Vos prises de parole et les messages que vous v&eacute;hiculez ont une grande importance : ils refl&egrave;tent les engagements de votre organisation envers l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes. Quel que soit le th&egrave;me de votre projet, il importe de parler du r&ocirc;le qu&rsquo;y jouent les femmes et de reconna&icirc;tre que les femmes et les hommes peuvent vivre le probl&egrave;me diff&eacute;remment. Veillez &agrave; ne pas renforcer les st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes sur ce qu&rsquo;une femme peut et doit faire, et ce qu&rsquo;un homme peut et doit faire, et faites passer le message que les femmes et les hommes sont &eacute;gaux en droit et doivent avoir acc&egrave;s aux m&ecirc;mes opportunit&eacute;s et aux m&ecirc;mes avantages.</p>\r\n<p>Quelques exemples de questions &agrave; vous poser:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>De quelle fa&ccedil;on mes messages-cl&eacute;s refl&egrave;tent-ils les engagements de mon organisation envers l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n<li>Est-ce que j&rsquo;ai des messages sp&eacute;cifiques sur l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH en lien avec le th&egrave;me du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Est-ce que mes messages renforcent des st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes sur les r&ocirc;les des femmes et des hommes?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des images</strong></p>\r\n<p>Vos supports de communication doivent mettre en sc&egrave;ne et des femmes et des hommes. Privil&eacute;giez les images qui montrent les femmes dans une situation d&rsquo;action, comme leaders, et non dans un &eacute;tat passif. Une image vaut mille mots : recourez-y pour montrer que les femmes et les hommes jouent un r&ocirc;le positif et essentiel dans le d&eacute;veloppement.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des mots</strong></p>\r\n<p>Le choix des mots est important. Dans les textes, il faut donner une visibilit&eacute; &eacute;gale aux femmes et aux hommes et ne jamais utiliser le masculin pour d&eacute;signer &agrave; la fois les femmes et les hommes. La chose est particuli&egrave;rement importante en fran&ccedil;ais. L&rsquo;Association qu&eacute;b&eacute;coise des organismes de coop&eacute;ration internationale (AQOCI) a produit un Guide de r&eacute;daction non sexiste pour aider ses membres &agrave; exprimer leur engagement envers l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH dans leurs communications &eacute;crites en fran&ccedil;ais.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des m&eacute;dias et des outils promotionnels</strong></p>\r\n<p>Les femmes et les hommes ne lisent pas toujours les m&ecirc;mes journaux et les m&ecirc;mes magazines, ne suivent pas les m&ecirc;mes &eacute;missions de radio ou de t&eacute;l&eacute; et n&rsquo;ont peut-&ecirc;tre pas le m&ecirc;me acc&egrave;s aux nouvelles technologies. Ciblez les m&eacute;dias en fonction du public que vous souhaitez rejoindre et songez que votre choix de m&eacute;dias peut avoir une influence plus marqu&eacute;e sur un des deux groupes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix de vos porte-parole</strong></p>\r\n<p>Veillez &agrave; ce qu&rsquo;une brochette &eacute;quilibr&eacute;e de femmes et d&rsquo;hommes repr&eacute;sente votre projet d&rsquo;engagement du public comme porte-parole, pan&eacute;listes, animatrices et animateurs, etc.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix des journalistes</strong></p>\r\n<p>Invitez des journalistes femmes et hommes pour couvrir vos activit&eacute;s. Les femmes journalistes ne traiteront pas n&eacute;cessairement le sujet de la m&ecirc;me mani&egrave;re que leurs coll&egrave;gues masculins. Si vous formez les journalistes en amont, veillez &agrave; introduire des donn&eacute;es sexosp&eacute;cifiques pour mettre en valeur le fait que les femmes et les hommes vivent le probl&egrave;me diff&eacute;remment et qu&rsquo;il faudra des efforts sp&eacute;cifiques pour rem&eacute;dier aux in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les sexes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Autres ressources</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>AQOCI,</strong> Guide de r&eacute;daction non sexiste (2013) <em>(en fran&ccedil;ais seulement) </em><a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/spip.php?article331\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/spip.php?article331</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>Vachon-L\'Heureux</strong> Pierretteet <strong>Gu&eacute;nette</strong> Louise (2006), Avoir bon genre &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;crit : guide de r&eacute;daction &eacute;pic&egrave;ne <em>(en fran&ccedil;ais seulement)</em>, <a href=\"http://osez-dare.ainc-inac.gc.ca/tr/guide-fra.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://osez-dare.ainc-inac.gc.ca/tr/guide-fra.pdf</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>UNESCO,</strong> Media Development Indicators (2008) <a href=\"http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/communication-and-information/resources/publications-and-communication-materials/publications/full-list/media-development-indicators-a-framework-for-assessing-media-development/\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.unesco.org/new/fr/communication-and-information/resources/publications-and-communication-materials/publications/full-list/media-development-indicators-a-framework-for-assessing-media-development/</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>Conseil r&eacute;gional de l&rsquo;&Icirc;le-de-France,</strong> Le genre dans la communication, 2008 <em>(en fran&ccedil;ais seulement)</em>&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.iledefrance.fr/fileadmin/contrib_folder/Doc/Communication_genree.08.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.iledefrance.fr/fileadmin/contrib_folder/Doc/Communication_genree.08.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Intégrer l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) à votre stratégie de communication','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'entrevue_radio.jpg','image/jpeg',93518,'2013-09-06 17:02:28','Andréanne Germain','Andréanne Germain',NULL,NULL,NULL,'57',NULL,NULL),(45,NULL,'Integrate gender equality in your project evaluation','<p><strong>Setting up your project monitoring system</strong></p>\r\n<p>Project monitoring is an ongoing process by which you track progress towards set objectives. To integrate gender equality in your project monitoring system, include some indicators that specifically relate to gender equality and collect sex-disaggregated data for all other project indicators. For example, track how many women attend your trainings and gather their feedback. When it comes to media monitoring, track how many times your issue is raised in the press and assess whether women&rsquo;s role is described in a positive way.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing your evaluation methods</strong></p>\r\n<p>An evaluation allows you to determine if your project has reached its objectives. You can conduct an evaluation halfway through a project, at the end of a project, or many years after to measure its long term impacts.</p>\r\n<p>The evaluation of a public engagement project aims to measure increased awareness, new knowledge, and changes in values, attitudes and behaviours. If you&rsquo;ve integrated gender equality throughout your project, this will come up in the evaluation and in people&rsquo;s perception of the project.</p>\r\n<p>It isn&rsquo;t easy to measure the impact of public engagement projects on target populations because most projects don&rsquo;t have the means to track medium- and long-term changes. The following table gives an idea of the kind of feedback you could gather during a qualitative evaluation that would reflect impact in terms of gender equality:</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 307px; width: 537px;\" border=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Increased awareness</td>\r\n<td>&ldquo;I now realize that I don&rsquo;t experience the issue in the same way my partner does.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;I now know that women in the South have a harder time than men in accessing&hellip; &ldquo;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>New knowledge</td>\r\n<td>&ldquo;I learned that 99 percent of all maternal deaths occur in developing countries.&rdquo;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Values</td>\r\n<td>&ldquo;I have realized that equality is a fundamental value for me.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;I am outraged to see the inequalities that still exist between women and men.&rdquo;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Attitudes &amp;&nbsp;Behaviours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I am committed to raising awareness about gender equality in my school.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;I am going to do volunteer work in a women&rsquo;s center.&rdquo;<br />&ldquo;From now on I&rsquo;m going to speak up when I hear sexist remarks or witness sexist behaviour.&ldquo;<br />&ldquo;I am going to pay more attention to provincial gender equality policies.&rdquo;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10px;\">Further resources:</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>CIDA</strong>, CIDA&rsquo;s Framework for Assessing Gender Equality results (2005) <a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/ACDI-CIDA.nsf/eng/FRA-324153433-QY6\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/ACDI-CIDA.nsf/eng/FRA-324153433-QY6</a></li>\r\n<li><strong>AQOCI</strong>, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2011), Training kit : Promoting Gender Equality from Theory to Practice, p. 53 to 57, <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 18:30:15','2013-09-06 18:30:57',5,'wide','','',NULL,'<p><strong style=\"font-size: 10px;\">Mettre au point votre syst&egrave;me de suivi</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le suivi de votre projet est un processus continu qui vous permet de mesurer votre progr&egrave;s en fonction des objectifs que vous vous &ecirc;tes donn&eacute;s au d&eacute;part. Pour int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH au suivi de votre projet, formulez des indicateurs sp&eacute;cifiques &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH et colligez des donn&eacute;es d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;es par sexe pour l&rsquo;ensemble des indicateurs du projet. Par exemple, enregistrez le nombre de femmes qui participent &agrave; vos formations et recueillez leur feedback sp&eacute;cifique. Dans le cas des m&eacute;dias, comptez le nombre de fois o&ugrave; l&rsquo;on parle de votre th&egrave;me et v&eacute;rifiez si le r&ocirc;le des femmes est pr&eacute;sent&eacute; de mani&egrave;re positive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Le choix des m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Une &eacute;valuation vous permet de d&eacute;terminer si votre projet a atteint ses objectifs; elle peut se faire en cours de projet, &agrave; la fin du projet ou plusieurs ann&eacute;es plus tard afin d&rsquo;en mesurer les effets &agrave; long terme.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation d&rsquo;un projet d&rsquo;engagement du public vise &agrave; mesurer les prises de conscience, les nouveaux apprentissages, les changements de valeurs, d&rsquo;attitudes et de comportements. Si on a bien int&eacute;gr&eacute; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH, cela devrait se refl&eacute;ter dans les &eacute;valuations et dans les perceptions des personnes interrog&eacute;es sur le projet.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Il est difficile de mesurer l&rsquo;impact des projets d&rsquo;engagement du public sur les publics cibles parce que la plupart des projets ont peu de ressources pour faire un suivi &agrave; moyen et long terme aupr&egrave;s des personnes sensibilis&eacute;es. N&eacute;anmoins, la grille suivante donne un aper&ccedil;u du type de commentaires qu&rsquo;on pourrait obtenir lors d&rsquo;une &eacute;valuation qualitative du projet pour en mesurer l&rsquo;impact au niveau de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH:</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<table style=\"height: 470px; width: 537px;\"><colgroup><col width=\"304\" /><col width=\"317\" /></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Prise de conscience</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; J&rsquo;ai compris que je ne vis pas le probl&egrave;me de la m&ecirc;me mani&egrave;re que ma compagne.&raquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Je vois que les femmes du Sud ont plus de difficult&eacute;s que les hommes &agrave; avoir acc&egrave;s &agrave;&hellip; &raquo;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Apprentissage</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; J&rsquo;ai appris que 99% de tous les d&eacute;c&egrave;s maternels surviennent dans les pays en d&eacute;veloppement.&raquo;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Valeurs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Je comprends &agrave; quel point l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; est une valeur fondamentale pour moi.&raquo;&laquo; Je suis indign&eacute;e de constater les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s qui existent encore entre les femmes et les hommes.&raquo;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Attitudes &amp;&nbsp;Comportements</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Je suis r&eacute;solue &agrave; m&rsquo;engager pour sensibiliser diff&eacute;rentes instances de mon CEGEP &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH.&raquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo;Je vais faire du b&eacute;n&eacute;volat dans un centre de femmes.&raquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Dor&eacute;navant, je vais faire valoir mon opinion face &agrave; des commen-taires ou &agrave; des attitudes sexistes. &raquo;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo;Je vais accorder plus d&rsquo;attention aux politiques provinciales en rapport avec l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH.&raquo;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Autres ressources:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">ACDI, &Eacute;galit&eacute; entre les sexes, politiques et outils (2005)&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/ACDI-CIDA.nsf/eng/FRA-324153433-QY6\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/ACDI-CIDA.nsf/eng/FRA-324153433-QY6</a></li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">AQOCI, Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement (2011), Trousse de formation. Promouvoir l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes : la mise en pratique, p. 53-57,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Intégrer l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) à l’évaluation de votre projet','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Survey.jpg','image/jpeg',249484,'2013-09-06 18:30:09','Photo: Robyn Lee','Photo: Robyn Lee',NULL,NULL,NULL,'108',NULL,NULL),(46,NULL,'Integrate gender equality in your project strategy','<p><strong>Designing your awareness-raising activities</strong></p>\r\n<p>Civil society organizations use a range of approaches to reach out to and mobilize Canadians on international solidarity issues. For example: information kiosks, conferences, debates, awareness raising workshops, exhibitions, screenings, theatre, workshops in schools, contests, roleplay and simulations, volunteer activities, etc.</p>\r\n<p>When debating which approach to use, ask yourself whether men and women and boys and girls will be able to participate, understand, express themselves and get involved on an equal footing.</p>\r\n<p>Consider the following issues:</p>\r\n<p>- Is the activity equally accessible to women/girls and men/boys?<br />- Are women/girls and men/boys equally available to participate in the activity?<br />- Does the activity equally appeal to women/girls and men/boys?<br />- Will they be able to equally express themselves during the activity?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Deciding who will be the target of your advocacy campaign</strong></p>\r\n<p>To bring about change we need to challenge our governments and promote our vision of international solidarity. Advocacy is a public mobilization strategy that allows citizens to express their aspirations in a democratic setting.</p>\r\n<p>When planning an advocacy initiative you should do a <strong>power analysis</strong> (see &lsquo;Further resources,&rsquo; below) to determine who your allies and opponents are, who you may be able to convince, and who doesn&rsquo;t yet have an opinion on the issue. You should then work with your allies, respond to your opponents and build support among people and groups who are still undecided.</p>\r\n<p>When doing your power analysis, try to find out what each of these groups thinks of gender equality issues. This will help you determine the likelihood they will support or counter your efforts to promote gender equality and you can then strategize accordingly.</p>\r\n<p>For example, a power analysis could reveal that a member of parliament (MP) is willing to push for legislation related to your advocacy issue, but that they are not aware of women&rsquo;s specific needs and may therefore oppose certain gender equality clauses. Based on this information you can craft a narrative that addresses this lack of information and seeks to overcome these misgivings.</p>\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>PROFILE</td>\r\n<td>STRATEGY</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>The MP does not know much about gender equality</td>\r\n<td>Provide the MP with information about the gender dimensions of the issue</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>The MP is resistant to gender equality</td>\r\n<td>Provide the MP with information about the gender dimensions of the issue AND work with allies to help convince him or her</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A power analysis that incorporates gender equality will help focus your efforts and increase the effectiveness of your campaign, namely by ensuring that you use the right strategies and activities to reach your targets at the right time.</p>\r\n<p>By integrating gender equality in your advocacy initiatives, you will contribute to transforming gender power relations, advancing women&rsquo;s empowerment and promoting social justice.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Further resources:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Oxfam</strong>, Integrating gender in the GROW campaign (internal document)</li>\r\n<li><strong>Oxfam</strong>, Guide to gender mainstreaming in advocacy work (internal document)</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 18:43:05','2013-09-06 18:43:18',5,'wide','','',NULL,'<p><strong>La conception des activit&eacute;s de sensibilisation</strong></p>\r\n<p>Pour changer les choses, il faut interpeller nos gouvernements et promouvoir notre conception de la solidarit&eacute; internationale. Le plaidoyer est une strat&eacute;gie de mobilisation qui permet aux citoyennes et aux citoyens d&rsquo;exprimer leurs aspirations dans un cadre d&eacute;mocratique.</p>\r\n<p>Au moment de planifier une action de plaidoyer, il est bon de mener une <strong>analyse de pouvoir</strong> (voir ci-apr&egrave;s les &laquo; Autres ressources &raquo;) pour identifier vos alli&eacute;-e-s et vos adversaires, qui vous pourriez convaincre et qui n&rsquo;a pas encore d&rsquo;opinion sur la question. Vous devrez alors travailler avec vos alli&eacute;-e-s, r&eacute;pondre &agrave; vos adversaires, et aller chercher l&rsquo;appui des personnes et des groupes encore ind&eacute;cis.</p>\r\n<p>En faisant votre analyse de pouvoir, cherchez &agrave; conna&icirc;tre la position de chacun de ces groupes sur les questions d&rsquo;&Eacute;FH afin de d&eacute;terminer qui est susceptible de soutenir ou de freiner vos efforts pour promouvoir l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH et quelles strat&eacute;gies adopter.</p>\r\n<p>Par exemple, l&rsquo;analyse de pouvoir pourrait r&eacute;v&eacute;ler qu&rsquo;un-e d&eacute;put&eacute;-e est dispos&eacute;-e &agrave; faire &eacute;voluer la l&eacute;gislation en lien avec votre sujet, mais ignore les besoins sp&eacute;cifiques des femmes et risque de s&rsquo;opposer &agrave; certaines dispositions relatives &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH. Vous pourrez donc pr&eacute;parer votre argumentaire en tenant compte de ces points de r&eacute;sistance ou de ce manque d&rsquo;information.</p>\r\n<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<table style=\"height: 124px; width: 589px;\"><colgroup><col width=\"301\" /><col width=\"303\" /></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">PROFILS</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">STRAT&Eacute;GIE</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">L&rsquo;&eacute;lu-e peu inform&eacute;-e sur l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lui fournir de l&rsquo;information sur l&rsquo;aspect &Eacute;FH du dossier</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">L&rsquo;&eacute;lu-e r&eacute;ticent-e ou r&eacute;sistant-e &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lui fournir de l&rsquo;information sur l&rsquo;aspect &Eacute;FH du dossier ET vous associer &agrave; des alli&eacute;-e-s pour le-a convaincre</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Une analyse de pouvoir qui int&egrave;gre l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH vous permettra de mieux concentrer vos efforts et d&rsquo;accro&icirc;tre l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; de votre campagne, en veillant notamment &agrave; appliquer les bonnes strat&eacute;gies aux bonnes cibles au bon moment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">En int&eacute;grant l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; vos initiatives de plaidoyer, vous contribuerez &agrave; transformer les relations de pouvoir entre les sexes, &agrave; promouvoir l&rsquo;autonomisation des femmes et &agrave; favoriser la justice sociale.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Autres ressources:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Oxfam</strong>, <em>Guide sur l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration du genre dans la campagne &laquo; Cultivons &raquo;</em> (document interne)</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Oxfam</strong>,<em> Guide to gender mainstreaming in advocacy work</em> (document interne)</li>\r\n</ul>','Intégrer l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) à la stratégie de votre projet','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Nyala_-_Youth_Rebuilding_Darfur_Volunteer_Project.jpg','image/jpeg',207537,'2013-09-06 18:42:56','Photo: Albert González Farran','Photo: Albert González Farran',NULL,NULL,NULL,'44',NULL,NULL),(47,NULL,'Promote commitment to gender equality within your team','<p><strong>Making time to discuss and raise awareness about gender equality</strong></p>\r\n<p>Gender equality is a shared responsibility. Everyone involved (volunteers, employees, etc.) should feel responsible for ensuring that gender equality gets integrated into the public engagement project and should convey messages that promote equality between women and men.</p>\r\n<p>If project leaders are open and respectful about gender equality, all stakeholders will be inspired. Demonstrate your leadership and commitment to gender equality.</p>\r\n<p>Project leaders should identify opportunities (such as teams meetings) to discuss gender equality with volunteers, allies and partners at different stages of the project. For example you can organize a training session or a discussion on the topic. For more ideas and additional resources, consult the AQOCI training kit <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Promoting Gender Equality from Theory to Practice</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Choosing partners with expertise in gender equality</strong></p>\r\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t feel sufficiently versed in women&rsquo;s rights and gender equality, identify civil society partners who can support or train you. Give preference to civil society organizations that have a proven track record working on gender equality. These organizations are listed on provincial council websites (such as AQOCI&rsquo;s <em>Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement</em>) and on CCIC&rsquo;s website. You can also reach out to women&rsquo;s rights organizations in your province.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 19:01:41','2013-09-06 19:02:15',1,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Prendre le temps de sensibiliser &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</strong></p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;&Eacute;FH est une responsabilit&eacute; partag&eacute;e. Il importe que les personnes impliqu&eacute;es dans la mise en &oelig;uvre du projet d&rsquo;EP (b&eacute;n&eacute;voles, personnel de l&rsquo;organisation, etc.) se sentent responsables d&rsquo;assurer l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH au projet et v&eacute;hiculent des messages qui promeuvent l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes.</p>\r\n<p>L&rsquo;ouverture et le respect envers l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH dont feront preuve les responsables du projet inspireront toutes les parties prenantes. Faites valoir votre leadership et votre engagement envers les principes de l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes.</p>\r\n<p>Les responsables de l&rsquo;EP devraient identifier des moments (comme les r&eacute;unions d&rsquo;&eacute;quipe) o&ugrave; discuter d&rsquo;&Eacute;FH avec les b&eacute;n&eacute;voles, les alli&eacute;-e-s et les partenaires, &agrave; diff&eacute;rentes &eacute;tapes du projet. Vous pouvez, par exemple, organiser une session de formation ou une discussion sur le th&egrave;me. Pour plus d&rsquo;id&eacute;es et de ressources, consultez la trousse de l&rsquo;AQOCI, <a href=\"http://www.aqoci.qc.ca/IMG/pdf/trousse_efh_vang.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Promouvoir l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; et entre les femmes et les hommes &ndash; la mise en pratique</a>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Le choix de partenaires sp&eacute;cialis&eacute;s</strong></p>\r\n<p>Si vous sentez que vous ne ma&icirc;trisez pas suffisamment l&rsquo;argumentaire sur les droits des femmes et l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes, identifiez des partenaires de la soci&eacute;t&eacute; civile qui soient capables de vous appuyer ou de vous former. Privil&eacute;giez des OSC qui ont d&eacute;montr&eacute; leur expertise en &Eacute;FH. Ces organismes sont r&eacute;f&eacute;renc&eacute;s sur les sites Internet des conseils provinciaux comme l&rsquo;AQOCI <em>(Comit&eacute; qu&eacute;b&eacute;cois femmes et d&eacute;veloppement)</em> et du CCCI au niveau pancanadien. Vous pouvez aussi solliciter des organismes de promotion des droits des femmes de votre province.</p>','Promouvoir l’engagement envers l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH) au sein de votre équipe','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Paper_dolls.jpg','image/jpeg',5597993,'2013-09-06 19:01:04','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'38',NULL,NULL),(48,NULL,'Additional Resources on gender equality','<p><strong>Resources on gender equality:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/acdi-cida.nsf/eng/JUD-31194519-KBD\" target=\"_blank\">Gender analysis (CIDA)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_ethics_gender_equality_study.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Gender Equality, Promise to Practice (CCIC)</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://icad-cisd.com/pdf/Gender_Analysis_for_Project_Planners_EN_FINAL.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Gender Analysis for Project Planners (Interagency Coalition on AIDS and Development)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aid.govt.nz/sites/default/files/Gender%20Analysis%20Guideline_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Integrating Gender Equality and Women&rsquo;s Empowerment into an Activity, Programme or Policy (New Zealand Aid Programme)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.genderatwork.org/sites/genderatwork.org/files/resources/Action_Learning_for_Gender_Equality-FINAL-3_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Action Learning for Gender Equality (Gender at Work)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/acdi-cida.nsf/eng/EMA-2181431-QCF\" target=\"_blank\">CIDA resources on equality between men and women (CIDA)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.ca/sites/default/files/Ox-Gender-Toolkit_web-final_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">The Power of Gender-Just Organizations (Oxfam Canada)&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unifem.org/gender_issues/millennium_development_goals/\" target=\"_blank\">Millennium Development Goals (UN Women)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/vfile/upload/4/document/1105/BB17Francophone_webresources_final_onlineversion1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">20 Key Gender Websites in French (BRIDGE)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/vfile/upload/4/document/1105/BB16Francophone_nonwebresources_french_onlineversion.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Annotated bibliography</a> on 20 key francophone resources on gender and development (BRIDGE) <em>(in French only)</em>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Resources on public engagement:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Toward Good Practice in Public Engagement (CCIC)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://oxfam.qc.ca/sites/oxfam.qc.ca/files/au-dela-de-la-pancarte.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Beyond the Placard: A guide to creative public engagement (Oxfam-Qu&eacute;bec)</a> <em>(in French only)</em>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Resources on communications:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.awid.org/eng/AWID-s-Publications/Gender-Equality-New-Technologies\" target=\"_blank\">Gender Equality and New Technologies (AWID)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.mondefemmes.be/genre-developpement-plan-site_outils-animations_photo-langage.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Photo-language (Le monde selon les femmes)</a> <em>(in French only)&nbsp;</em></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://waccglobal.org/images/stories/media_and_gender_monitor/Issue-23/mgm23.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Media and Gender Monitor (World Alliance of Christian Communication)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.fao.org/docrep/014/am319e/am319e00.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Communicating Gender for Rural Development (FAO)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://suco.org/suco/wp-content/themes/twentyten/images/expo-photos/800x600.html\" target=\"_blank\">Portraits of Women in Action (SUCO)</a> <em>(in French only)&nbsp;</em></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acic-caci.org/storage/EthicalImgSlideShw.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">The South through the Northern Eye: Understanding how images of the South influence public opinion (ACIC)&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_ethics_focus_on_ethics.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Focus on Ethics: Addressing Tensions in Choosing Fundraising Images (CCIC)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://policy-practice.oxfam.org.uk/publications/search?q=*;q1=publications;q2=Gender%20%26%20Development%20Volume%2015%20Issue%203;x1=page_type;x2=journal\" target=\"_blank\">Gender and Development Journal, Media Issue</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Thematic issues:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.ca/sites/default/files/imce/towards-gender-justice.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Towards Gender Justice : Mainstreaming a Gender Perspective in Farmer&rsquo;s Organisations (Oxfam Canada)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://ccrweb.ca/en/pathways-gender-justice-handbook-htm-format\" target=\"_blank\">Pathways to Gender Justice Handbook (Canadian Council for Refugees)&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://oxfam.qc.ca/sites/oxfam.qc.ca/files/10realities.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">10 Facts About Gender Inequality in the World of Agriculture in West Africa (Oxfam)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/gender/mainstreaming/en/MDG.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Engendering the millennium development goals on health (WHO)&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://plan-international.org/girls/pdfs/2012-report/The-State-of-the-World-s-Girls-Learning-for-Life-Plan-International-2012.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Because I am a Girl: The State of the World&rsquo;s Girls 2012 (Plan International)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Other:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cininet.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/230111-implementation-toolkit-en-web.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Putting the Istanbul Principles into Practice (Open Forum for CSO Development Effectiveness)</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'resources','2013-09-06 19:45:44','2013-09-06 19:45:57',5,'wide','','',NULL,'<p><strong>Ressources sur l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/acdi-cida.nsf/fra/JUD-31194519-KBD\" target=\"_blank\">Analyse comparative entre les sexes</a>&nbsp;(ACDI)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/f/docs/002_ethics_gender_equality_study.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">L&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes, de la promesse &agrave; la pratique</a>&nbsp;(CCCI)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://icad-cisd.com/content/fr/component/content/article/110-gender-analysis-forproject-planners\" target=\"_blank\">Analyse sexosp&eacute;cifique &agrave; l&rsquo;intention des planificateurs de projet,</a>&nbsp;(Coalition interagence Sida et D&eacute;veloppement)&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.aid.govt.nz/sites/default/files/Gender%20Analysis%20Guideline_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Principaux cadres de r&eacute;f&eacute;rence en analyse de genre ainsi que leurs forces et leurs faiblesses</a>&nbsp;(Programme d&rsquo;aide de la Nouvelle-Z&eacute;lande, en anglais seulement)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.genderatwork.org/sites/genderatwork.org/files/resources/Action_Learning_for_Gender_Equality-FINAL-3_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Action Learning for Gender Equality</a>&nbsp;(Gender at Work)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acdi-cida.gc.ca/acdi-cida/acdi-cida.nsf/fra/EMA-2181431-QCF\" target=\"_blank\">Liste de ressources sur le genre, ACDI&nbsp;</a></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.ca/sites/default/files/Ox-Gender-Toolkit_web-final_0.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">The Power of Gender-Just Organizations</a>&nbsp;(Oxfam Canada)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.unifem.org/gender_issues/millennium_development_goals/\" target=\"_blank\">ONU-Femmes, Objectifs du Mill&eacute;naire pour le d&eacute;veloppement</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/vfile/upload/4/document/1105/BB17Francophone_webresources_final_onlineversion1.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">20 sites francophones cl&eacute;s sur le genre, BRIDGE</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.bridge.ids.ac.uk/vfile/upload/4/document/1105/BB16Francophone_nonwebresources_french_onlineversion.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">20 ressources francophones cl&eacute;s sur genre et d&eacute;veloppement, BRIDGE</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Ressources sur l&rsquo;engagement du public:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/fr/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Vers de bonnes pratiques en engagement du public</a>&nbsp;(CCCI)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://oxfam.qc.ca/sites/oxfam.qc.ca/files/au-dela-de-la-pancarte.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Au-del&agrave; de la pancarte : guide sur les pratiques cr&eacute;atives d&rsquo;engagement du public</a>&nbsp;(Oxfam-Qu&eacute;bec)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Ressources sur les communications:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.awid.org/fre/Nos-publications/Egalite-des-Sexes-et-Nouvelles-Technologies\" target=\"_blank\">&Eacute;galit&eacute; des sexes et nouvelles technologies</a>&nbsp;(AWID)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.mondefemmes.be/genre-developpement-plan-site_outils-animations_photo-langage.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Le Photo-langage, Monde de femmes</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://waccglobal.org/images/stories/media_and_gender_monitor/Issue-23/mgm23.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Media and Gender Monitor</a>&nbsp;(World Alliance of Christian Communication)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.fao.org/docrep/014/am319f/am319f00.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Communiquer le genre pour le d&eacute;veloppement rural</a>&nbsp;(FAO)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://suco.org/suco/wp-content/themes/twentyten/images/expo-photos/800x600.html\" target=\"_blank\">Portraits de femmes en action</a>&nbsp;(SUCO)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.acic-caci.org/storage/EthicalImgSlideShw.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">The South through the Northern Eye: Understanding how images of the South influence public opinion,</a>&nbsp;Conseil atlantique pour la coop&eacute;ration international (CACI)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/fr/what_we_do/002_ethics_focus_f.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Question d&rsquo;&eacute;thique : surmonter les d&eacute;saccords sur le choix des images destin&eacute;es aux collectes de fonds,</a>&nbsp;<span id=\"docs-internal-guid-74bd9be2-f4cb-daff-dc05-32c6acd59c43\"><span>Conseil canadien de coop&eacute;ration internationale (CCCI)</span></span></li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://policy-practice.oxfam.org.uk/publications/search?q=*;q1=publications;q2=Gender%20%26%20Development%20Volume%2015%20Issue%203;x1=page_type;x2=journal\" target=\"_blank\">Gender and Development Journal, Media Issue, 2007</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Th&eacute;matiques:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.oxfam.ca/sites/default/files/imce/towards-gender-justice.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Towards Gender Justice : Mainstreaming a Gender Perspective in Farmers&rsquo; Organisations</a>&nbsp;(Oxfam Canada)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://ccrweb.ca/documents/guidegenre-htm\" target=\"_blank\">Guide des avenues pour la justice entre les genres</a>&nbsp;<span id=\"docs-internal-guid-74bd9be2-f4c9-7158-034c-24fbcedcbdab\"><span>(Conseil canadien pour les r&eacute;fugi&eacute;s)</span></span>&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://oxfam.qc.ca/sites/oxfam.qc.ca/files/10realities.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">10 r&eacute;alit&eacute;s sur les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes dans le monde agricole en Afrique de l&rsquo;Ouest</a>&nbsp;(Oxfam)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://www.who.int/gender/mainstreaming/en/MDG.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Engendering the millennium development goals on health</a>&nbsp;(OMS)</li>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://plan-international.org/filles/global/publications/campaigns/biag-2012-report-french\" target=\"_blank\">Parce que je suis une fille : la situation des filles dans le monde 2012</a>&nbsp;Plan International&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Autre:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a href=\"http://cercle.lu/download/implementationtoolkit.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Guide de mise en &oelig;uvre des Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul</a>&nbsp;<span id=\"docs-internal-guid-74bd9be2-f4c8-aeeb-d7e9-ba5e6d71fdc3\"><span>Forum ouvert pour les OCS sur l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; du d&eacute;veloppement)</span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Ressources additionnelles sur l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH)','ressources','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Girl_reaching.jpg','image/jpeg',217547,'2013-09-06 19:45:38','Photo: Erik Törner','Photo: Erik Törner',NULL,NULL,NULL,'172',NULL,NULL),(49,NULL,'Checklist for gender equality integration','<p>A public engagement program, project, activity or campaign that successfully integrates gender equality will:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Explain what gender inequality has to do with the issue;</li>\r\n<li>Denounce gender inequality and suggest specific actions to remedy the situation;</li>\r\n<li>Provide sex-disaggregated data in order to convey women and men&rsquo;s different lived experiences;</li>\r\n<li>Reach out to both men and women and ensure that women and men&rsquo;s voices are equally heard.</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-06 19:53:31','2013-09-06 19:53:59',5,'small','','',NULL,'<p>Un programme, un projet, une activit&eacute; ou une campagne d&rsquo;engagement du public qui int&egrave;gre l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>pr&eacute;sente les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes par rapport au th&egrave;me du projet d&rsquo;EP;</li>\r\n<li>d&eacute;nonce ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s et propose des gestes ou des actions sp&eacute;cifiques pour y rem&eacute;dier;</li>\r\n<li>pr&eacute;sente de l&rsquo;information diff&eacute;renci&eacute;e par sexe, ce qui permet de communiquer les r&eacute;alit&eacute;s diff&eacute;rentes des femmes et des hommes;</li>\r\n<li>s&rsquo;assure que la d&eacute;marche d&rsquo;engagement du public touchera autant les femmes que les hommes et fera entendre la voix des unes et des autres.</li>\r\n</ul>','Liste de contrôle pour l’intégration de l’égalité entre les femmes et les hommes (ÉFH)','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Youthsupportingwomensleadership.jpg','image/jpeg',1017800,'2013-09-06 19:53:20','Group of OCIC Global Changemakers. Photo: Anice Wong','Ce groupe de l’OCIC veut changer le monde. Photo: Anice Wong',NULL,NULL,NULL,'30',NULL,NULL),(50,NULL,'Four levels of engagement','<p>There are different degrees to which you can integrate gender equality in a public engagement initiative:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><strong>Level 0:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Does not address inequalities between women and men</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Level 1: Aware</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Provides the opportunity for both women and men to speak up on the issue</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Level 2: Enlightened</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reveals inequalities between women and men</li>\r\n<li>Highlights the causes and consequences of these inequalities</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Level 3: Committed</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reveals inequalities between women and men</li>\r\n<li>Highlights the causes and consequences of these inequalities</li>\r\n<li>Suggests specific actions to reduce these inequalities, both in terms of individual behaviour and public policies.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>The following examples illustrate the different degrees to which you can integrate gender equality in public engagement.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Level 0:</strong><em> Does not address inequalities between women and men</em></p>\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s imagine a fictional campaign to adopt a treaty to eliminate certain kinds of weapons. The campaign does not address gender equality if it does not use sex-disaggregated data in the campaign narrative, and does not explain how women and men and boys and girls are specifically affected by the existence and use of these weapons.</p>\r\n<p>As such, the campaign can&rsquo;t recommend measures to address the specific needs of women and men in relation to the circulation, trade and use of these weapons in the new treaty.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Level 1: Aware</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Provides the opportunity for both women and men to speak up on the topic</em></p>\r\n<p>Let&rsquo;s imagine a fictional conference on working conditions and trade union freedoms in a country in the South.<br />You can say that the conference provides the opportunity for both women and men to speak up on the topic if the host organization has made sure to invite both male and female speakers from the South in order to hear their respective points of view.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Level 2: Enlightened</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Reveals inequalities between women and men</em></p>\r\n<p>+ Highlights the causes and consequences of these inequalities</p>\r\n<p>A coalition is preparing a series of activities on climate change and drafts a document to further explain the issue. You can say that the document is &ldquo;enlightened&rdquo; if:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It reveals the inequalities between women and men in the face of climate change.</li>\r\n<li>It includes materials on the impacts of climate change on women&rsquo;s living conditions and access to resources such as water and land.</li>\r\n<li>It explains why women and girls are more vulnerable in the face of climate change and makes recommendations using examples from civil society projects.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Level 3: Committed</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Reveals inequalities between women and men</em><br /><em>+ Highlights the causes and consequences of these inequalities</em><br /><em>+ Suggests courses of action to reduce these inequalities, both in terms of individual behaviour and public policies.</em></p>\r\n<p>A human rights organization organizes an awareness raising campaign on forced marriage and the right to sexual and reproductive health.</p>\r\n<p>You can say that the campaign is &ldquo;committed&rdquo; if:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>It reveals gender inequalities.</strong> Violations of the right to sexual and reproductive health occur. In developing countries, more than 60 million women aged 20-24 are married or living with a partner before the age of 18.</li>\r\n<li><strong>It highlights the causes and consequences of these inequalities:</strong><br />\r\n<blockquote><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Causes:</em></span> Poverty (one less mouth to feed), discrimination against women and minorities (women don&rsquo;t have the same value as men), the excuse of wanting to protect young girls from sexual violence or to safeguard the honour of a village or a family if a young girl has had sex outside of wedlock and becomes pregnant, etc.<br /><br /><span style=\"font-size: 10px; text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Consequences:</em></span> Maternal and child mortality, lagging school enrolment and increased drop-out rates, abuse, rape, poverty, domestic violence.</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>It suggests specific actions to take:</strong><br />\r\n<blockquote><em><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Individual behaviour:</span><br /><br /></em>Sign a petition addressed to the Minister of Women&rsquo;s Affairs and the Minister of Justice in targeted countries.<br /><br />Sign a petition addressed to global leaders who are meeting to discuss the ICPD+20 and the post-2015 development agenda.<br /><br />Show your solidarity with organizations working to end child marriage in targeted countries by sending drawings and messages of support.<br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Public policies:</em></span> Improve access to education for boys and girls, apply existing laws to ensure that the rights of children and women are respected, raise awareness of all aspects of sexuality, provide access to information and family planning services, and decriminalize abortion.</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-06 20:24:03','2013-09-06 20:24:25',5,'tall','','',NULL,'<p>Une activit&eacute; d&rsquo;engagement du public peut int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes &agrave; diff&eacute;rents niveaux:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 0:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;aborde pas les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 1: Conscient-e</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Donne la parole aux femmes et aux hommes sur le sujet</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 2: &Eacute;clair&eacute;-e</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>R&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes.</li>\r\n<li>Fait ressortir les causes et les cons&eacute;quences de ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 3: Engag&eacute;-e</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>R&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes</li>\r\n<li>Fait ressortir les causes et les cons&eacute;quences de ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</li>\r\n<li>Propose des pistes d&rsquo;action pour r&eacute;duire ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s, au niveau personnel et &agrave; celui des politiques publiques</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Les exemples pr&eacute;sent&eacute;s ci-dessous illustrent les diff&eacute;rents niveaux d&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH en engagement du public.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 0:</strong><em> N&rsquo;aborde pas les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes</em></p>\r\n<p>Imaginons une campagne fictive sur l&rsquo;adoption d&rsquo;un trait&eacute; pour &eacute;liminer certains types d&rsquo;armes. La campagne ne tient pas compte de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH si aucune des donn&eacute;es utilis&eacute;es n&rsquo;est d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;e par sexe et si on ne pr&eacute;cise pas la mani&egrave;re diff&eacute;rente dont les femmes et les hommes, les filles et les gar&ccedil;ons sont touch&eacute;s par l&rsquo;existence et l&rsquo;emploi des armes en question.</p>\r\n<p>La campagne ne peut donc pas recommander, pour le futur trait&eacute;, des mesures qui r&eacute;pondraient aux besoins sp&eacute;cifiques des femmes et des hommes quant &agrave; la circulation, au commerce et &agrave; l&rsquo;usage de ces armes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 1: Conscient-e</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Donne la parole aux femmes et aux hommes sur le sujet</em></p>\r\n<p>Imaginons une conf&eacute;rence sur les conditions de travail et les libert&eacute;s syndicales dans un pays du Sud.<br />On peut dire que cette conf&eacute;rence donne la parole aux femmes et aux hommes si l&rsquo;organisation h&ocirc;te a pris soin d&rsquo;inviter des conf&eacute;renci&egrave;res et des conf&eacute;renciers du Sud afin de faire entendre les points de vue f&eacute;minins et masculins sur le sujet.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 2: &Eacute;clair&eacute;-e</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>R&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes</em></p>\r\n<p>+ Fait ressortir les causes et les cons&eacute;quences de ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</p>\r\n<p>Une coalition pr&eacute;pare une s&eacute;rie d&rsquo;activit&eacute;s sur le th&egrave;me des changements climatiques et r&eacute;dige un document pour approfondir le sujet. On peut dire que ce document est &laquo; &eacute;clair&eacute; &raquo; si :</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Il r&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les homes face au probl&egrave;me des changements climatiques.</li>\r\n<li>Il contient plusieurs encadr&eacute;s sur l&rsquo;impact des changements climatiques sur les conditions de vie des femmes et leur acc&egrave;s aux ressources comme l&rsquo;eau et la terre.</li>\r\n<li>Il explique pourquoi les femmes et les filles sont plus vuln&eacute;rables face aux changements climatiques et propose certaines solutions, illustr&eacute;es par des projets d&rsquo;organisations de la soci&eacute;t&eacute; civile.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Niveau 3: Engag&eacute;-e</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>R&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s entre les femmes et les hommes</em><br /><em>+ Fait ressortir les causes et les cons&eacute;quences de ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s</em><br /><em>+ Propose des pistes d&rsquo;action pour r&eacute;duire ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s, au niveau personnel et &agrave; celui des politiques publiques.</em></p>\r\n<p>Une organisation de d&eacute;fense des droits de la personne organise une campagne de sensibilisation sur le mariage forc&eacute; et les droits en mati&egrave;re de sant&eacute; sexuelle et reproductive.</p>\r\n<p>On peut dire que cette campagne est &laquo; engag&eacute;e &raquo; si:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Elle r&eacute;v&egrave;le les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s.</strong> Les violations des droits sexuels et reproductifs existent. Dans les pays en d&eacute;veloppement, plus de 60 millions de femmes aujourd&rsquo;hui &acirc;g&eacute;es de 20 &agrave; 24 ans &eacute;taient mari&eacute;es ou en concubinage avant l&rsquo;&acirc;ge de 18 ans.</li>\r\n<li>\r\n<blockquote><strong>Elle fait ressortir les causes et les cons&eacute;quences de ces in&eacute;galit&eacute;s:<br /><br /></strong><em>Causes:</em> La pauvret&eacute; (une bouche de moins &agrave; nourrir), la discrimination envers les femmes et les minorit&eacute;s (les femmes n&rsquo;ont pas la m&ecirc;me valeur que les hommes), et le pr&eacute;texte de prot&eacute;ger la jeune fille (des violences sexuelles) et de sauvegarder l&rsquo;honneur d&rsquo;un village ou d&rsquo;une famille (au cas o&ugrave; elle aurait des relations hors mariage et deviendrait enceinte), etc.<br /><br /><em>Cons&eacute;quences:</em> mortalit&eacute; maternelle et infantile, sous-scolarisation ou d&eacute;scolarisation, mauvais traitements, viols, pauvret&eacute;, violence conjugale.</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Elle propose des pistes d&rsquo;action:<br /><br /></strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Comportement personnel:</em></span><br /><br />Signer une p&eacute;tition adress&eacute;e aux ministres de la Promotion de la femme et de la Justice des pays cibl&eacute;s.<br /><br />Signer une p&eacute;tition adress&eacute;e aux leaders mondiaux qui se rencontrent pour discuter de la CIPD+20 et de l&rsquo;agenda du d&eacute;veloppement apr&egrave;s 2015.<br /><br />Montrer notre solidarit&eacute; avec les organisations qui travaillent pour faire cesser la pratique des mariages d&rsquo;enfants dans des pays cibl&eacute;s, en envoyant des dessins et des messages d&rsquo;appui.<br /><br /><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em>Politiques publiques:</em></span> Plus d&rsquo;&eacute;ducation des gar&ccedil;ons et des filles, application des lois existantes pour faire respecter les droits des enfants et des femmes, sensibilisation &agrave; tous les aspects de la sexualit&eacute;, acc&egrave;s &agrave; l&rsquo;information et &agrave; des services de planning familial, d&eacute;criminalisation de l&rsquo;avortement.</li>\r\n</ul>','Quatre niveaux d’engagement','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'JimmyChicaiza-5.jpg','image/jpeg',910739,'2013-09-06 20:23:55','Photo: Jimmy Chicaiza','Photo: Jimmy Chicaiza',NULL,NULL,NULL,'64',NULL,NULL),(51,NULL,'Applying our theory of change to an experiential youth exchange program','<p dir=\"ltr\"><em><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A8S_TwLzFC8mK0rwE7HZDKG2vviHnRZpuZ3i_UHMsh0/edit\">The following is a reflection on and application of the theory of change developed by the How Change Happens Knowledge Hub.</a></em></p>\r\n<p>This case study explores how the Theory of Change can be used as a tool to identify assumptions and gaps in our public engagement interventions. I worked with a volunteer program that engages young Canadians in learning about international development and related issues.</p>\r\n<p><span>Through the program, the young people learn a lot about issues affecting communities in Canada and other countries. They also develop skills like critical thinking and personal reflection through group educational activities, and debriefing their experiences with the supervisors and other participants (</span><strong>personal change</strong><span>). They work for six months on a cross-cultural team, so they get better at working cross-culturally and making decisions with groups (</span><strong>relational change</strong><span>). Many develop an understanding of power and privilege that helps them to understand their choices more critically (</span><strong>active global citizenship</strong><span>).</span></p>\r\n<p><span>The program doesn\'t usually engage directly with making change to structures (</span><strong>societal change</strong><span>), because it is a relatively short-term engagement. The philosophy of many people who work in the program is that the youth who finish it will go on to do work at the societal level. &nbsp;While anecdotally, this is often true, it is not always easy to demonstrate how big a role their participation in the program played in influencing those choices.</span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Questions for reflection:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Does helping young people to develop skills, knowledge and attitudes lead to longer-term engagement in work at the societal level?</li>\r\n<li>Are there interventions needed to make a bridge from the personal and relational change to societal change?</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 20:39:37','2013-09-06 21:33:37',3,'large','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\"><em><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A8S_TwLzFC8mK0rwE7HZDKG2vviHnRZpuZ3i_UHMsh0/edit\">Ce qui suit est une r&eacute;flexion sur l&rsquo;application de la th&eacute;orie du changement, pr&eacute;par&eacute;e par le P&ocirc;le de connaissances &laquo; Comment survient le changement &raquo;.</a></em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cette &eacute;tude de cas examine la fa&ccedil;on de recourir &agrave; la Th&eacute;orie du changement pour identifier les hypoth&egrave;ses et les failles dans nos interventions d&rsquo;engagement du public. J&rsquo;ai travaill&eacute; avec un programme b&eacute;n&eacute;vole qui mobilise de jeunes canadien-ne-s pour les sensibiliser aux enjeux du d&eacute;veloppement international et &agrave; des probl&egrave;mes connexes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ce programme donne beaucoup d&rsquo;information aux jeunes sur des probl&egrave;mes qui touchent des collectivit&eacute;s au Canada et &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger. Il d&eacute;veloppe aussi la pens&eacute;e critique et la r&eacute;flexion personnelle gr&acirc;ce &agrave; des activit&eacute;s &eacute;ducatives en groupe et &agrave; des exercices de retour sur l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience [<em>d&eacute;briefing</em>] avec des superviseur-e-s et avec les autres participant-e-s (<strong>changement personnel</strong>). Les jeunes travaillent six mois dans une &eacute;quipe transculturelle, de sorte qu&rsquo;ils apprennent &agrave; travailler de mani&egrave;re transculturelle et &agrave; prendre des d&eacute;cisions en groupe (<strong>changement relationnel</strong>). Plusieurs en viennent &agrave; comprendre ce que sont le pouvoir et les privil&egrave;ges, ce qui les aide &agrave; examiner leurs d&eacute;cisions d&rsquo;un &oelig;il plus critique (<strong>citoyennet&eacute; globale active</strong>).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le programme ne vise pas directement &agrave; changer les structures (<strong>changement soci&eacute;tal</strong>) parce qu&rsquo;il s&rsquo;agit plut&ocirc;t d&rsquo;un engagement &agrave; court terme. Les gens qui travaillent au programme ont pour principe que les jeunes qui font l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience vont continuer de cheminer et travailler &eacute;ventuellement au niveau soci&eacute;tal. M&ecirc;me si on trouve des cas isol&eacute;s pour confirmer la chose, il n&rsquo;est pas toujours facile d&rsquo;apporter la preuve que le programme a jou&eacute; un r&ocirc;le dans les choix faits par ces jeunes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Est-ce que le fait d&rsquo;aider les jeunes &agrave; d&eacute;velopper leurs habilet&eacute;s, leurs connaissances et leurs attitudes conduit &agrave; un engagement &agrave; long terme au niveau soci&eacute;tal?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Y a-t-il des interventions qui s&rsquo;imposent pour faire le pont entre le changement personnel et relationnel et le changement soci&eacute;tal?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Appliquer notre théorie du changement à un programme expérimental d’échange jeunesse','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'CWY_Program.JPG','image/jpeg',2760325,'2013-09-06 21:14:58','Photo: Zoë Gross','Photo: Zoë Gross',NULL,NULL,NULL,'18',NULL,NULL),(52,NULL,'Applying our theory of change to fair trade procurement','<p dir=\"ltr\"><em><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A8S_TwLzFC8mK0rwE7HZDKG2vviHnRZpuZ3i_UHMsh0/edit\">The following is a reflection on and application of the theory of change developed by the How Change Happens Knowledge Hub.</a></em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fair Trade Manitoba, a program of the Manitoba Council for International Cooperation (MCIC), works with various institutions, including local and provincial governments, schools, and crown corporations, as they discover, consider, plan for, and take action on fair trade procurement and policies. Over the past five years we have worked with approximately 15 groups that are engaged in different ways and have differing levels of commitment with the fair trade movement.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">For some organizations and individuals, the concept of fair trade and the connection with Fair Trade Manitoba are quite new, and they come to us seeking information (<strong>point of entry</strong>). For other organizations, green or social procurement is already accepted as part of their mandate, and key individuals within their institution are taking leadership to move from intention to action. We try our best to connect with organizations that are in the process of exploring these options to ensure that fair trade is considered as a way that they can live out that mandate.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The process of changing practices and policies with regard to fair trade is a slow one, often taking months or years. A common challenge is finding a way to move fair trade from a &ldquo;back-burner&rdquo; issue to a &ldquo;front-burner&rdquo; issue.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Fair Trade Manitoba&rsquo;s role is to try to help people make emotional connections with the issues through live presentations (<strong>personal change</strong>); build relationships and connect organizations to allies and brokers (<strong>relational change</strong>); and assist with face-to-face meetings with decision makers (<strong>societal change</strong>). Often this means just patiently keeping in contact.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some organizations will change their practices because of the work of specific individuals with a strong belief in the philosophy of fair trade. This is a point where our work builds on the work of other organizations who have helped these individuals become active global citizens (<strong>active global citizenship</strong>). Others struggle with concerns about budget, doubts about fair trade&rsquo;s credibility, and the idea of imposing a policy that is seen to restrict purchasing decisions.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Ultimately we believe the organizations that implement procedures and policies are contributing to more sustainable futures for producers (<strong>outcomes</strong>).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions for reflection:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">What steps can we take to encourage those who are struggling with budget, credibility and &ldquo;imposing&rdquo; a policy, to help them see the big picture?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Does this type of policy change make a difference to the individuals within the organization? Does it engage them in a cycle of transformation, or is change only happening within the key decision makers</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">What interventions are the most effective?</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 20:47:42','2013-09-06 21:34:02',3,'wide','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\"><em><a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1A8S_TwLzFC8mK0rwE7HZDKG2vviHnRZpuZ3i_UHMsh0/edit\">Ce qui suit est une r&eacute;flexion et une application de la Th&eacute;orie du changement, pr&eacute;par&eacute;e par le P&ocirc;le de connaissances &laquo; Comment survient le changement &raquo;.</a></em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Fair Trade Manitoba</em>, programme du Conseil manitobain pour la coop&eacute;ration internationale (MCIC), travaille avec diverses institutions, notamment les gouvernements locaux et provincial, des &eacute;coles et des soci&eacute;t&eacute;s de la Couronne, pour les accompagner dans la d&eacute;couverte, l&rsquo;examen, la planification et la mise en &oelig;uvre de politiques d&rsquo;approvisionnement en produits issus du commerce &eacute;quitable. Au cours des cinq derni&egrave;res ann&eacute;es, nous avons travaill&eacute; avec une quinzaine de groupes qui se trouvent &agrave; diff&eacute;rents niveaux de mobilisation et d&rsquo;engagement par rapport au mouvement du commerce &eacute;quitable.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Pour certaines organisations et certains individus, l&rsquo;id&eacute;e du commerce &eacute;quitable et le lien avec <em>Fair Trade Manitoba</em> sont tout &agrave; fait nouveaux et ils viennent nous voir pour obtenir de l&rsquo;information (<strong>point d&rsquo;entr&eacute;e</strong>). Pour d&rsquo;autres organisations, l&rsquo;approvisionnement vert ou socialement judicieux fait d&eacute;j&agrave; partie de leur mandat, et des responsables de l&rsquo;institution prennent l&rsquo;initiative de passer &agrave; l&rsquo;action. Nous faisons de notre mieux pour faire le lien avec les organisations qui explorent ces options afin qu&rsquo;elles consid&egrave;rent le commerce &eacute;quitable comme un moyen pour elles de respecter leur mandat. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le processus de changement des fa&ccedil;ons de faire et des politiques par rapport au commerce &eacute;quitable demande du temps, souvent des mois ou des ann&eacute;es. Le d&eacute;fi consiste fr&eacute;quemment &agrave; faire passer le dossier du commerce &eacute;quitable du second plan au premier plan.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Fair Trade Manitoba</em> a pour r&ocirc;le d&rsquo;aider les gens &agrave; &eacute;tablir un lien affectif avec les enjeux au moyen d&rsquo;expos&eacute;s faits en personne (<strong>changement personnel</strong>); &agrave; nouer des relations et &agrave; mettre les organisations en lien avec des alli&eacute;s et avec des courtiers (<strong>changement relationnel</strong>); et &agrave; donner un coup de main en rencontrant personnellement les d&eacute;cideurs (<strong>changement soci&eacute;tal</strong>). Souvent, il s&rsquo;agit d&rsquo;&ecirc;tre patient et de rester en contact.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Certaines organisations vont changer leur fa&ccedil;on de faire par suite du travail de quelques personnes qui sont profond&eacute;ment acquises aux principes du commerce &eacute;quitable. Sur ce point, notre travail peut tabler sur ce qui a &eacute;t&eacute; accompli par d&rsquo;autres organisations qui ont aid&eacute; ces personnes &agrave; acc&eacute;der &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; globale active. D&rsquo;autres organisations doivent composer avec des inqui&eacute;tudes relatives au budget, des doutes sur la cr&eacute;dibilit&eacute; du commerce &eacute;quitable et l&rsquo;id&eacute;e d&rsquo;imposer une politique qui semble limiter la libert&eacute; des responsables des achats.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">En fin de compte, nous sommes convaincus que les organisations qui adoptent des politiques et des proc&eacute;dures d&rsquo;approvisionnement &eacute;quitable contribuent &agrave; assurer un avenir plus durable aux producteurs (<strong>r&eacute;sultats</strong>).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\"><span>Qu&rsquo;est-ce que nous pouvons faire pour offrir une perspective d&rsquo;ensemble aux organisations qui ont des probl&egrave;mes relativement &agrave; leur budget, &agrave; la cr&eacute;dibilit&eacute; du commerce &eacute;quitable, ou qui h&eacute;sitent &agrave; s&rsquo;imposer une politique d&rsquo;achats?</span></li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\"><span>Ce type de changement de politique change-t-il quelque chose pour les personnes &agrave; l&rsquo;int&eacute;rieur de l&rsquo;organisation? Est-ce qu&rsquo;il les fait entrer dans un cycle de transformation, ou est-ce que le changement ne concerne que les principaux d&eacute;cideurs?</span></li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\"><span>Quelles sont les interventions qui sont les plus efficaces? </span></li>\r\n</ul>','Appliquer notre théorie du changement à l’approvisionnement auprès du commerce équitable','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fair_Trade_Procurement_4.JPG','image/jpeg',1129465,'2013-09-06 21:21:20','Photo: Dustin Leader','Photo: Dustin Leader',NULL,NULL,NULL,'138',NULL,NULL),(53,NULL,'Reflection questions for integrating gender equality','<p>Reflection Questions for Integrating Gender Equality in Public Engagement</p>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #1 : Integrate gender equality at the project planning stage</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choosing and analyzing your topic</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I do a gender analysis to collect sex-disaggregated data?</li>\r\n<li>Did this data help me understand and explain how women and men experience the issue differently?</li>\r\n<li>In the terms of reference for the background research, did I specify the need to collect and analyze information on how the issue affects women and men differently?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Defining your objectives</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>Gender mainstreaming:</em> Did I include gender equality in the framing of all project objectives?</li>\r\n<li><em>Specific objectives on gender equality:</em> Did I include a specific objective on gender equality in addition to other project objectives?</li>\r\n<li><em>Gender mainstreaming and stand alone work on gender equality:</em> Did I decide to do both?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing your indicators</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I design my indicators in such a way as to gather sex-disaggregated data (ex: number of women and men, percentage of women and men, etc.)?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #2 : Integrate gender equality in your project strategy</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Designing your awareness raising activities</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Were the project activities equally accessible to women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities take into account the availability of women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities equally appeal to women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities offer the opportunity for women/girls and men/boys to equally express themselves?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Deciding who your advocacy campaign will target</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I do a power analysis to determine who was likely to support or oppose the project&rsquo;s efforts to promote gender equality?</li>\r\n<li>Did I organize specific activities to raise awareness and convince elected officials who were less informed or had misgivings about gender equality?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><strong>BEST PRACTICE #3 : Raise awareness and commitment to gender equality within your team</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Making time to discuss and raise awareness about gender equality</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Have I demonstrated my own commitment to promoting gender equality within the project?</li>\r\n<li>Do I raise the issue of gender equality during team meetings and when planning activities?</li>\r\n<li>Did I organize a gender equality training at the outset of the project to strengthen the capacity of my colleagues?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing partners with expertise in gender equality</em></p>\r\n<p>1) Did I involve women&rsquo;s organizations and/or other civil society organizations with expertise in gender equality?<br />BEST PRACTICE #4 : Integrate gender equality in your communication strategy</p>\r\n<p>Crafting your messages</p>\r\n<p>1) How do my key messages reflect my organization&rsquo;s commitment to gender equality?<br />2) Do I have specific messages on the gender dimensions of my project theme?<br />3) Do my messages reinforce stereotypes about women and men&rsquo;s roles?</p>\r\n<p>Choosing the right images</p>\r\n<p>1) Are women and men equally represented in my communication materials?<br />2) Are women represented as victims or as leaders in my communication materials?</p>\r\n<p>Using the right words<br />1) Do my written communications use gender-neutral language?</p>\r\n<p>Choosing your media outlets and promotional materials<br />1) Do the media outlets and promotional materials I use allow me to reach as many men as women?</p>\r\n<p>Choosing your spokespeople<br />1) Are there as many women as men who speak publicly about the project (as spokespeople, panelists, facilitators, etc.)?</p>\r\n<p>Choosing the journalists you work with<br />1) Do I work with both men and women journalists?<br />2) Do I provide them with sex-disaggregated data so they can convey the different realities faced by women and men?</p>\r\n<p>BEST PRACTICE #5 : Integrate gender equality in your project evaluation</p>\r\n<p>Setting up your project monitoring system<br />1) Have I collected sex-disaggregated data for all my project monitoring indicators?<br />2) Does the data collected allow me to measure the participation and specific impact of the project on women and men?</p>\r\n<p>Choosing your evaluation methods</p>\r\n<p>1) Did the evaluation allow me to determine whether the project achieved its specific gender equality objectives?<br />2) Did the evaluation allow me to assess whether I adequately integrated gender equality in the design and implementation of all steps of the project?<br />3) Did the evaluation allow me to measure increased awareness or changes in attitudes vis-&agrave;-vis gender equality?</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-06 20:49:51','2013-09-06 20:49:51',5,'','','',NULL,'','','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'JimmyChicaiza-49.jpg','image/jpeg',1535878,'2013-09-06 20:49:49','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(54,NULL,'Deliberative dialogue','<p dir=\"ltr\">Dialogue is a different way of engaging. It is about creating meaning together, thinking about issues in new ways and exploring and building common ground. Deliberative dialogue goes further and asks people to make choices by weighing competing values and priorities, by thinking through pros and cons, and by determining acceptable trade-offs. It is a cornerstone of participatory democracy, where citizens can collectively work through the tough issues facing their community or society and build robust skills for citizenship that go far beyond showing up at the ballot box every four years.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At its best, deliberative dialogue can nourish <strong>personal, relational and social change</strong>. For example, in a recent process, citizens came together to deliberate on climate change, identify solutions and provide advice to municipal decision-makers in ways that could impact policy and program. To complete this rather daunting mandate, citizens had to explore their own assumptions and values &ndash; about climate change, about the economy, about government, about citizenship &ndash; and find common ground. Randomly selected, they came into the room with a diversity of viewpoints. They listened to presentations from various perspectives and asked questions. They thought critically about the issue. And they began to really listen to each other and explore ideas together. This broke down the stereotypes they held of one another. It created new understanding and insights that the group used to find common ground on values and principles from which they could provide their best advice to decision-makers.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">But deliberative dialogue poses challenges for our sector&rsquo;s work. When citizens come together to think about tough societal issues, there is no guarantee that they will arrive at the same solutions as we might as NGOs. It requires letting go of the outcomes of the dialogue, which can come into conflict with our campaigning work. We also know that dialogue doesn&rsquo;t necessarily lead to action &ndash; individually or collectively - and when it does, it may go in a different direction than envisioned by us as NGOs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Reflection questions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">How can we use deliberative dialogue to better collaborate with each other and with other stakeholders?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Can we accept that citizens can make good judgments, even when they are different from our proposed solutions?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">How can we bridge dialogue and action? (Or do we need to?) Who defines the action?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">How can we bring citizen perspectives to policy and decision-makers?</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 20:50:39','2013-09-06 21:34:30',3,'small','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\">Le dialogue offre une forme diff&eacute;rente d&rsquo;engagement. Il s&rsquo;agit de cr&eacute;er du sens ensemble, de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir aux probl&egrave;mes d&rsquo;une mani&egrave;re nouvelle et d&rsquo;explorer voire d&rsquo;am&eacute;nager un terrain d&rsquo;entente. Le dialogue d&eacute;lib&eacute;ratif va plus loin et demande aux gens de faire un choix en comparant des valeurs et des priorit&eacute;s contrast&eacute;es, en pesant le pour et le contre, et en d&eacute;finissant des compromis acceptables. Il constitue une pierre angulaire de la d&eacute;mocratie participative, gr&acirc;ce &agrave; laquelle les citoyennes et les citoyens peuvent r&eacute;soudre ensemble des probl&egrave;mes qui se posent &agrave; leur collectivit&eacute; ou &agrave; leur soci&eacute;t&eacute; et d&eacute;velopper de robustes savoir-faire citoyens qui d&eacute;passent largement le fait d&rsquo;aller aux urnes une fois tous les quatre ans.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Dans le meilleur des cas, le dialogue d&eacute;lib&eacute;ratif peut alimenter le <strong>changement personnel, relationnel et social</strong>. Par exemple, lors d&rsquo;un processus v&eacute;cu r&eacute;cemment, des citoyens se sont r&eacute;unis pour d&eacute;lib&eacute;rer sur les changements climatiques, identifier des solutions et formuler des recommandations aux &eacute;lus municipaux (d&eacute;cideurs) de mani&egrave;re &agrave; influencer les programmes et les politiques. Pour r&eacute;ussir &agrave; s&rsquo;acquitter d&rsquo;un mandat aussi impressionnant, les citoyens ont d&ucirc; explorer leurs propres hypoth&egrave;ses et leurs propres valeurs &ndash; sur les changements climatiques, sur l&rsquo;&eacute;conomie, sur le gouvernement, sur la citoyennet&eacute; &ndash; et trouver un terrain d&rsquo;entente. &nbsp;Choisis de mani&egrave;re al&eacute;atoire, ils sont arriv&eacute;s avec des points de vue diff&eacute;rents. Ils ont entendu des expos&eacute;s qui illustraient des perspectives diff&eacute;rentes et ils ont pos&eacute; des questions. Ils ont fait une r&eacute;flexion critique sur le probl&egrave;me en cause. Et ils ont commenc&eacute; &agrave; s&rsquo;&eacute;couter vraiment les uns les autres, et &agrave; explorer ensemble certaines id&eacute;es. Cet exercice a fait tomber les pr&eacute;jug&eacute;s qu&rsquo;ils avaient les uns &agrave; l&rsquo;endroit des autres. Il en a &eacute;merg&eacute; une nouvelle perception et de nouvelles id&eacute;es dont le groupe s&rsquo;est servi pour arriver &agrave; une entente sur des valeurs et des principes dont ils ont pu s&rsquo;inspirer pour formuler leurs recommandations aux d&eacute;cideurs.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mais le dialogue d&eacute;lib&eacute;ratif comporte des d&eacute;fis dans le travail que nous faisons. Lorsque des citoyens se r&eacute;unissent pour r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir &agrave; des enjeux de soci&eacute;t&eacute; complexes, rien ne garantit qu&rsquo;ils arriveront aux solutions que nous voudrions pr&ocirc;ner en tant qu&rsquo;ONG. Il nous faut renoncer &agrave; contr&ocirc;ler les r&eacute;sultats du dialogue. Nous savons aussi que le dialogue ne d&eacute;bouche pas n&eacute;cessairement sur l&rsquo;action &ndash; individuelle ou collective &ndash; et que lorsqu&rsquo;il le fait, il peut aller dans un sens diff&eacute;rent de celui que nous avions pr&eacute;vu comme ONG.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions pour la r&eacute;flexion:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Comment se servir du dialogue d&eacute;lib&eacute;ratif pour mieux collaborer entre nous avec d&rsquo;autres parties prenantes?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Pouvons-nous reconna&icirc;tre que les citoyens font preuve de jugement, m&ecirc;me quand ils choisissent d&rsquo;autres solutions que celles que nous proposons?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Comment jeter un pont du dialogue &agrave; l&rsquo;action? (Est-il n&eacute;cessaire de le faire?) Qui doit d&eacute;finir l&rsquo;action?</li>\r\n<li>Comment pr&eacute;senter les perspectives des citoyens aux d&eacute;cideurs politiques?</li>\r\n</ul>','Le dialogue délibératif','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(55,NULL,'Transaction vs. transformation in a large humanitarian organization','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Lessons can always be learned from public engagement work on development issues. The following case study specifically explores a malaria prevention program and the interconnections between public engagement, public relations, and fundraising.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>The malaria prevention program took place in over twelve countries in Africa in a collaborative process that engaged local educators and humanitarian volunteers, regional and national health authorities, as well as international aid organizations. On the ground, the focus was on prevention and capacity building. Over seven million nets were distributed to families with young children. The dissemination process included training almost thirty thousand local volunteers to facilitate community-based prevention education and to support effective use of the nets. In many communities the malaria program included vaccination campaigns and training for health professionals in rural areas to administer medical treatment.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>While the malaria prevention program was a comprehensive partnership between communities, humanitarian organizations and governments, the Canadian public engagement around this program focused on a </span><span>transactional</span><span> style of engagement, encouraging Canadians to &lsquo;buy a net and save a life&rsquo;. Millions of nets were purchased through online and in-person fundraising initiatives (</span><strong>points of engagement</strong><span>). The fundraising focus of the Canadian portion provided little context on the spread or impact of malaria, nor were additional opportunities for engagement facilitated. Despite raising significant funds to support the malaria program, when national and international funding ceased, so did Canadian engagement.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions for engagement:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">How can we move from transactional points of engagement to personal, relational or societal engagement?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Is it possible to run a campaign which has both transactional and transformational goals? How can fund-raising and public engagement work together?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">What are the potential risks of focusing solely on transactional points of entry?</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 20:53:05','2013-09-06 21:33:10',3,'large','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\">Il y a toujours des le&ccedil;ons &agrave; tirer du travail d&rsquo;engagement du public sur les enjeux de d&eacute;veloppement. Le cas que voici explore examine un programme de pr&eacute;vention du paludisme et les liens entre engagement du public, relations publiques et collecte de fonds.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le programme de pr&eacute;vention du paludisme a &eacute;t&eacute; d&eacute;ploy&eacute; dans plus de douze pays d&rsquo;Afrique dans un effort de collaboration regroupant des &eacute;ducatrices, des &eacute;ducateurs et des b&eacute;n&eacute;voles humanitaires locaux, les autorit&eacute;s de la sant&eacute; r&eacute;gionales et nationales et des organisations d&rsquo;aide internationale. Sur le terrain, on a mis l&rsquo;accent sur la pr&eacute;vention et le renforcement des capacit&eacute;s. On a distribu&eacute; plus de sept millions de moustiquaires &agrave; des familles avec de jeunes enfants. Le processus de distribution a exig&eacute; la formation de pr&egrave;s de trente mille b&eacute;n&eacute;voles locaux pour donner la formation communautaire en pr&eacute;vention et pour soutenir l&rsquo;utilisation efficace des moustiquaires. Dans de nombreuses collectivit&eacute;s, le programme anti-paludisme comprenait des campagnes de vaccination et de la formation aux professionnel-le-s de la sant&eacute; sur l&rsquo;administration des soins m&eacute;dicaux.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Alors que le programme de pr&eacute;vention du paludisme constituait un partenariat complet entre les collectivit&eacute;s, les organismes humanitaires et les gouvernements, le volet canadien d&rsquo;engagement du public pour ce programme comportait un engagement de type transactionnel, qui encourageait les Canadiennes et les Canadiens &agrave; &laquo; acheter un moustiquaire pour sauver une vie &raquo;. Des millions de moustiquaires ont &eacute;t&eacute; achet&eacute;s en ligne ou dans le cadre d&rsquo;initiatives de collecte de fonds en personne (<strong>points d&rsquo;engagement</strong>). L&rsquo;accent plac&eacute; sur la collecte de fonds au Canada a fait qu&rsquo;on a donn&eacute; peu d&rsquo;information sur la propagation ou sur l&rsquo;incidence du paludisme, et qu&rsquo;on n&rsquo;a pas offert d&rsquo;autres possibilit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement. M&ecirc;me si on est arriv&eacute; &agrave; recueillir des sommes consid&eacute;rables pour appuyer le programme anti-paludisme, d&egrave;s qu&rsquo;a pris fin la collecte de fonds nationale et internationale, l&rsquo;engagement canadien s&rsquo;est termin&eacute;.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Questions pour l&rsquo;engagement:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Comment passer de points d&rsquo;engagement transactionnels &agrave; un engagement personnel, relationnel ou soci&eacute;tal?</li>\r\n<li dir=\"ltr\">Est-il possible de mener une campagne qui ait des objectifs &agrave; la fois transactionnels et transformationnels? Comment concilier collecte de fonds et engagement du public?</li>\r\n<li>Quels risques peut-il y avoir &agrave; ne mettre l&rsquo;accent que sur des points d&rsquo;entr&eacute;e transactionnels?</li>\r\n</ul>','Transaction ou transformation au sein d’un gros organisme humanitaire','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Bednet.jpg','image/jpeg',447726,'2013-09-06 21:32:45','Village health worker Mohammed inspects a bed-net at the home of Amina Waziri in Songa village, Tanzania, June 2007. Photo: Gates Foundation','Mohammed, l’agent de santé du village, inspecte une moustiquaire chez Amina Waziri dans le village de Songa, en Tanzanie, juin 2007. Photo: La Fondation Gates',NULL,NULL,NULL,'57',NULL,NULL),(56,NULL,'Reflection questions for integrating gender equality','<p>Reflection Questions for Integrating Gender Equality in Public Engagement</p>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #1 : Integrate gender equality at the project planning stage</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choosing and analyzing your topic</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I do a gender analysis to collect sex-disaggregated data?</li>\r\n<li>Did this data help me understand and explain how women and men experience the issue differently?</li>\r\n<li>In the terms of reference for the background research, did I specify the need to collect and analyze information on how the issue affects women and men differently?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Defining your objectives</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>Gender mainstreaming:</em> Did I include gender equality in the framing of all project objectives?</li>\r\n<li><em>Specific objectives on gender equality:</em> Did I include a specific objective on gender equality in addition to other project objectives?</li>\r\n<li><em>Gender mainstreaming and stand alone work on gender equality:</em> Did I decide to do both?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing your indicators</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I design my indicators in such a way as to gather sex-disaggregated data (ex: number of women and men, percentage of women and men, etc.)?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #2 : Integrate gender equality in your project strategy</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Designing your awareness raising activities</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Were the project activities equally accessible to women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities take into account the availability of women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities equally appeal to women/girls and men/boys?</li>\r\n<li>Did the project activities offer the opportunity for women/girls and men/boys to equally express themselves?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Deciding who your advocacy campaign will target</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I do a power analysis to determine who was likely to support or oppose the project&rsquo;s efforts to promote gender equality?</li>\r\n<li>Did I organize specific activities to raise awareness and convince elected officials who were less informed or had misgivings about gender equality?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><strong>BEST PRACTICE #3 : Raise awareness and commitment to gender equality within your team</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Making time to discuss and raise awareness about gender equality</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Have I demonstrated my own commitment to promoting gender equality within the project?</li>\r\n<li>Do I raise the issue of gender equality during team meetings and when planning activities?</li>\r\n<li>Did I organize a gender equality training at the outset of the project to strengthen the capacity of my colleagues?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing partners with expertise in gender equality</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did I involve women&rsquo;s organizations and/or other civil society organizations with expertise in gender equality?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #4 : Integrate gender equality in your communication strategy</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Crafting your messages</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>How do my key messages reflect my organization&rsquo;s commitment to gender equality?</li>\r\n<li>Do I have specific messages on the gender dimensions of my project theme?</li>\r\n<li>Do my messages reinforce stereotypes about women and men&rsquo;s roles?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing the right images</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Are women and men equally represented in my communication materials?</li>\r\n<li>Are women represented as victims or as leaders in my communication materials?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Using the right words</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Do my written communications use gender-neutral language?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing your media outlets and promotional materials</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Do the media outlets and promotional materials I use allow me to reach as many men as women?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing your spokespeople</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Are there as many women as men who speak publicly about the project (as spokespeople, panelists, facilitators, etc.)?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing the journalists you work with</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Do I work with both men and women journalists?</li>\r\n<li>Do I provide them with sex-disaggregated data so they can convey the different realities faced by women and men?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BEST PRACTICE #5 : Integrate gender equality in your project evaluation</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Setting up your project monitoring system</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Have I collected sex-disaggregated data for all my project monitoring indicators?</li>\r\n<li>Does the data collected allow me to measure the participation and specific impact of the project on women and men?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choosing your evaluation methods</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Did the evaluation allow me to determine whether the project achieved its specific gender equality objectives?</li>\r\n<li>Did the evaluation allow me to assess whether I adequately integrated gender equality in the design and implementation of all steps of the project?</li>\r\n<li>Did the evaluation allow me to measure increased awareness or changes in attitudes vis-&agrave;-vis gender equality?</li>\r\n</ol>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'tools','2013-09-06 21:12:39','2013-09-06 21:12:39',5,'small','','',NULL,'<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-0c3b70ab-f517-c331-fd5b-8d97a0bf1975\"><span>Questions de r&eacute;flexion pour int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes &agrave; l&rsquo;engagement public</span></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>BONNE PRATIQUE #1 : Int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; la planification du projet d&rsquo;EP</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choix et analyse du th&egrave;me</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je men&eacute; une &laquo; analyse de genre &raquo; pour colliger des donn&eacute;es d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;es par sexe?</li>\r\n<li>Ces donn&eacute;es ont-elles permis de comprendre et de pr&eacute;senter les r&eacute;alit&eacute;s diff&eacute;rentes des femmes et des hommes par rapport au th&egrave;me?</li>\r\n<li>Le mandat pour la collecte de donn&eacute;es distinguait-il l&rsquo;impact du th&egrave;me sur les femmes et sur les hommes?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des objectifs</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Int&eacute;gration transversale: ai-je ajout&eacute; une composante &Eacute;FH &agrave; chacun des objectifs du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Int&eacute;gration sp&eacute;cifique: ai-je formul&eacute; un objectif sp&eacute;cifique &Eacute;FH qui s&rsquo;ajoute aux autres objectifs du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Int&eacute;gration transversale et sp&eacute;cifique: avez-vous d&eacute;cid&eacute; de faire les deux?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des indicateurs</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je formul&eacute; mes indicateurs de mani&egrave;re &agrave; r&eacute;colter des informations distinctes pour chacun des deux sexes (ex.: nombre de femmes et d&rsquo;hommes, pourcentage de femmes et d&rsquo;hommes, etc.)?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BONNE PRATIQUE #2 : Int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; la strat&eacute;gie du projet</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choix des activit&eacute;s de sensibilisation</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Les activit&eacute;s du projet ont-elles garanti une accessibilit&eacute; &eacute;gale aux femmes/filles et aux homes/gar&ccedil;ons?</li>\r\n<li>Les activit&eacute;s du projet ont-elles tenu compte de la disponibilit&eacute; des femmes/filles et des hommes/gar&ccedil;ons?</li>\r\n<li>Les activit&eacute;s du projet &eacute;taient-elles aussi attrayantes pour les femmes/filles que pour les hommes/gar&ccedil;ons?</li>\r\n<li>Les activit&eacute;s du projet ont-elles offert des possibilit&eacute;s &eacute;gales de s&rsquo;exprimer aux femmes/filles et aux hommes/gar&ccedil;ons?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des personnes vis&eacute;es par une campagne de plaidoyer</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je fait une analyse de pouvoir pour d&eacute;terminer qui est susceptible d&rsquo;appuyer ou de freiner les efforts de mon projet en faveur de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n<li>Ai-je organis&eacute; des activit&eacute;s sp&eacute;cifiques sur l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH pour sensibiliser et convaincre les &eacute;lu-e-s jug&eacute;-e-s moins inform&eacute;-e-s ou oppos&eacute;-e-s?</li>\r\n<li>BONNE PRATIQUE #3 : Int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH en sensibilisant les membres de l&rsquo;&eacute;quipe</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Prendre le temps de discuter et de se sensibiliser &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je manifest&eacute; mon propre engagement &agrave; promouvoir l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH au sein du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Est-ce que je profite des r&eacute;unions d&rsquo;&eacute;quipe et de planification pour aborder l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n<li>Ai-je organis&eacute;, au d&eacute;but du projet, une formation sur l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH pour renforcer les capacit&eacute;s de mes collaboratrices et collaborateurs?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des partenaires sp&eacute;cialis&eacute;s</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je impliqu&eacute; des organisations de femmes ou d&rsquo;autres OSC avec une expertise en &Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BONNE PRATIQUE #4 : Int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; ma strat&eacute;gie de communication</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choix des messages diffus&eacute;s</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>En quoi mes messages cl&eacute;s refl&egrave;tent-ils l&rsquo;engagement de mon organisme envers l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n<li>Ai-je des messages sp&eacute;cifiques sur la dimension &Eacute;FH du th&egrave;me du projet?</li>\r\n<li>Mes messages renforcent-ils des st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes sur les r&ocirc;les de femmes et des hommes?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des images</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Repr&eacute;sentation &eacute;quilibr&eacute;e des femmes et des hommes dans le mat&eacute;riel ?</li>\r\n<li>Les femmes y sont-elles repr&eacute;sent&eacute;es comme des victimes ou comme des leaders?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des mots</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Mes communications &eacute;crites utilisent-elles un langage non sexiste?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des m&eacute;dias et des outils promotionnels</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Les m&eacute;dias et les outils promotionnels que j&rsquo;utilise me permettent-ils de rejoindre autant de femmes que d&rsquo;hommes?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des porte-parole</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Y a-t-il autant de femmes que d&rsquo;hommes qui interviennent publiquement pour le projet (porte-parole, pan&eacute;listes, animatrices ou animateurs, etc.)?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des journalistes avec qui vous travaillez</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Est-ce que je travaille autant avec des journalistes femmes et hommes?</li>\r\n<li>Est-ce que je leur donne de l&rsquo;information sexosp&eacute;cifique pour qu&rsquo;ils communiquent la r&eacute;alit&eacute; diff&eacute;renci&eacute;e des femmes et des hommes?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>BONNE PRATIQUE #5 : Int&eacute;grer l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation du projet</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>Choix des m&eacute;thodes de suivi</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Ai-je collig&eacute; des donn&eacute;es d&eacute;sagr&eacute;g&eacute;es par sexe pour l&rsquo;ensemble de mes indicateurs de suivi?</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;information recueillie me permet-elle de mesurer la participation et l&rsquo;impact sp&eacute;cifique du projet sur les femmes et sur les hommes?</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><em>Choix des m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation</em></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation me permet-elle de mesurer l&rsquo;atteinte de mes objectifs sp&eacute;cifiques en mati&egrave;re d&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation me permet-elle d&rsquo;analyser l&rsquo;int&eacute;gration de l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH &agrave; la conception et &agrave; la mise en &oelig;uvre de toutes les &eacute;tapes du projet?</li>\r\n<li>L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation me permet-elle de mesurer s&rsquo;il y a eu des prises de conscience ou des changements d&rsquo;attitudes par rapport &agrave; l&rsquo;&Eacute;FH?</li>\r\n</ol>','Questions de réflexion pour l’intégration de l’égalité entre les femmes et les homes (ÉFH)','outil','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(57,NULL,'International Women’s Day partnership  scenario','<p>Imagine a scenario where five organizers have come together to plan a public engagement activity for International Women&rsquo;s Day, March 8. They represent a cross-section of the education sector: a public high school teacher, an international NGO supporting women&rsquo;s projects in Africa, a local women&rsquo;s organisation that runs a shelter for abused women, a professor of Women&rsquo;s Studies at a local university and a small business owner.</p>\r\n<p>They are being brought together by the international NGO with the understanding that the objective of the activity is to raise awareness of the issue of violence against women and girls worldwide, and the search for solutions. There is an acknowledgement that this issue has been a focus for a long time but has somewhat fallen off the radar of people&rsquo;s consciousness given some of the positive changes that have occurred in women&rsquo;s lives over the past thirty years.</p>\r\n<p>All have agreed with the objective of the activity as outlined above. The activity will involve presentations from women involved in the issue of violence against women, including a Zambian woman whose organization is supported by the NGO.</p>\r\n<p>The partners next outline what they have to bring to the table to ensure a successful outcome. The international NGO is bringing some funds to support the activity, plus a guest speaker from Zambia. The high school teacher has no funds but can ensure an audience and some volunteers to help with logistics. The local women&rsquo;s organization has no funds but can provide speakers who are willing to speak directly to the issue. The academic can support with funds in a limited way and also some student volunteers and potential audience members. The business entrepreneur is new to this kind of activity but is willing to learn and also to support the activity financially. It would seem that all is in place for a successful outcome.</p>\r\n<p>Issues of equity arise, however, when it comes to making decisions about the following. <em>(Note: These are not meant to be a comprehensive list of issues that may arise &ndash; you might think of others.)</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Budget:</strong> Who will contribute, and how much? Obviously some will contribute more than others &ndash; will this allow some participants to exert influence over the others? How will the funds be accounted for? Do partners representing organisations have particular demands to meet from their organizations that others may not have?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Program of the activity:</strong> Given the backgrounds of the partners, there may be power dynamics at play. For example, the academic may see herself as the expert in the group. There may be a difference of opinion as to the importance given to different presenters.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Logistics:</strong> Who will take on responsibilities for communications and publicity? Who will secure a venue? Is insurance an issue? How often does the group of partners have to meet? How will differences of opinion be handled?</p>\r\n<p>There are other issues of equity involved that may have more to do with the personalities of the partners rather than the tasks at hand. For example, a successful entrepreneur may not be familiar with consultation processes that NGOs use as a matter of course. Meeting face to face and getting to know one another will help open channels to resolve these issues. Being open to discussion of processes goes a long way toward achieving success in a collaboration and leaving the partners with a desire for future collaborative work.</p>\r\n<p>Identifying the various ways to contribute to a partnership can help to overcome inequality. Different organizations may be able to contribute different aspects of a public engagement campaign: funds, staff time, audience reach, facilitation skills, varying experience. These aspects are all required to create a campaign that is far-reaching; identifying these needs and determining how best to address them equitably can help ensure a productive and fulfilling partnership.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 21:17:10','2013-09-06 21:17:10',7,'','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(58,NULL,'The Great Earth Society (Success case)','<p>Putting the partnerships &amp; collaboration principles of good practice into action</p>\r\n<p><em><strong>Scenario:</strong></em></p>\r\n<p><br />Your organization, The Great Earth Society, has some great ideas for public engagement during the upcoming International Development Week. Not only that, you&rsquo;ve just received some extra funding to implement public engagement activities related to environmental awareness, which is this year&rsquo;s International Development Week theme.</p>\r\n<p>However, being a small organization, you could more fully implement your ideas if you were able to partner with other organizations that could not only augment the money available but could also help with the organizing and marketing of the event.</p>\r\n<p>Your organizing committee knows some of the individuals involved in the international office of the local Happy Valley College, but in previous dealings with that group, you have come away feeling completely overwhelmed, powerless to make your own case or to stand your ground when decisions are made. You also know the College is already partnering with the local International Council of Good Works, which further complicates the picture. You feel that the three organizations could have a real impact building on the shared goals of each of your organizations related to international development and public engagement, but you are leery of being \'swallowed up\' by the other organizations and therefore unable to meet your own organization&rsquo;s goals.</p>\r\n<p>You aren&rsquo;t certain that the two organizations realize that your group has often felt excluded and disrespected in past collaborations. You bring good organizational skills and huge grassroots support to the table, while they are bigger organizations with more experience and more money to put towards activities. You all share similar goals related to public engagement and international development, as well as a passion for protection of the environment both at home and around the world.</p>\r\n<p>In discussing the situation, your International Development Week Planning Committee decides to put into practice some of the new ideas you&rsquo;ve learned related to public engagement partnerships and collaboration. The Planning Committee decides to approach the other two organizations with your ideas regarding a possible collaboration for International Development Week activities &ndash; specifically, a large joint display and activities related to the environment.</p>\r\n<p>Before you approach them, however, you write up your own &lsquo;rules of engagement,&rsquo; which identify the common goals you believe you share, the strengths of each of the partners and the type of activities you believe the three organizations could undertake. You also identify the funding that you are able to bring to the event and the parameters and guidelines around that funding which your organization must utilize. You also determine that planning for consensus building is important and identify ways that this can be done in meetings so that everyone feels respected when decisions are made.<br />The Great Earth Society organizing committee also decides to identify in advance some of the areas for possible conflict and determine your own stance in these areas so that you can feel prepared when the discussion comes. You also outlined some ideas for timelines and a communication protocol. Because your funding is tied to results, you also have a draft of an evaluation tool you&rsquo;d like to see agreed upon for the activity by all three partners. In this way, you&rsquo;ve been able to outline your own objectives, expectations, roles and responsibilities as well as what you are able to contribute to the activity.<br />You meet with the other organizations, and the first meeting turns out surprisingly well. They&rsquo;re grateful that you&rsquo;ve already put in time preparing your own goals, objectives and expectations and are ready to assist them in determining how best to work together and how the work of the College and Council could help achieve the Great Earth Society&rsquo;s goals while still achieving many of their own goals. There are a few sticky issues, but having identified them in advance you&rsquo;re prepared to discuss them and come to a consensus. The group is excited to organize a super International Development Week event. More meetings are planned.</p>\r\n<p><br /><em><strong>Analysis:</strong></em></p>\r\n<p>The Great Earth Society is like many smaller organizations that feel they sometimes have to struggle to be heard when partnering with other organizations. Having had some negative partnership/collaboration experiences in the past, the organization determined that the best defence is to be very well prepared when wanting to form partnerships. The organization followed good practices related to establishing partnerships by:</p>\r\n<p>a) Reviewing their own goals, vision, guidelines and organizational structure to make sure they well understood their own organizational parameters. They also reviewed the goals and aims of potential partner organizations to ensure that shared common ground in terms of public engagement.</p>\r\n<p>b) In trying to be very clear about the type of activity they wanted to implement, they prepared the objectives, goals, timeline and parameters of the activity they expected to undertake together, along with what their organization could contribute. They also identified what they hoped the other organizations could contribute while leaving the opportunity for them to bring their own ideas forward.</p>\r\n<p>c) To avoid conflict in which they felt they had no voice, they identified a number of effective consensus-building practices and were ready to implement them during meetings should the need arise.</p>\r\n<p>d) The organization also identified any issues that might occur around funding &ndash; and knew explicitly what their organization required of them and what they hoped the other organizations could contribute. They were aware of restrictions and knew that they also had to be sensitive about their partner organizations&rsquo; funding restrictions.</p>\r\n<p>e) They established good communications timelines for their shared activity.</p>\r\n<p>f) They also identified a way of evaluating both the activity and the collaboration/partnership process itself to provide information for their next event.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 21:20:02','2013-09-06 21:20:02',7,'','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(59,NULL,'Participatory, dialogue-based evaluation','<p><em>By Vince Terstappen, Project &amp; Operations Coordinator for Check Your Head: The Youth Global Education Network</em></p>\r\n<p>For a project to train youth as peer educators, we experimented with several participatory, dialogue-based evaluation methods that yielded great results. The impact of this approach was twofold. First, it created powerful opportunities for participants to share, take ownership of the project, and engage with one another, strengthening their relationships. Second, it created a great deal of very interesting, unexpected, and useful evaluation data that we incorporated into reports to participants, members, and funders. Two particularly interesting approaches were used.</p>\r\n<p>First, after participants completed an online survey with a number of quantitative and qualitative questions about actions they had taken in the community, we created a <a href=\"http://checkyourhead.org/blog/taking-action-against-violence/\" target=\"_blank\">visual representation</a> of the information in aggregate. We &lsquo;closed the loop&rsquo; by presenting this visual to the participants during a gathering and supported them as they facilitated a dialogue on what it meant to be part of an active and engaged community.</p>\r\n<p>When the online surveys were considered in isolation, the participants may not have felt that their impact was substantial; however, when seen as one part of a larger movement, the actions appeared much larger. In post-evaluations, several participants noted that one of the biggest things that they took away from the project was knowing that they are part of a community of like-minded youth.</p>\r\n<p>Secondly, as a closing exercise after a year of training and engagement activities, participants were able to give feedback to one another anonymously. For this, 15 participants stood in a circle with their eyes closed. One participant was selected to step outside of the circle, open their eyes, and think of one person who inspired them over the last year. They walked to that person, tapped them on the shoulder, and silently returned to their spot in the circle, closing their eyes. The person who was tapped could then open their eyes and was asked to anonymously tap someone who taught them something and then return to their spot. This process continued with a number of questions about different contributions made by participants until everyone had been anonymously tapped a few times.</p>\r\n<p>Participants remarked later that they really enjoyed this evaluation exercise, that they were caught off-guard (in a good way!) by the reasons they were tapped, and that it created a sense of community. It was a great way to &lsquo;close the loop&rsquo; with participants, to report back to them in a participatory and creative way, and to have them take a leading role in providing feedback to one another and, as a result, to the organization and the project evaluation.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'case-studies','2013-09-06 21:29:21','2013-09-06 21:30:50',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><em>par Vince Terstappen, coordonnateur des projets et des op&eacute;rations &agrave; &laquo; Check Your Head: The Youth Global Education Network &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>Nous sommes un projet visant &agrave; former des jeunes &agrave; devenir &eacute;ducateurs et &eacute;ducatrices de leurs pairs, et nous avons essay&eacute; plusieurs m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation participative fond&eacute;e sur le dialogue. Cette approche a eu un double impact. Premi&egrave;rement, elle a donn&eacute; aux participantes et aux participants d&rsquo;excellentes occasions de partager, de s&rsquo;approprier le projet et de se parler, ce qui renfor&ccedil;ait les liens entre eux. Deuxi&egrave;mement, elle a g&eacute;n&eacute;r&eacute; une grande quantit&eacute; de donn&eacute;es d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation tr&egrave;s int&eacute;ressantes, inattendues et utiles, que nous avons pu inclure dans nos rapports aux participant-e-s, &agrave; nos membres et &agrave; nos bailleurs de fonds. Nous avons utilis&eacute; deux approches particuli&egrave;rement int&eacute;ressantes.</p>\r\n<p>D&rsquo;abord, apr&egrave;s que les participant-e-s eurent rempli un sondage en ligne comportant diff&eacute;rentes questions quantitatives et qualitatives au sujet de leurs interventions dans la collectivit&eacute;, nous avons pr&eacute;par&eacute; une <a href=\"http://checkyourhead.org/blog/taking-action-against-violence/\" target=\"_blank\">repr&eacute;sentation visuelle</a> de l&rsquo;ensemble de cette information. Puis nous avons &laquo; boucl&eacute; la boucle &raquo; en pr&eacute;sentant cette synth&egrave;se visuelle aux participant-e-s lors d&rsquo;une r&eacute;union et en les aidant &agrave; animer un dialogue sur ce que cela signifie que de faire partie d&rsquo;une communaut&eacute; active et engag&eacute;e.</p>\r\n<p>En ne consid&eacute;rant que les sondages en ligne, les participant-e-s avaient pu penser que leur impact n&rsquo;&eacute;tait pas tr&egrave;s cons&eacute;quent; mais, replac&eacute;es dans le cadre d&rsquo;un mouvement plus large, leurs actions prenaient un autre relief. Dans les &eacute;valuations finales, plusieurs participant-e-s ont soulign&eacute; qu&rsquo;une des principales le&ccedil;ons du projet pour eux, c&rsquo;est l&rsquo;id&eacute;e qu&rsquo;ils font partie de tout un groupe de jeunes qui pensent comme eux.</p>\r\n<p>Ensuite, comme dernier exercice apr&egrave;s un an d&rsquo;activit&eacute;s de formation et d&rsquo;engagement, les participantes et les participants ont pu se donner une r&eacute;troaction de mani&egrave;re anonyme. Pour ce faire, 15 participant-e-s se tenaient en cercle, les yeux ferm&eacute;s. On demandait &agrave; un ou une participante de sortir du cercle, d&rsquo;ouvrir les yeux et de penser &agrave; une personne qui avait &eacute;t&eacute; pour lui ou pour elle une source d&rsquo;inspiration pendant l&rsquo;ann&eacute;e, de se diriger vers cette personne et de lui taper sur l&rsquo;&eacute;paule avant de regagner sa place et de fermer les yeux. La personne qui avait re&ccedil;u le signal sortait du cercle et on lui demandait d&rsquo;aller taper sur l&rsquo;&eacute;paule de quelqu&rsquo;un qui lui avait appris quelque chose, puis de retourner &agrave; sa place. La d&eacute;marche continuait avec un certain nombre de questions sur l&rsquo;apport des participant-e-s jusqu&rsquo;&agrave; ce que tout le monde ait pu recevoir quelques tapes sur l&rsquo;&eacute;paule.</p>\r\n<p>Les participant-e-s devaient confier par la suite qu&rsquo;ils ont beaucoup aim&eacute; cet exercice d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation, qu&rsquo;ils avaient &eacute;t&eacute; surpris (positivement!) de voir les raisons pour lesquelles on leur avait donn&eacute; une tape sur l&rsquo;&eacute;paule et que l&rsquo;exercice avait nourri chez eux le sentiment de former une communaut&eacute;. C&rsquo;&eacute;tait une excellente fa&ccedil;on de &laquo; boucler la boucle &raquo;, de leur pr&eacute;senter un rapport en mode participatif et de mani&egrave;re originale, et de leur permettre de contribuer activement &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;change de r&eacute;troaction et donc aussi &agrave; l&rsquo;organisation du projet d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation.</p>','Évaluation participative, fondée sur le dialogue','cas','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Facil_training_12.jpg','image/jpeg',457844,'2013-09-06 21:29:15','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'190',NULL,NULL),(60,NULL,'Partnerships and collaboration in context','<p>Civil society organizations address some of the most complex social, economic and environmental issues of our time. In the same way that civil society organizations are created because people recognize that they must organize themselves with others to tackle these issues, collective efforts among organizations are also necessary in order to have a successful impact. This section of the toolkit takes as its starting point that civil society organizations\' public engagement efforts are an important element of bringing about social change, and that successful change happens through collective effort.</p>\r\n<p>By working in partnership and collaboration, organizations are able to benefit from broader perspectives and expertise that are brought to the table. Working with others helps our public engagement efforts to have a greater reach and potentially save resources. The aim of this chapter is therefore not to discuss whether, but how, partnerships and collaboration can contribute to reaching the overriding goal of public engagement in Canada. It offers insights from the reflections of practitioners who have many years of experience working in, and researching, partnerships and collaboration in public engagement in Canada.</p>\r\n<p>The discussions in this chapter refer to both partnerships and collaboration. It was a deliberate choice of the authors to refer to both terms because, although they overlap in meaning, they often differ in practice. When we paid attention to how we speak about them in practice, we noted that when referring to collaboration we tend to talk about relationships between organizations that are more informal. For example, we may collaborate with other like-minded organizations to implement International Development Week activities once a year. Another example may be collaboration that takes place through mutual efforts on a policy advocacy initiative, like Make Poverty History. These collaborations rarely involve a formal agreement, but may be based on discussions with like-minded organizations to keep one another appraised of the progress of individual or joint activities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Partnerships</strong> was taken to describe a deeper form of collaboration, one that is often formalized. They may be prolonged joint efforts designed to achieve mutual, named goals. For example, public engagement efforts that revolve around ongoing linkages between Canadian civil society organizations (e.g. health care organizations) and southern civil society organizations (e.g. HIV/AIDS organizations) are seen as being a partnership between the organizations involved.<br />Partnerships may, however, also be short-term, revolving around a specific time-limited project requiring a more formalized relationship because organizations involved want to identify themselves as partners and want clear roles and responsibilities outlined. These may at times involve relationships between organizations that may not be automatically recognized as being like-minded. These also often involve funding support that requires a formalized contractual arrangement.</p>\r\n<p>As the members of this knowledge hub discussed how these terms are similar and different, we recognized that all partnerships are a form of collaboration, but not all collaboration is a partnership. Some organizations may be more comfortable in a less formal collaboration when first working with another organization. This allows time to get to know one another and to avoid the higher risk involved in a more formal partnership. In addition, opportunities to collaborate may arise quickly, leaving organizations little time to take the steps to formalize a partnership.</p>\r\n<p>Working in partnership and collaboration is not easy and is often more time-consuming than working alone. It requires a particular knowledge and skill set among the individuals involved, and a certain level of capacity within each of the organizations.</p>\r\n<p>Regardless of which form of collective action organizations choose, partnerships and collaboration play an important role in our public engagement efforts. The insights in this section are written to support organizations as they reflect on how their partnerships and collaborations contribute to good practice in public engagement.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-06 21:31:11','2013-09-06 21:33:20',7,'tall','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'5772931215_24568b9758_o.jpg','image/jpeg',2992796,'2013-09-06 21:32:44','Fitting the pieces together to get the ball rolling. Photo: flickr.com/fdecomite/','Caption: Rassembler les morceaux pour mettre la balle en jeu. Photo: flickr.com/fdecomite/',NULL,NULL,NULL,'126',NULL,NULL),(61,NULL,'Base partnerships and collaboration on shared visions and goals','<p>Partnerships that are built on shared visions and goals will help promote mutual support and solidarity beyond the implementation of specific programs and projects.</p>\r\n<p>This principle is particularly important when partnering with other kinds of organizations, including those from the private sector. Partnering with a different sector helps to open new opportunities and increase the reach of public engagement initiatives. It also involves dealing with very different organizational cultures and values that may come into conflict. This makes it particularly important to be open and transparent about each of the organization&rsquo;s values, goals and roles before agreeing to partner. It is easy to make wrong assumptions about why or how either partner wants to be involved in a public engagement effort. Asking key questions at the beginning will ensure you work with partners that help you live your values. It will also help partners avoid conflict later on and even possible loss of trust with your supporters.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:36:31','2013-09-06 21:36:52',7,'large','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4925267732_492be0075f_o.jpg','image/jpeg',1421979,'2013-09-06 21:36:28','Compass to lead. Photo: Calsidyrose','Suivre la boussole. Photo: Calsidyrose',NULL,NULL,NULL,'115',NULL,NULL),(62,NULL,'Be respectful, honest, transparent and accountable with partners and collaborators','<p>The best partnerships are dynamic relationships founded in respect and honesty, in which partners strive for better understanding and appreciation of one another. Partnership agreements should take into account that over time the partnership needs to be re-examined to ensure that the good fit remains. Ensure that processes are in place to ensure that all partners operate in a transparent and accountable manner, with a common understanding of timelines and results to be achieved. Ensure all partners have a clearly defined understanding of how finances for the activity/project will be handled. Build in processes that encourage and ensure transparency and accountability.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:39:01','2013-09-06 21:39:22',7,'small','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'8050049446_4433e7564c_o.jpg','image/jpeg',179659,'2013-09-06 21:39:00','Young girls working together. Photo:Hannah Findlay (Frontier)','Young girls working together. Photo:Hannah Findlay (Frontier)',NULL,NULL,NULL,'74',NULL,NULL),(63,NULL,'Create partnerships and collaborations that embody equity','<p>Acknowledging that inequalities often exist as a result of power dynamics, especially in funding relationships, partners should strive for equitable partnerships. Think through potential inequalities that could exist in the partnership (from all sides) prior to embarking on the relationship and put structures or processes in place that will ensure that these inequities are easily recognized and overcome.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:41:57','2013-09-06 21:42:28',7,'large','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'For_Partnership_section___BCCIC_Apr_19_final_1.jpg','image/jpeg',2126172,'2013-09-06 21:41:51','Pursuing Equitable Partnerships. Photo: www.wholepicturethinking.com','Pursuing Equitable Partnerships. Photo: www.wholepicturethinking.com',NULL,NULL,NULL,'117',NULL,NULL),(64,NULL,'Facilitate the sharing of knowledge among partners and collaborators','<p>While collaborations operate much more fluidly, an effective communications plan with specific timelines for communications among partners is critical to ensure knowledge is shared. A process can be established within the project or activity cycle that requires partners to identify things they\'ve learned as a result of the partnership. These new learnings can be a part of reporting and can provide useful information for new partnerships in the future.</p>\r\n<p>Even for looser collaborations, an informal debrief session at the conclusion of a campaign can help to identify successes and challenges while solidifying positive relations.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:45:12','2013-09-06 21:45:36',7,'wide','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'8135280620_2e746067f6_o.jpg','image/jpeg',6690037,'2013-09-06 21:45:00','Being open with the information gathered. Photo: Calgary New Central Library','Being open with the information gathered. Photo: Calgary New Central Library',NULL,NULL,NULL,'95',NULL,NULL),(65,NULL,'How Change Happens - Context','<p dir=\"ltr\">In order to be effective as public engagement practitioners, we need opportunities to reflect on our work and think about the underlying theories and assumptions on which we base our actions. The tools and resources that follow are designed to encourage practitioners to think about how change happens as a result of public engagement, and to help them apply that understanding to the work of their organizations. We hope that organizations in our sector will use our theory of change model to reflect on their own assumptions about how change happens, and ultimately that they will undertake to develop, or adapt, a theory of change to inform their work.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Definition of Public Engagement</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The following was developed as a working definition of public engagement for the ICN project. &nbsp;It is not meant to be a prescriptive or conclusive definition, but rather, a definition that helps contextualize the approach and understanding of public engagement for this project, in this moment in time.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Public engagement is the practice of inspiring, supporting and challenging people and groups in dynamic cycles of learning, reflection and action on global issues. Public engagement is a transformative process that works towards more equitable social, economic, environmental and political structures.</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Transformational vs. transactional engagement</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;We need to shift the balance of NGO public engagement activities away from &lsquo;transactions&rsquo; and towards &lsquo;transformations&rsquo;. This means placing less emphasis on &lsquo;&pound;5 buys...&rsquo; appeals and simple campaigning actions, and more emphasis on providing supporters with opportunities to engage increasingly deeply over time through a &lsquo;supporter journey&rsquo;.&rdquo;<em><br /></em>-<a href=\"http://www.findingframes.org/Finding%20Frames%20New%20ways%20to%20engage%20the%20UK%20public%20in%20global%20poverty%20Bond%202011.pdf\">Finding Frames, Page 10</a></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Over the past few decades there have been pressures on public engagement that have led to an increased adoption of transactional, rather than transformational, methods. We believe that the purpose of public engagement is transformational change: it should create long-term, sustainable change within individuals, groups and societies.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>Transactional engagement</em> seeks to lower or eliminate barriers to entry and calls for actions that are broad-based, easy and fast &ndash; such as a small donation via a text message, or signing an online petition. While these methods can be an important and often vital part of public engagement, we don&rsquo;t believe that transactional methods alone will ultimately lead to the change we seek. In fact, some argue that they can be counter-productive for creating lasting change <a href=\"http://www.findingframes.org/Finding%20Frames%20New%20ways%20to%20engage%20the%20UK%20public%20in%20global%20poverty%20Bond%202011.pdf\">(Finding Frames, 6)</a>.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Transformational engagement seeks to implicate individuals and groups in dynamic cycles of learning, reflection and action on global issues. This process requires spaces for deeper engagement and methods that foster longer-term participation. Techniques for transformational engagement might include learning circles, experiential learning (local or global), or deliberative dialogue to work through complex issues, among many others.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">As argued in a discussion paper commissioned by CCIC:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;Generating change in global systems cannot happen exclusively through awareness raising. . . . &nbsp;More and more, [civil society organizations] of the South are telling their northern counterparts that the best way they can support development is by catalyzing changed attitudes and practices in the North and to entrust them with their own local development efforts. Public engagement needs to be holistic in its approach and include all of the actions leading to social change that citizens can take and this includes advocacy&rdquo; (&ldquo;Public Engagement in Challenging Times: The Context, Implications, and Possible Directions&rdquo;, 18).</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Public engagement is work that is never complete, and changes as we change, as our organizations change and as our societies change.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The &lsquo;How Change Happens&rsquo; knowledge hub explored the explicit and implicit messages of our public engagement work. Our sector has had many conversations about the conflicting paradigms of justice on the one hand (the idea that development is a process of addressing inequities in social, economic, environmental and political structures, for the betterment of all) and charity on the other (the idea that development is a gift from the North to the South), and how they are both reflected in our messaging. The Finding Frames report looks at how the public in the UK understands global poverty through a frame of charity even when practitioners try to frame their message as one based in justice:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&ldquo;The causes of poverty are seen as internal to poor countries: famine, war, natural disasters, bad governance, overpopulation and so on. The dominant paradigm has been labelled the Live Aid Legacy, characterised by the relationship of &lsquo;Powerful Giver&rsquo; and &lsquo;Grateful Receiver.&rsquo; Public perceptions have been stuck in this frame for 25 years&rdquo; (Finding Frames 6).</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The report demonstrates that the UK public is mostly unable to identify the ways in which their own behaviour and that of their government perpetuate inequality. Additionally, they hold onto the paradigm of &ldquo;Us vs. Them&rdquo; and perceive any solution as being tied to the charity model (20). We see many parallels between the UK report and the public engagement environment in Canada.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lynette Shultz, Associate Professor of Education Policy Studies, identifies another dominant paradigm in public engagement practice in Canada: that of the &ldquo;empowered individual&rdquo; (<a href=\"http://www.cgcer.ualberta.ca/en/~/media/cgcer/Documents/ICN_GCE_and_the_Empowered_Individual.pdf\">&ldquo;Public Engagement and Educating for Global Citizenship: What do we risk by focusing on &ldquo;the Empowered Individual&rdquo;?&rdquo;</a>, 3), a person in the developed world who has the power to make positive change. On first glance, this paradigm appears different than that of the &ldquo;Powerful Giver&rdquo; and &ldquo;Grateful Receiver.&rdquo; However, this paradigm does not change the relationship between the giver and receiver, but, rather, shifts the frame to focus only on the &ldquo;giver&rdquo; &ndash; the empowered individual &ndash; thus de-legitimizing collective action, and shutting out voices from the Global South.</p>\r\n<p>We are left with the question of how we can re-frame our public engagement work in order to help Canadians understand themselves and their roles differently, and emphasize the values of cooperation, equality and justice that we believe are integral to our work. &nbsp;We hope that the tools in this module will provide opportunities for practitioners to reflect on and share their own understandings of how to help Canadians engage in transformative change.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-06 21:46:29','2013-09-06 21:46:55',3,'wide','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\">Pour &ecirc;tre efficaces comme praticiennes et praticiens en engagement du public, nous devons prendre le temps de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir &agrave; notre travail et de repenser les th&eacute;ories et les hypoth&egrave;ses sur lesquelles se fondent nos interventions. Les outils et les ressources qui suivent sont con&ccedil;us pour inviter praticiennes et praticiens &agrave; r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir &agrave; la fa&ccedil;on dont survient le changement par suite du travail d&rsquo;engagement du public, et pour les aider &agrave; appliquer leurs r&eacute;flexions &agrave; la m&eacute;thode de travail de leur organisation. Nous esp&eacute;rons que les organisations de notre secteur utiliseront notre mod&egrave;le de th&eacute;orie du changement pour r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir aux hypoth&egrave;ses qu&rsquo;elles utilisent pour expliquer le changement et qu&rsquo;elles en viendront &agrave; se donner une th&eacute;orie du changement, ou &agrave; adapter celle qu&rsquo;elles ont, pour orienter leur travail.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>D&eacute;finition de l&rsquo;engagement du public</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">La formulation qui suit a &eacute;t&eacute; &eacute;labor&eacute;e comme d&eacute;finition provisoire dans le cadre du projet du RCC. Elle ne se veut ni normative ni d&eacute;finitive et esp&egrave;re seulement aider &agrave; mettre en contexte l&rsquo;approche et la conception de l&rsquo;engagement du public pour ce projet pr&eacute;cis et &agrave; ce moment pr&eacute;cis.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>L&rsquo;engagement du public est la pratique qui veut inspirer, soutenir et interpeller les individus et les groupes &agrave; l&rsquo;int&eacute;rieur de cycles dynamiques d&rsquo;apprentissage, de r&eacute;flexion et d&rsquo;action sur des enjeux globaux. L&rsquo;engagement du public est un processus de transformation qui travaille en vue de structures sociales, &eacute;conomiques, environnementales et politiques plus &eacute;quitables.</em></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Transformation ou transactions</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Il nous faut d&eacute;placer l&rsquo;axe des activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public des ONG autour de la transformation plut&ocirc;t qu&rsquo;autour de transactions. Cela veut dire mettre moins l&rsquo;accent sur les demandes de dons de 5 livres et les actions de campagne simples afin de donner plut&ocirc;t l&rsquo;occasion aux gens qui nous appuient de s&rsquo;engager plus profond&eacute;ment, &agrave; terme, dans une d&eacute;marche d&rsquo;appui. &raquo;<br />-<a href=\"http://www.findingframes.org/Finding%20Frames%20New%20ways%20to%20engage%20the%20UK%20public%20in%20global%20poverty%20Bond%202011.pdf\">Finding Frames, Page 10</a></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Au cours des derni&egrave;res d&eacute;cennies, les pressions exerc&eacute;es sur l&rsquo;engagement du public l&rsquo;ont amen&eacute; &agrave; adopter de plus en plus de m&eacute;thodes ax&eacute;es sur la transaction plut&ocirc;t que sur la transformation. Nous croyons que l&rsquo;engagement du public a pour objectif un changement transformateur : il devrait susciter un changement durable &agrave; long terme chez les individus, dans les groupes et les soci&eacute;t&eacute;s.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>L&rsquo;engagement transactionnel</em> cherche &agrave; r&eacute;duire ou &agrave; &eacute;liminer les barri&egrave;res &agrave; des appels &agrave; l&rsquo;action faciles et rapides, destin&eacute;s au grand public &ndash; comme un petit don par message-texte ou la signature d&rsquo;une p&eacute;tition en ligne. M&ecirc;me si ces m&eacute;thodes peuvent &ecirc;tre un &eacute;l&eacute;ment important, voire vital, de l&rsquo;engagement du public, nous ne croyons pas qu&rsquo;&agrave; elles seules, les m&eacute;thodes fond&eacute;es sur les transactions vont suffire &agrave; susciter les changements que nous recherchons. En fait, certains les juge contre-productives et estiment qu&rsquo;elles freinent l&rsquo;apparition d&rsquo;un changement durable<a href=\"http://www.findingframes.org/Finding%20Frames%20New%20ways%20to%20engage%20the%20UK%20public%20in%20global%20poverty%20Bond%202011.pdf\">(Finding Frames, 6)</a>.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">L&rsquo;engagement transformationnel cherche &agrave; inclure les individus et les groupes dans des cycles dynamiques d&rsquo;apprentissage, de r&eacute;flexion et d&rsquo;action sur des enjeux globaux. Ce processus exige des espaces d&rsquo;engagement plus profond et des m&eacute;thodes qui favorisent la participation &agrave; long terme. Les techniques d&rsquo;engagement transformationnel peuvent comprendre, entre autres, les cercles d&rsquo;apprentissage, l&rsquo;apprentissage fond&eacute; sur l&rsquo;exp&eacute;rience (locale ou globale) ou les d&eacute;lib&eacute;rations pour creuser des probl&egrave;mes complexes.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Comme l&rsquo;explique un document de travail command&eacute; par le CCCI,</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Le changement des syst&egrave;mes mondiaux ne pourra pas r&eacute;sulter de la seule conscientisation. . . . &nbsp;De plus en plus, [les organisations de la soci&eacute;t&eacute; civile] du Sud disent &agrave; leurs homologues du Nord que la meilleure fa&ccedil;on pour elles d&rsquo;appuyer le d&eacute;veloppement, c&rsquo;est de provoquer des changements d&rsquo;attitudes et de pratiques dans le Nord et de leur laisser, &agrave; elles, le soin de travailler au d&eacute;veloppement dans leur propre milieu. L&rsquo;engagement du public doit adopter une approche holistique et comprendre toutes les actions que peuvent poser les citoyens pour susciter le changement social, notamment le plaidoyer &raquo; (&laquo; <em>Public Engagement in Challenging Times: The Context, Implications, and Possible Directions</em> &raquo; [L&rsquo;engagement du public dans les temps difficiles : contexte, implications et orientations possibles], p.18).</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">L&rsquo;engagement du public est un travail qui n&rsquo;est jamais termin&eacute;, qui &eacute;volue avec nous, avec nos organisations et avec nos soci&eacute;t&eacute;s.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le p&ocirc;le de connaissances intitul&eacute; &laquo; Comment survient le changement &raquo; a explor&eacute; les messages explicites et implicites de notre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public. Notre secteur a eu de nombreuses conversations sur les paradigmes conflictuels de la justice, d&rsquo;une part (l&rsquo;id&eacute;e que le d&eacute;veloppement est un processus qui agit sur les in&eacute;galit&eacute;s dans les structures sociales, &eacute;conomiques, environnementales et politiques, en vue d&rsquo;am&eacute;liorer toutes ces structures), et la charit&eacute;, d&rsquo;autre part (l&rsquo;id&eacute;e que le d&eacute;veloppement est un don du Nord au Sud), et sur le fait que ces deux paradigmes se retrouvent dans les messages que nous diffusons. Le rapport <em>Finding Frames</em> examine la fa&ccedil;on dont le public du Royaume-Uni comprend la pauvret&eacute; mondiale sous l&rsquo;angle de la charit&eacute; alors m&ecirc;me que praticiennes et praticiens s&rsquo;efforcent de pr&eacute;senter leur message sous l&rsquo;angle de la justice:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">&laquo; Les gens estiment que les causes de la pauvret&eacute; se trouvent dans les pays pauvres : famine, guerre, cataclysmes, mauvaise gouvernance, surpopulation, etc. On a donn&eacute; au paradigme dominant le nom d&rsquo;H&eacute;ritage Live Aid : il est caract&eacute;ris&eacute; par la relation entre un donateur puissant et un donataire reconnaissant. Les perceptions du public sont fig&eacute;es dans ce cadre depuis 25 ans. &raquo; &nbsp;(<em>Finding Frames</em>, 6)</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Le rapport montre que, de fa&ccedil;on g&eacute;n&eacute;rale, le public britannique est incapable de voir en quoi son propre comportement et celui de son gouvernement contribuent &agrave; perp&eacute;tuer l&rsquo;in&eacute;galit&eacute;. En outre, il s&rsquo;en tient &agrave; une perspective &laquo; nous autres / eux autres &raquo; et estiment que toutes les solutions sont finalement affaire de charit&eacute; (20). On peut relever de nombreuses ressemblances entre le tableau que brosse ce rapport et le contexte dans lequel se fait l&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Lynette Shultz, professeure agr&eacute;g&eacute;e d&rsquo;&eacute;tudes en politique de l&rsquo;&eacute;ducation, identifie un autre paradigme dominant dans la pratique de l&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada: celui de &laquo; l&rsquo;individu habilit&eacute; &raquo; (<a href=\"http://www.cgcer.ualberta.ca/en/~/media/cgcer/Documents/ICN_GCE_and_the_Empowered_Individual.pdf\">&ldquo;Public Engagement and Educating for Global Citizenship: What do we risk by focusing on &ldquo;the Empowered Individual&rdquo;?&rdquo;</a>, [Engagement du public et &eacute;ducation &agrave; la citoyennet&eacute; mondiale : que risquons-nous &agrave; nous concentrer sur &laquo;l&rsquo;individu habilit&eacute;&raquo; ?, &nbsp;p.3), personne du monde d&eacute;velopp&eacute; qui a le pouvoir de changer les choses, de provoquer un changement positif. &Agrave; premi&egrave;re vue, ce paradigme semble diff&eacute;rent de celui du &laquo; donateur puissant / donataire reconnaissant &raquo;. Mais, en fait, ce paradigme ne change pas le rapport entre le donateur et le donataire : il se concentre uniquement sur le &laquo; donateur &raquo;, l&rsquo;individu habilit&eacute;, ce qui a pour effet d&rsquo;enlever toute l&eacute;gitimit&eacute; &agrave; l&rsquo;action collective et de r&eacute;duire au silence le Sud global.</p>\r\n<p>La question s&rsquo;impose donc &agrave; nous de voir comment recadrer notre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public afin d&rsquo;aider les Canadiennes et les Canadiens &agrave; se voir d&rsquo;un autre &oelig;il et &agrave; voir autrement le r&ocirc;le qu&rsquo;ils peuvent jouer, et de mettre l&rsquo;accent sur les valeurs de coop&eacute;ration, d&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; et de justice que nous jugeons essentielles &agrave; notre travail. &nbsp;Nous esp&eacute;rons que les outils que propose le pr&eacute;sent module donneront l&rsquo;occasion aux praticiennes et aux praticiens de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir ensemble &agrave; la fa&ccedil;on dont ils peuvent aider les Canadiennes et les Canadiens &agrave; vivre un changement transformateur.</p>','Comment survient le changement – Le contexte','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Change.jpg','image/jpeg',255178,'2013-09-06 21:46:25','Photo: Jordi Martorell','Photo: Jordi Martorell',NULL,NULL,NULL,'0',NULL,NULL),(66,NULL,'Negotiate objectives, expectations, roles and responsibilities for each partnership','<p>Use checklists or survey tools to identify your own organization&rsquo;s objectives, expectations, roles and responsibilities within the partnership, as well as those of your potential partner, and make certain all partners understand these fully to avoid misunderstandings. Written documentation of the discussions related to the above are critical.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:47:04','2013-09-06 21:48:00',7,'wide','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'6231641551_3b58da878d_o.jpg','image/jpeg',1793647,'2013-09-06 21:47:00','Listen, understand, act. Photo: Steven Shorrock','Listen, understand, act. Photo: Steven Shorrock',NULL,NULL,NULL,'21',NULL,NULL),(67,NULL,'Monitoring & evaluation in context','<p>Monitoring and evaluation are important across all public engagement activities. <em>Monitoring</em> is the process of tracking progress in the achievement of a program&rsquo;s objectives. <em>Evaluation</em> is the systematic assessment of that progress,or lack thereof, in relation to goals. Investing in monitoring and evaluation is a crucial component in determining whether the desired social change is taking place, and adjusting practices accordingly.</p>\r\n<p>Monitoring and evaluation for public engagement is important for four complementary reasons:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>to make progress in achieving our desired outcomes;</li>\r\n<li>to improve our programming as public engagement practitioners;</li>\r\n<li>to ensure we are communicating our work effectively with our network and stakeholders; and</li>\r\n<li>to justify the need for ongoing public engagement funding to donors.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>In the Inter-Council Network&rsquo;s 2012 focus groups and interviews with public engagement practitioners across Canada, <em>measuring the effectiveness of public engagement</em> was identified as one of the top five peer learning priorities. However, monitoring and evaluation in public engagement can be very challenging. These challenges were a common theme in this Knowledge Hub and across public engagement practitioners and organizations.</p>\r\n<p>As a result, the goal of this Knowledge Hub was to articulate and share good practices to address these challenges. As a group, we articulated a number of challenges and gaps related to monitoring and evaluation in public engagement, including:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>the tendency to report only to donors, basing our monitoring and evaluation around donor requirements, instead of program or organizational objectives. This tension can also be articulated as evaluation for donors versus evaluation for learning and stakeholder engagement.</li>\r\n<li>a lack of human and financial resources for monitoring and evaluation &ndash; another symptom of evaluation for donors versus evaluation for learning and stakeholder engagement. If monitoring and evaluation is primarily valued to fulfill donor needs, the commitment of time and resources will be lacking to measure the internal outcomes for long term organizational needs for public engagement learning. These internal outcomes will involve collection and analysis of qualitative data (i.e. participant reporting on how their behaviour has changed), often requiring a greater investment of time and resources than a donor&rsquo;s quantitative data requests (i.e. number of participants).</li>\r\n<li>diversity in types of public engagement has led to a large diversity of tools, and there is not one central place for these tools. Further, there is a lack of knowledge on what tools and methods are good (or not) and rigorous (or not).</li>\r\n<li>public engagement is challenging to measure. It is often not quantifiable, and attributing causality to changes in knowledge and behaviour is not easy. Combined with unspecified engagement targets such as &ldquo;the general public&rdquo; and a focus on short-term public engagement campaigns, measuring the results of public engagement can be difficult.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The context in which monitoring and evaluation for public engagement takes place is one in which the very definition of public engagement seems to be fluid and different between places and times (<a href=\"http://monitoringandevaluation.icn-rcc.wikispaces.net/file/view/Weber_Nadya_A_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf/391771520/Weber_Nadya_A_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Webber 2012</a>). Importantly, this toolkit has articulated a new definition of public engagement that captures the current context of public engagement in Canada:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>Public engagement is the practice of inspiring, supporting and challenging people and groups in dynamic cycles of learning, reflection and action on global issues. Public engagement is a transformative process that works towards more equitable social, economic, environmental and political structures.</em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Finally, the Istanbul Principles are an important guide for public engagement and for monitoring and evaluation. The principles relate to personal, relational, and societal change and therefore apply to all levels of public engagement. There is no one prescription that can ensure your organization&rsquo;s monitoring and evaluation activities will be perfect, but keeping the spirit of the Istanbul Principles of &ldquo;empowering people&rdquo; front and centre in planning and implementing your monitoring and evaluation plan is an excellent start.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'context','2013-09-06 21:48:45','2013-09-06 21:49:22',6,'tall','','',NULL,'<p>Le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation sont importants pour toutes les activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public. Le <em>suivi</em> consiste &agrave; surveiller la progression dans l&rsquo;atteinte des objectifs d&rsquo;un programme. <em>L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation</em> consiste &agrave; mesurer syst&eacute;matiquement le progr&egrave;s accompli en fonction de buts pr&eacute;cis. L&rsquo;effort de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation est essentiel pour &eacute;tablir si le changement social recherch&eacute; se produit effectivement et pour corriger en cons&eacute;quence les fa&ccedil;ons de faire.</p>\r\n<p>En engagement du public, le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation importent pour quatre raisons compl&eacute;mentaires:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>pour progresser et atteindre les r&eacute;sultats esp&eacute;r&eacute;s;</li>\r\n<li>pour am&eacute;liorer notre programmation en tant que praticiennes et praticiens en engagement du public;</li>\r\n<li>pour nous permettre de communiquer efficacement avec notre r&eacute;seau et avec les parties prenantes au programme; et</li>\r\n<li>pour justifier devant nos bailleurs de fonds le besoin de continuer de financer l&rsquo;engagement du public.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>Dans les entrevues et les groupes de discussion organis&eacute;s en 2012 par le R&eacute;seau de coordination des conseils avec des praticiennes et des praticiens en engagement du public de tout le Canada, le fait de <em>mesurer l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; de l&rsquo;engagement du public</em> est ressorti comme l&rsquo;une des cinq priorit&eacute;s d&rsquo;apprentissage entre pairs. Mais le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation en engagement du public peuvent poser de grosses difficult&eacute;s. Ces difficult&eacute;s ont &eacute;t&eacute; &eacute;voqu&eacute;es fr&eacute;quemment dans ce P&ocirc;le de connaissances comme chez les praticien-ne-s et les organisations d&rsquo;engagement du public.</p>\r\n<p>Aussi ce P&ocirc;le de connaissances s&rsquo;est-il fix&eacute; pour objectif d&rsquo;articuler et de partager les bonnes pratiques visant &agrave; surmonter ces difficult&eacute;s. Comme groupe, nous avons formul&eacute; un certain nombre d&rsquo;obstacles et de lacunes en lien avec le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation en engagement du public, notamment:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>la tendance &agrave; ne pr&eacute;senter des rapports qu&rsquo;aux bailleurs de fonds, en fondant notre suivi et notre &eacute;valuation sur les exigences des bailleurs de fonds plut&ocirc;t que sur les objectifs du programme ou de l&rsquo;organisation. On pourrait r&eacute;sumer cette tension en opposant l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation <em>pour les bailleurs de fonds &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation</em> en fonction de <em>l&rsquo;apprentissage et de l&rsquo;engagement des parties prenantes</em>.</li>\r\n<li>le manque de ressources humaines et financi&egrave;res pour le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation &ndash; autre sympt&ocirc;me de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation <em>pour les bailleurs de fonds</em> plut&ocirc;t qu&rsquo;en fonction de <em>l&rsquo;apprentissage et de l&rsquo;engagement des parties prenantes</em>. Si on n&rsquo;accorde de l&rsquo;importance au suivi-&eacute;valuation qu&rsquo;en fonction des besoins des bailleurs de fonds, on n&rsquo;investira pas le temps et les ressources n&eacute;cessaires pour mesurer les indicateurs internes des besoins de formation &agrave; long terme de l&rsquo;organisation en engagement du public. Ces indicateurs internes porteront sur la cueillette et l&rsquo;analyse des donn&eacute;es (les participants indiquent en quoi leur comportement a chang&eacute;), ce qui exige un plus grand investissement de temps et de ressources que les donn&eacute;es quantitatives demand&eacute;es par un bailleur de fonds (nombre de participant-e-s).</li>\r\n<li>la diversit&eacute; des types d&rsquo;engagement du public a donn&eacute; naissance &agrave; une grande diversit&eacute; d&rsquo;outils, qui ne sont pas regroup&eacute;s dans un lieu centralis&eacute;. Par ailleurs, on ne sait pas bien quels sont les outils et les m&eacute;thodes qui sont vraiment ad&eacute;quats et rigoureux.</li>\r\n<li>l&rsquo;engagement du public est difficile &agrave; mesurer. Il n&rsquo;est souvent pas quantifiable, et il n&rsquo;est pas facile de cerner ce qui entra&icirc;ne le changement des connaissances ou des comportements. Qu&rsquo;on y ajoute des cibles d&rsquo;engagement impr&eacute;cises, comme &laquo; le grand public &raquo;, et l&rsquo;accent plac&eacute; sur des campagnes &agrave; court terme, et la mesure des r&eacute;sultats devient vraiment difficile.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Le contexte dans lequel s&rsquo;effectuent le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation fait que la d&eacute;finition m&ecirc;me de l&rsquo;engagement du public fluctue selon les endroits et les moments (<a href=\"http://monitoringandevaluation.icn-rcc.wikispaces.net/file/view/Weber_Nadya_A_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf/391771520/Weber_Nadya_A_201211_PhD_thesis.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Webber 2012</a>). Notre bo&icirc;te &agrave; outils a donc tenu &agrave; proposer une nouvelle d&eacute;finition de l&rsquo;engagement du public qui tienne compte du contexte dans lequel se fait actuellement l&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada:</p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>L&rsquo;engagement du public est la pratique qui cherche &agrave; inspirer, &agrave; soutenir et &agrave; interpeller les personnes et les groupes au sein de cercles dynamiques d&rsquo;apprentissage, de r&eacute;flexion et d&rsquo;action sur les enjeux globaux. L&rsquo;engagement du public est un processus de transformation qui vise &agrave; instaurer des structures sociales, &eacute;conomiques, environnementales et politiques plus &eacute;quitables.</em></p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Enfin les Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul constituent un guide important pour l&rsquo;engagement du public et pour le suivi-&eacute;valuation. Ces principes concernent le changement personnel, relationnel et soci&eacute;tal, et s&rsquo;appliquent donc &agrave; tous les niveaux de l&rsquo;engagement du public. Il n&rsquo;y a pas de recette magique qui garantisse la perfection &agrave; votre organisation en mati&egrave;re de suivi-&eacute;valuation, mais vous aurez au moins un excellent d&eacute;part si vous axez la planification et la mise en &oelig;uvre de votre suivi-&eacute;valuation sur l&rsquo;esprit des Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul et &laquo; l&rsquo;autonomisation [<em>empowerment</em>] des gens &raquo;.</p>','Le suivi et l’évaluation mis en contexte','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Gender_course_2009.jpg','image/jpeg',593923,'2013-09-06 21:48:36','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'634',NULL,NULL),(68,NULL,'Be explicit about your values and principles','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Sometimes &ndash; unlike people working in international development projects overseas &ndash; we are working without clearly established principles. Having clear principles can help guide us in our decision-making, and stop us from inadvertently doing things that work against our long term goals. </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Over the last decade or so, civil society organizations from all across the world have worked on a set of principles to guide development effectiveness, called the </span><a href=\"http://www.cso-effectiveness.org/istanbul-principles,067\"><span>Istanbul Principles for CSO Development Effectiveness</span></a><span>. Many of our organizations are now working to adopt these principles for their own development practice. </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It is an important exercise to think about how these principles might impact our practice of public engagement. Take time to consider how your organization&rsquo;s public engagement activities reflect internationally accepted principles of development effectiveness.</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-3b5594da-f53f-44d5-94c9-fb71d49b3b9a\"><span>Some of these principles might be challenging for our practice of public engagement. For example, the principle &ldquo;Practice Transparency and Accountability&rdquo; is not often considered in the work of public engagement. To whom are we accountable in our public engagement work? To our donors? To our Southern partners? To our target audiences? Where in the planning process of public engagement can we consider our values and principles?</span></span></p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:52:03','2013-09-06 21:52:40',3,'tall','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Il arrive parfois &ndash; ce qui n&rsquo;est pas le cas pour les personnes qui travaillent sur des projets de d&eacute;veloppement international &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger &ndash; que nous travaillions sans disposer de principes clairement formul&eacute;s. Des principes clairs pourront nous aider dans la prise de d&eacute;cision et nous emp&ecirc;cheront de faire par inadvertance des choses qui vont &agrave; l&rsquo;encontre de nos objectifs &agrave; long terme.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Depuis une dizaine d&rsquo;ann&eacute;es environ, les organisations de la soci&eacute;t&eacute; civile de partout &agrave; travers le monde ont &eacute;labor&eacute; un ensemble de principes pour orienter l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; du d&eacute;veloppement: ce sont les</span><a href=\"http://www.cso-effectiveness.org/istanbul-principles,067\"><span>Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul sur l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; du d&eacute;veloppement des OSC</span></a><span>. Plusieurs de nos organisations travaillent pr&eacute;sentement &agrave; incorporer ces principes &agrave; leur propre pratique en mati&egrave;re de d&eacute;veloppement.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Il est important de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir &agrave; la fa&ccedil;on dont ces principes peuvent influencer notre pratique de l&rsquo;engagement du public. Prenez le temps de regarder jusqu&rsquo;&agrave; quel point les activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public de votre organisation refl&egrave;tent les principes sur l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; du d&eacute;veloppement qui ont &eacute;t&eacute; valid&eacute;s au niveau international.</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-3b5594da-f540-9fc6-4b0a-70c899c15356\"><span>Certains de ces principes pourraient s&rsquo;av&eacute;rer exigeants pour notre pratique de l&rsquo;engagement du public. Par exemple, celui qui demande de &laquo; pratiquer la transparence et la redevabilit&eacute; &raquo; n&rsquo;est pas souvent pris en compte dans le travail d&rsquo;engagement du public. &Agrave; qui sommes-nous redevables de notre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public? &Agrave; qui rendons-nous des comptes? &Agrave; nos bailleurs de fonds ? &Agrave; nos partenaires du Sud? &Agrave; nos publics cibles? &Agrave; quelle &eacute;tape du processus de planification de nos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public pouvons-nous nous arr&ecirc;ter &agrave; consid&eacute;rer nos valeurs et nos principes?</span></span></p>','Formulez explicitement vos valeurs et vos principes','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fair_Trade_Procurement_3.jpg','image/jpeg',5791241,'2013-09-06 21:51:24','Photo: Dustin Leader','Photo: Dustin Leader',NULL,NULL,NULL,'36',NULL,NULL),(69,NULL,'Create spaces for deeper engagement','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>It is clear that the kind of work that we need to do is not superficial, and means enduring changes in our attitudes and perspectives, as well as our skills. It is hard work that requires us to take risks. Some have noted that in the past several decades many Canadians participated in transformative learning through their unions and faith-based groups. These spaces are becoming less central in many people&rsquo;s lives, and have not yet been replaced by other spaces where deeper conversations and transformative experiences can happen. </span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>We need to find a balance between this transformative, in-depth level of engagement and dialogue and the briefer, large scale engagement that will often serve as entry points for people. Both are essential in our public engagement.</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-6bc0705b-f543-2799-8a9e-4388f32355f2\"><span>However, sometimes the paths that people can take from our short-term engagements into deeper engagements are not clear. Think about how your public engagement can build or support the spaces and opportunities for deeper engagement that are necessary for transformative change. One of the key lessons is that not all of us need to do everything. Some organizations may be stronger in organizing short-term, broad-based engagements, and others in more intensive engagements. How do we work together?</span></span></p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 21:56:15','2013-09-06 21:57:01',3,'large','','',NULL,'<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Il est clair que le genre de travail que nous devons faire ne saurait &ecirc;tre superficiel et qu&rsquo;il suppose des changements durables dans nos attitudes et nos fa&ccedil;ons de voir comme dans nos savoir-faire. C&rsquo;est un travail difficile qui nous oblige &agrave; prendre des risques. On a fait remarquer qu&rsquo;au cours des derni&egrave;res d&eacute;cennies, bon nombre de Canadiennes et de Canadiens ont v&eacute;cu des apprentissages transformateurs dans leurs syndicats ou leurs groupes religieux. Ces lieux occupent aujourd&rsquo;hui une place moins centrale dans la vie des gens, mais ils n&rsquo;ont pas &eacute;t&eacute; remplac&eacute;s par d&rsquo;autres lieux o&ugrave; puissent se vivre en profondeur des conversations et des exp&eacute;riences transformatrices.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Nous devons trouver un &eacute;quilibre entre ce niveau d&rsquo;engagement et de dialogue qui transforme en profondeur et l&rsquo;engagement plus court et &agrave; plus grande &eacute;chelle qui repr&eacute;sente souvent un point d&rsquo;entr&eacute;e pour les gens. Les deux niveaux d&rsquo;interaction sont indispensables &agrave; notre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public.</span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-6bc0705b-f544-c3e2-4eed-c2ce5f36372b\"><span>Toutefois, il n&rsquo;est pas toujours facile de comprendre comment les gens vont faire le pas de nos engagements &agrave; court terme &agrave; des formes plus profondes d&rsquo;engagement. Pensez &agrave; la fa&ccedil;on dont votre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public peut construire ou appuyer des lieux et des occasions d&rsquo;engagement plus profond, car ceux-ci sont indispensables au changement transformateur. Une des le&ccedil;ons les plus importantes &agrave; retenir, c&rsquo;est que nous ne devons pas toutes et tous faire la m&ecirc;me chose. Certaines organisations peuvent &ecirc;tre plus habiles dans l&rsquo;organisation de vastes campagnes d&rsquo;engagement &agrave; court terme alors que d&rsquo;autres ma&icirc;trisent les engagements plus intensifs. Comment travaillons-nous ensemble?</span></span></p>','Créer des lieux pour un engagement en profondeur','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Workshop.jpg','image/jpeg',10447168,'2013-09-06 21:55:20','Young filmmakers and family members participate in a workshop on filmmaking for social change.  Photo: Dustin Leader','De jeunes cinéastes et des membres de leur famille participent à un atelier de cinématographie pour le changement social. Photo: Dustin Leader ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'105',NULL,NULL),(70,NULL,'Be a learning organization','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Make sure to occasionally revise your theory of change (or the other model you chose to work with) to adapt to unexpected results. Even though it is important to have a clear direction for what you hope to achieve, practice might bring you to realize that you need to further adapt those goals. Be critical, reflective and flexible to improve your model. This is called &ldquo;double-loop learning&rdquo;, in which organizations <a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">&ldquo;critically examine our assumptions and our theories in light of the results&rdquo;</a>, going beyond changes to programs and activities.</li>\r\n<li>Take time to reflect after each public engagement activity. You can reflect on: What was supposed to happen? What did happen? Why? Include your lessons learned in an internal report, so future employees can learn from your experience instead of making the same mistakes or starting all over again. After each of your public engagement activities, take some time to reflect on what worked, what unexpected results can be incorporated in future, and what should be improved. Reporting is about learning to improve, not only about reporting to donors.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t modify your theory of change on a frequent basis. Your theory of change can be dynamic, but it is still a foundational document that shouldn&rsquo;t be changed without careful consideration. Changing it will have impacts down the line &ndash; on your methodologies and therefore your data, which can make it harder for statistical analysis and data comparison.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t believe there is &ldquo;no time&rdquo; for reflection or that you can &ldquo;do it later.&rdquo; If you do not take the time to reflect after each activity, your team will end up losing more time by making the same mistakes with new activities, and the quality of your public engagement evaluation data will suffer from it.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioner perspective:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;Through our public engagement campaign to raise awareness among Canadian teachers, students, and union members about global issues, we had some unexpected and unintended positive results, which we discovered through our regular monitoring activities. One of our Canadian partners spontaneously initiated the formation of a permanent international solidarity fund, funded directly from its own members. This is something that occurred as a direct result of our engagement on international development issues, but was not one of our anticipated outcomes or part of our theory of change. We learned from this and adapted our approach, and are now including the formation of an international fund as a possible &ldquo;step&rdquo; in the engagement ladder which we encourage.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&ndash; Program Director for a small NGO</p>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;At our planning stage, we elaborated two logic models: One for the desired poverty reduction changes in the field, and one for the desired behaviour changes (public engagement) to support poverty reduction from Canada. Even though complementary, the two logic models have been used and implemented separately with separate approaches. The regular monitoring of our results helped us realize that the Canadian and overseas logic models would benefit from being more integrated to better show how public engagement concretely supports international development initiatives beyond Canadians&rsquo; current targeted attitude or behaviour changes. This is the next step for us.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Public engagement specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:01:41','2013-09-06 22:02:09',6,'wide','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire :</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Veiller &agrave; r&eacute;viser p&eacute;riodiquement votre th&eacute;orie du changement (ou l&rsquo;autre mod&egrave;le avec lequel vous aurez choisi de travailler) pour vous adapter &agrave; des r&eacute;sultats inattendus. M&ecirc;me s&rsquo;il est important d&rsquo;avoir une id&eacute;e pr&eacute;cise de ce que vous voulez r&eacute;aliser, la pratique peut vous amener &agrave; voir que vous devez encore adapter vos objectifs. Faites preuve d&rsquo;esprit critique, de r&eacute;flexion et de souplesse pour am&eacute;liorer votre mod&egrave;le. C&rsquo;est ce qu&rsquo;on appelle &laquo; l&rsquo;apprentissage en double boucle &raquo;, par lequel les organisations ne se contentent pas d&rsquo;apporter des changements &agrave; leurs programmes et &agrave; leurs activit&eacute;s, mais <a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">&laquo; reviennent sur leurs hypoth&egrave;ses et leurs th&eacute;ories &agrave; la lumi&egrave;re de leurs r&eacute;sultats &raquo;</a>.</li>\r\n<li>Prendre le temps de faire le point, apr&egrave;s chaque activit&eacute; d&rsquo;engagement du public. Vous pouvez r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir aux questions suivantes : Qu&rsquo;est-ce qui &eacute;tait cens&eacute; arriver? Qu&rsquo;est-ce qui est arriv&eacute; de fait? Pourquoi? Consignez vos observations dans un rapport interne, de mani&egrave;re qu&rsquo;&agrave; l&rsquo;avenir le personnel puisse tirer les le&ccedil;ons de votre exp&eacute;rience au lieu de r&eacute;p&eacute;ter les m&ecirc;mes erreurs ou de devoir tout reprendre &agrave; z&eacute;ro. Apr&egrave;s chacune de vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public, prenez le temps de revenir sur ce qui a fonctionn&eacute;, sur les r&eacute;sultats inattendus &agrave; incorporer dor&eacute;navant au projet, et &agrave; ce qui pourrait &ecirc;tre am&eacute;lior&eacute;. Le rapport sert &agrave; apprendre pour s&rsquo;am&eacute;liorer, pas seulement &agrave; r&eacute;pondre aux questions des bailleurs de fonds.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire :</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ne modifiez pas votre th&eacute;orie du changement &agrave; tout bout de champ. Votre th&eacute;orie du changement peut &ecirc;tre &eacute;volutive, mais elle reste un document fondamental qu&rsquo;on ne doit pas modifier sans y avoir m&ucirc;rement r&eacute;fl&eacute;chi. Les changements que vous apporterez finiront par avoir un impact sur vos m&eacute;thodologies et donc aussi sur vos donn&eacute;es, ce qui rendra plus difficiles l&rsquo;analyse statistique et la comparaison des donn&eacute;es.</li>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;allez pas croire que vous n&rsquo;avez &laquo; pas le temps &raquo; de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir, ou que vous pourrez le faire &laquo; plus tard &raquo;. Si vous ne prenez pas le temps de r&eacute;fl&eacute;chir apr&egrave;s chaque activit&eacute;, votre &eacute;quipe finira par perdre encore plus de temps &agrave; force de r&eacute;p&eacute;ter les m&ecirc;mes erreurs &agrave; chaque nouvelle activit&eacute;, et la qualit&eacute; de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation de votre engagement du public en souffrira.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Notre campagne d&rsquo;engagement du public aupr&egrave;s d&rsquo;enseignant-e-s, d&rsquo;&eacute;tudiant-e-s et de syndiqu&eacute;-e-s canadiens sur des enjeux globaux a eu des effets inattendus et non recherch&eacute;s, que nous ont r&eacute;v&eacute;l&eacute;s nos activit&eacute;s r&eacute;guli&egrave;res de suivi. Un de nos partenaires canadiens a spontan&eacute;ment cr&eacute;&eacute; un fonds permanent de solidarit&eacute; internationale, financ&eacute; directement par ses membres. C&rsquo;est un r&eacute;sultat direct de notre travail d&rsquo;engagements sur les enjeux du d&eacute;veloppement international, mais ce n&rsquo;&eacute;tait pas un r&eacute;sultat que nous avions envisag&eacute; et cela ne faisait pas partie de notre th&eacute;orie du changement. Nous avons appris, nous avons adapt&eacute; notre approche, et nous avons ajout&eacute; la cr&eacute;ation d&rsquo;un fonds international comme un &laquo; &eacute;chelon &raquo; possible de l&rsquo;&eacute;chelle d&rsquo;engagement que nous proposons. &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&ndash; Charg&eacute;e de programme dans une petite ONG</p>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; &Agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification, nous avons &eacute;labor&eacute; deux mod&egrave;les logiques: un pour les changements recherch&eacute;s sur le terrain en mati&egrave;re de r&eacute;duction de la pauvret&eacute;, et l&rsquo;autre pour les changements de comportement d&eacute;sir&eacute;s (engagement du public) afin d&rsquo;appuyer la r&eacute;duction de la pauvret&eacute; au Canada. Quoique compl&eacute;mentaires, les deux mod&egrave;les logiques ont &eacute;t&eacute; utilis&eacute;s et appliqu&eacute;s s&eacute;par&eacute;ment et selon des approches diff&eacute;rentes. Le suivi r&eacute;gulier de nos r&eacute;sultats nous a aid&eacute;s &agrave; comprendre que les mod&egrave;les logiques pour le Canada et pour l&rsquo;&eacute;tranger gagneraient &agrave; &ecirc;tre plus int&eacute;gr&eacute;s, afin de faire mieux voir en quoi l&rsquo;engagement du public soutient concr&egrave;tement les initiatives de d&eacute;veloppement international en plus des changements d&rsquo;attitude ou de comportement qu&rsquo;on veut provoquer au Canada. C&rsquo;est la prochaine &eacute;tape pour nous. &raquo;</em><br /><br />- Sp&eacute;cialiste en engagement du public dans une grosse ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Être une organisation intelligente [apprenante]','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'M_E_BCCIC_mtg.jpg','image/jpeg',186030,'2013-09-06 22:01:35','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'174',NULL,NULL),(71,NULL,'Help reframe development','<p>Much of the public understands development as a question of charity &ndash; the idea that &ldquo;we&rdquo; (developed countries/the global north) need to give more to &ldquo;them&rdquo; (developing countries/the Global South). This has been described as the paradigm of the &ldquo;generous giver / deficient receiver.&rdquo; Many of our organizations have worked extensively to show how this paradigm is harmful to positive social change (for example, The South through the Northern Eye).</p>\r\n<p>The <em>Finding Frames: New Ways to Engage the UK Public in Global Poverty</em> report (developed by Andrew Darnton with Martin Kirk) explores how sometimes even when public engagement campaigns aim to send a different message &ndash; for instance, the Make Poverty History Campaign, which tried to look at poverty as an issue of political policy and trade justice &ndash; the public received the message as one of charitable giving. They call this the &ldquo;Live Aid Legacy,&rdquo; reflecting our tendency, and that of the public, to receive messages about global poverty through the &ldquo;frame&rdquo; of what we already understand.</p>\r\n<p>The report&rsquo;s authors challenge us to think about how our use of some of the tools of these early campaigns &ndash; eg: celebrity endorsements, benefit concerts &ndash; can re-activate this frame, and sometimes reinforce values that are the opposite of those which lead to positive social change.</p>\r\n<p>Lynette Shultz explores how recent shifts in public engagement practice have made the dynamic of the &ldquo;deficient recipient&rdquo; less visible, but questions whether the new paradigm of the &ldquo;empowered individual&rdquo; has sufficiently changed the power relations in our work.</p>\r\n<p>The Finding Frames report proposes that our sector look for ways to reinforce values such as universalism, cooperation and social justice in the way we plan and present our public engagement programs.</p>\r\n<p>As practitioners, we might imagine alternative frames such as collective action towards common goals or honouring leadership from the Global South and understanding our role as one of solidarity.</p>\r\n<p>For some organizations, our public engagement work connects closely with work in fundraising and communications. Sometimes, the messages that we think are very important in public engagement may not be the most effective messages for short-term goals like fundraising or communications. For this reason, it is critical to work within your organization to help align public engagement, communications and fundraising, or at least to minimize the potential for mixed messaging.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:02:20','2013-09-06 22:02:20',3,'tall','','',NULL,'<p>Une bonne partie du public voit le d&eacute;veloppement comme une question de charit&eacute; : c&rsquo;est l&rsquo;id&eacute;e que &laquo; nous &raquo; (les pays d&eacute;velopp&eacute;s, le Nord global) devons &laquo; leur &raquo; donner plus (&agrave; eux, les pays en d&eacute;veloppement, le Sud global). C&rsquo;est ce qu&rsquo;on a appel&eacute; le paradigme du &laquo; donateur g&eacute;n&eacute;reux / donataire n&eacute;cessiteux &raquo;. Plusieurs de nos organisations ont beaucoup travaill&eacute; pour montrer le tort que ce paradigme peut causer au changement social (voir, par exemple,<a href=\"http://www.acic-caci.org/our-work/the-south-through-the-northern-eye-ethical-images-campaign.html\"><span>The South through the Northern Eye</span></a><span>[Le Sud dans l&rsquo;&oelig;il du Nord]</span><span>).</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Le rapport </span><em>Finding Frames: New Ways to Engage the UK Public in Global Poverty</em><span> [</span><span>Trouver des cadres : nouvelles fa&ccedil;ons de mobiliser le public du Royaume-Uni autour de la pauvret&eacute; mondiale</span><span>] (r&eacute;dig&eacute; par Andrew Darnton et Martin Kirk) examine comment, m&ecirc;me lorsque que des campagnes d&rsquo;engagement du public cherchent &agrave; diffuser un message diff&eacute;rent &ndash; par exemple, la campagne &laquo; Pour en finir avec la pauvret&eacute; &raquo;, qui essayait de pr&eacute;senter la pauvret&eacute; comme un enjeu de politiques publiques et de justice commerciale --, le grand public continue de recevoir le message comme un appel &agrave; faire la charit&eacute;. Les auteurs baptisent &laquo; H&eacute;ritage </span><span>Live Aid</span><span> &raquo; cette tendance, qui est la n&ocirc;tre et celle du grand public, &agrave; &laquo; recadrer &raquo; les messages que nous recevons &nbsp;sur la pauvret&eacute; en fonction de nos id&eacute;es toutes faites sur le sujet.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Les auteurs du rapport nous invitent &agrave; nous demander comment notre fa&ccedil;on de recourir aux outils de campagnes ant&eacute;rieures &ndash; par ex., l&rsquo;appui de personnalit&eacute;s bien connues, les concerts b&eacute;n&eacute;fices &ndash; peut contribuer &agrave; r&eacute;activer le cadre traditionnel et renforcer ainsi des valeurs &agrave; l&rsquo;oppos&eacute; de celles qui favorisent un changement social positif.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Lynette Shultz</span><a href=\"http://www.cgcer.ualberta.ca/en/~/media/cgcer/Documents/ICN_GCE_and_the_Empowered_Individual.pdf\"><span>explore</span></a><span> comment de r&eacute;cents d&eacute;placements dans la pratique de l&rsquo;engagement du public ont att&eacute;nu&eacute; la dynamique du &laquo; donataire n&eacute;cessiteux &raquo;, mais elle se demande si le nouveau paradigme de &laquo; l&rsquo;individu habilit&eacute; &raquo; change suffisamment les rapports de pouvoir dans notre travail.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Le rapport </span><span>Finding Frames </span><span>propose &agrave; notre secteur de chercher le moyen de renforcer des valeurs comme l&rsquo;universalisme, la coop&eacute;ration et la justice sociale dans notre fa&ccedil;on de planifier et de d&eacute;ployer nos programmes d&rsquo;engagement du public.</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><span>Comme praticiennes et praticiens, nous pourrions imaginer des &laquo; cadrages alternatifs &raquo; : une action collective pour des objectifs communs, la c&eacute;l&eacute;bration du leadership manifest&eacute; par le Sud, notre r&ocirc;le relu en termes de solidarit&eacute;. </span></p>\r\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-534d2ef0-f549-05d5-e8aa-0aa3b7a78237\"><span>Pour certaines organisations, notre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public est trop &eacute;troitement associ&eacute; &agrave; la collecte de fonds et aux communications. Les messages que nous jugeons tr&egrave;s importants en engagement du public ne sont pas toujours les messages les plus efficaces pour des objectifs &agrave; court terme comme la collecte de fonds ou les communications. C&rsquo;est pourquoi il est indispensable de travailler avec votre organisation pour harmoniser l&rsquo;engagement du public, les communications et la collecte de fonds ou, du moins, pour r&eacute;duire le risque de messages divergents.</span></span></p>','Aider à resituer le développement','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(72,NULL,'Partner and collaborate in the spirit of inclusion','<p>Partnerships and collaborations that are formed in a spirit of inclusion can better respect and promote the value of diversity. Working with others allows for a diversity of organizations to be part of the conversation, helping to ensure that public engagement initiatives reflect diverse voices, actors and opinions.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:08:57','2013-09-06 22:11:17',7,'wide','','',NULL,'','','contexte','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'8033531074_4cb3519840_o.jpg','image/jpeg',6061104,'2013-09-06 22:08:47','Ensuring many are included. Photo: Calgary New Central Library','Ensuring many are included. Photo: Calgary New Central Library',NULL,NULL,NULL,'37',NULL,NULL),(73,NULL,'Clearly articulate your vision, goals and desired outcomes','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Seek out tools to clarify your organization&rsquo;s belief in how change happens, such as those found in the &ldquo;How Change Happens&rdquo; section of this site. These tools allow you to approach change in a strategic and thoughtful way while considering the qualitative and quantitative measures you might use in your monitoring and evaluation efforts. Some examples of commonly used tools include the theory of change, the pyramid of engagement, outcome mapping and the logic model. These tools will help you to find the best means of achieving the changes you seek.</li>\r\n<li>Consider your public engagement activities and how you evaluate them as part of an overall development program.</li>\r\n<li>Approach your beliefs about change for public engagement in Canada with the same two-way engagement that characterizes work with Southern partners. Public engagement in Canada should have the same reference points as international work, such as values of solidarity, anti-oppressive practice and equity. Ask yourself: How do you conduct and measure public engagement in your work with partners? Do you measure changes in behaviour or attitude? Can you look at your public engagement work in Canada with the same lens?</li>\r\n<li>Ask yourself the following questions:<br />\r\n<blockquote>What level(s) of change are you working with (personal, relational and/or societal)?<br /><br />What are your assumptions related to these desired changes?<br /><br />What would you like the outcomes to be?<br /><br />What is your organization or activity&rsquo;s role in this outcome? <br /><br />Where do you fit in the big picture?What are all the conditions you need to reach in order to be able to achieve your organization&rsquo;s vision?<br /><br />What actions do you need your audience to take to achieve your desired outcomes?<br /><br />How will you measure those actions? The progress towards your outcomes?</blockquote>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t base your actions solely on assumptions or intuition.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid looking at only one part of the process; use a holistic approach and take the time to articulate your whole vision.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t keep your theory of change hidden. It can be a powerful tool to inform and engage your target audience and others.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t simply apply someone else&rsquo;s theory of change to your work. While the Theory of Change for Public Engagement provides an excellent entry point, your organization&rsquo;s activities and initiatives will benefit from their own tailored theory of change. If your organization does not have a theory of change, start the discussion to develop one for your organization. In the meantime, you could refer to the broader Theory of Change for Public Engagement module of this toolkit.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioner&rsquo;s perspectives:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;In 2012, my organization went through a process of determining how we believe change happens. This process involved gathering input from the majority of our staff over several months. With the help of outside consultants we mapped out the conditions we need to reach, the actions that we encourage specific audiences to take, and our current campaigns and how those all reinforce our vision. The result of the exercise allows us to be clear on our organizational theories of change.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Public engagement specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;As part of a new public engagement program, we were working with a consultant to help us develop our monitoring and evaluation system. To start the process off, the consultants took us through a Theory of Change workshop. The workshop helped us to clearly articulate who our target audiences are, what changes we are hoping to bring about, and how we think the changes will happen. The session was very useful to help us think these things through and come to a common understanding as a team. We were then able to design a practical, useful monitoring and evaluation system around our theory of change.&rdquo;</em><br /><br />- Communications specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:16:45','2013-09-06 22:17:47',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Cherchez des outils pour pr&eacute;ciser les convictions de votre organisation sur la fa&ccedil;on de changer les choses, comme ceux qu&rsquo;on peut trouver dans la section &laquo; Comment survient le changement &raquo; de notre site. Ces outils vous permettront d&rsquo;approcher le changement de mani&egrave;re strat&eacute;gique et r&eacute;fl&eacute;chie et d&rsquo;envisager les indices qualitatifs et quantitatifs que vous pourriez utiliser pour suivre et &eacute;valuer votre travail. Entre autres outils largement utilis&eacute;s, citons la th&eacute;orie du changement, la pyramide de l&rsquo;engagement, la cartographie des incidences et le mod&egrave;le logique. Ces outils vous aideront &agrave; trouver les meilleurs moyens de provoquer les changements que vous recherchez.</li>\r\n<li>Consid&eacute;rez que vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public et votre fa&ccedil;on de les &eacute;valuer ne sont qu&rsquo;une partie de votre programme de d&eacute;veloppement global.</li>\r\n<li>Abordez vos croyances sur le changement en mati&egrave;re d&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada en appliquant les crit&egrave;res de r&eacute;ciprocit&eacute; qui caract&eacute;risent votre travail avec vos partenaires du Sud. L&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada devrait avoir les m&ecirc;mes points de rep&egrave;re que le travail international : valeurs de solidarit&eacute;, de pratique anti-oppressive et d&rsquo;&eacute;quit&eacute;. Posez-vous la question : comment pratiquez-vous et comment &eacute;valuez-vous l&rsquo;engagement du public dans votre travail avec vos partenaires? Mesurez-vous les changements de comportement ou d&rsquo;attitude? Pouvez-vous appliquer la m&ecirc;me grille d&rsquo;analyse &agrave; votre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public au Canada?</li>\r\n<li>Posez-vous les questions suivantes:<br /><br />Sur quel(s) niveau(x) de changement travaillez-vous (personnel, relationnel et/ou soci&eacute;tal)?<br /><br />Quelles sont vos hypoth&egrave;ses en lien avec les changements recherch&eacute;s?<br /><br />Quels r&eacute;sultats voudriez-vous obtenir?<br /><br />Quel r&ocirc;le jouent votre organisation ou vos activit&eacute;s pour l&rsquo;obtention de ces r&eacute;sultats? Quelle est votre place dans le tableau d&rsquo;ensemble?<br /><br />Quelles sont toutes les conditions qu&rsquo;il vous faut pour arriver &agrave; mettre en &oelig;uvre la vision de votre organisation?<br /><br />Quelles d&eacute;cisions doit prendre votre public pour que vous obteniez les r&eacute;sultats que vous recherchez?<br /><br />Comment allez-vous &eacute;valuer ces d&eacute;cisions? La progression vers les r&eacute;sultats que vous recherchez?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ne fondez pas votre action uniquement sur des hypoth&egrave;ses ou des intuitions.</li>\r\n<li>&Eacute;vitez de ne regarder qu&rsquo;une partie de la d&eacute;marche; appliquez une approche holistique et prenez le temps d&rsquo;articuler toute votre vision.</li>\r\n<li>Ne cachez pas votre th&eacute;orie du changement. Elle peut constituer un outil tr&egrave;s efficace pour informer et engager votre public cible et d&rsquo;autres encore.</li>\r\n<li>Ne vous contentez pas d&rsquo;appliquer &agrave; votre travail la th&eacute;orie du changement de quelqu&rsquo;un d&rsquo;autre. Si la Th&eacute;orie du changement pour l&rsquo;engagement du public offre un excellent point de d&eacute;part, les activit&eacute;s et les initiatives de votre organisation gagneront &agrave; s&rsquo;articuler &agrave; une th&eacute;orie du changement faite sur mesure. Si votre organisation n&rsquo;a pas de th&eacute;orie du changement, amorcez la discussion pour vous en donner une. Entre-temps, vous pourriez vous reporter &agrave; l&rsquo;approche plus g&eacute;n&eacute;rale de la Th&eacute;orie du changement pour l&rsquo;engagement du public, que vous trouvez dans notre bo&icirc;te &agrave; outils.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; En 2012, mon organisation a v&eacute;cu une d&eacute;marche pour d&eacute;finir nos convictions sur le changement. Cette d&eacute;marche nous a amen&eacute;s &agrave; prendre plusieurs mois pour recueillir les points de vue de la plus grande partie de notre personnel. Avec des consultant-e-s externes, nous avons cartographi&eacute; les conditions qu&rsquo;il nous faut atteindre, les d&eacute;cisions que nous voulons inviter diff&eacute;rents publics &agrave; prendre, nos campagnes en cours, et la fa&ccedil;on dont tout cela confirme notre vision. Les r&eacute;sultats de cet exercice nous permettent de toutes et tous bien comprendre les th&eacute;ories du changement de notre organisation. &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>- Sp&eacute;cialiste en engagement du public dans une grosse ONG</p>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Dans le cadre d&rsquo;un nouveau programme d&rsquo;engagement du public, nous avons travaill&eacute; avec un-e consultant-e qui nous a aid&eacute;s &agrave; mettre au point notre syst&egrave;me de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Pour d&eacute;buter, l&rsquo;expert-conseil nous a fait faire un atelier sur la Th&eacute;orie du changement. Cet atelier nous a aid&eacute;s &agrave; articuler clairement quels sont nos publics cibles, quels changements nous esp&eacute;rons provoquer et comment nous pensons que surviendront ces changements. La session a beaucoup aid&eacute; notre &eacute;quipe &agrave; creuser ces questions et &agrave; en arriver &agrave; une conception commune. Apr&egrave;s cela, nous avons pu concevoir, &agrave; partir de notre th&eacute;orie du changement, un syst&egrave;me de suivi-&eacute;valuation pratique.&raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>- Sp&eacute;cialiste en communications dans une grosse ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Articuler clairement votre vision, vos objectifs et les résultats que vous recherchez','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Occupy_Montreal_-_Global_Day_of_Action_-_2011-10-15_-_Victoria_Square_-_A_call_for_social_change.jpg','image/jpeg',963457,'2013-09-06 22:16:36','Photo: Justinform','Photo: Justinform',NULL,NULL,NULL,'192',NULL,NULL),(74,NULL,'Define the scope of your activities','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ensure evaluation and monitoring and its indicators are relevant to the objectives and outcomes of the specific public engagement initiative. Consider the elements that your organization wants to measure, including factors such as diversity or gender equality.</li>\r\n<li>Make indicators and tools appropriate to the change that you can realistically expect to see. Have indicators for width, depth, and height (for an explanation of those concepts, see <a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">&ldquo;Towards good practice in public engagement&rdquo;</a>).</li>\r\n<li>Ensure indicators and tools are realistically measurable and manageable based on the resources you have available (both human and financial).</li>\r\n<li>Verify that indicators and tools are applicable to, and implementable in, the context in which your public engagement activities are taking place.</li>\r\n<li>Establish a reference point or baseline at the design phase, and monitor progress throughout the process. In some cases, baseline data may not have been collected or may not be possible given the available resources. Depending on the type of change you want to measure, you can use other techniques such as a retrospective &ldquo;<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1TA4CVlh6mYV9CYXh71qIVZeVQpRv1mXO2A982O0bFeA/edit\" target=\"_blank\">post-then-pre&rdquo; question design</a> to measure change over time.</li>\r\n<li>Use a diverse set of indicators and methods, including qualitative and quantitative measures (a mixed method approach). Using a complementary suite of indicators is more important than any single indicator alone. At a doctor&rsquo;s office, for example, one&rsquo;s blood pressure alone may not reveal much, but when considered in concert with family history, cholesterol levels, weight, etc., a more complete picture can emerge. This practice is called \"triangulation\" or \"cross examination\" in social sciences.</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:24:57','2013-09-06 22:25:14',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Veiller &agrave; ce que l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation et le suivi correspondent bien aux objectifs et aux r&eacute;sultats de l&rsquo;initiative particuli&egrave;re d&rsquo;engagement du public. Examinez les &eacute;l&eacute;ments que votre organisation veut mesurer, entre autres des facteurs comme la diversit&eacute; ou l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes.</li>\r\n<li>Veillez &agrave; ce que les outils et les indicateurs conviennent au changement que vous pouvez esp&eacute;rer de mani&egrave;re r&eacute;aliste. Ayez des indicateurs de largeur, de profondeur et de hauteur (pour une explication de ces concepts, voir <a href=\"http://www.ccic.ca/_files/en/what_we_do/002_public_engagement_2009-03_toward_good_practice_in_public_engagement.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">&laquo; Pour une bonne pratique en engagement du public &raquo;</a>).</li>\r\n<li>Veillez &agrave; ce que les indicateurs et les outils soient pratiques &agrave; mesurer et &agrave; g&eacute;rer compte tenu des ressources (humaines et financi&egrave;res) dont vous disposez.</li>\r\n<li>V&eacute;rifiez que les indicateurs et les outils peuvent bien s&rsquo;appliquer dans le contexte o&ugrave; se d&eacute;rouleront vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public.</li>\r\n<li>D&eacute;finissez un point de r&eacute;f&eacute;rence ou un point de d&eacute;part d&egrave;s l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la conception, et surveillez la progression tout au long de la d&eacute;marche. Dans certains cas, on n&rsquo;aura pas collig&eacute; les donn&eacute;es de d&eacute;part &ndash; ou on n&rsquo;aura pas pu les colliger &ndash; vu les ressources disponibles. Tout d&eacute;pendant du type de changement que vous souhaitez mesurer, vous pouvez avoir recours &agrave; d&rsquo;autres techniques comme une grille de questions r&eacute;trospectives &laquo; post-then-pre &raquo; [o&ugrave; on s&rsquo;interroge apr&egrave;s coup sur ce qui a chang&eacute;] afin de mesurer le changement dans le temps .</li>\r\n<li>Utilisez une gamme diversifi&eacute;e d&rsquo;indicateurs et de m&eacute;thodes, notamment des mesures qualitatives et quantitatives (approche mixte). Il est pr&eacute;f&eacute;rable d&rsquo;appliquer une s&eacute;rie compl&eacute;mentaire d&rsquo;indicateurs que de s&rsquo;en remettre &agrave; un seul. Chez le m&eacute;decin, par exemple, le seul chiffre de la pression sanguine peut ne pas r&eacute;v&eacute;ler grand-chose, mais si vous y ajoutez l&rsquo;histoire familiale, le taux de cholest&eacute;rol, le poids, etc., vous aurez probablement un tableau plus complet de la situation. En sciences sociales, on donne &agrave; cette pratique le nom de &laquo; triangulation &raquo; ou d&rsquo; &laquo; examen transversal &raquo;.</li>\r\n</ul>','Définir la portée de vos activités','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Occupy_Montreal_-Beaver_Hall_Hill.jpg','image/jpeg',1095422,'2013-09-06 22:24:45','Photo: Justinform','Photo: Justinform',NULL,NULL,NULL,'188',NULL,NULL),(75,NULL,'Develop a theory of change','<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;Public engagement activities often include events or one-time workshops with Canadians. How can we evaluate the impacts of these smaller engagements and ensure that they are contributing to our vision? Placing these activities in the context of an explicit and thoughtful theory of change illuminates their role in the profound social change that we are working towards. It can be very empowering to see all of your organization&rsquo;s activities connected in this way.&rdquo;</em><br /><br />-Communications Specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Has your organization talked about:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where you are in terms of public engagement?</li>\r\n<li>Where you are going?</li>\r\n<li>How you will get there?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Because of the breadth of public engagement activities in which organizations are engaged, articulating your desired outcomes and the actions required to achieve them is crucial to evaluating the success of your activities. A &ldquo;theory of change&rdquo; can be a very useful tool for clarifying these processes.</p>\r\n<p>Developing a theory of change takes time. You can dedicate time and resources to it over a specific, defined time period and then revisit it periodically, or you can develop it in an evolving, ongoing process. Rest assured, however, that there are always ways to discuss theories of change and to do good evaluation, even with limited resources. The key is to be clear about what you want to achieve, and set realistic, measurable objectives that are meaningful to the change you are aiming for.</p>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:32:59','2013-09-06 22:33:10',6,'small','','',NULL,'<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Les activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public comprennent souvent des &eacute;v&eacute;nements ou des ateliers ponctuels avec les Canadiennes et les Canadiens. Comment &eacute;valuer l&rsquo;impact de ces petits exercices d&rsquo;engagement et faire en sorte qu&rsquo;ils contribuent &agrave; notre vision? Le fait de replacer ces activit&eacute;s dans le contexte d&rsquo;une th&eacute;orie du changement explicite et m&ucirc;rement r&eacute;fl&eacute;chie &eacute;clair le r&ocirc;le qu&rsquo;elles jouent dans le changement social en profondeur auquel nous travaillons. Il peut &ecirc;tre tr&egrave;s dynamisant de voir sous cet angle le lien entre toutes les activit&eacute;s de votre organisation. &raquo;</em><br /><br />- Sp&eacute;cialiste en communications pour une grosse ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Votre organisation a-t-elle pris le temps de se dire:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>O&ugrave; vous en &ecirc;tes en mati&egrave;re d&rsquo;engagement du public?</li>\r\n<li>O&ugrave; vous allez?</li>\r\n<li>Comment vous allez vous y rendre?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&Eacute;tant donn&eacute; la vari&eacute;t&eacute; des activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public dans lesquelles sont impliqu&eacute;es les organisations, il est essentiel d&rsquo;articuler les r&eacute;sultats que vous voulez obtenir et les moyens que vous allez prendre afin de pouvoir &eacute;valuer le succ&egrave;s de vos activit&eacute;s. Une &laquo; th&eacute;orie du changement &raquo; vous sera tr&egrave;s utile pour pr&eacute;ciser ces processus.</p>\r\n<p>Il faut du temps pour &eacute;laborer une th&eacute;orie du changement. Vous pouvez soit y consacrer du temps et des ressources pendant une p&eacute;riode de temps d&eacute;finie pour y revenir ensuite p&eacute;riodiquement, soit mettre votre th&eacute;orie au point dans le cadre d&rsquo;un processus permanent d&rsquo;&eacute;volution &agrave; plus long terme. Comprenez bien, cependant, qu&rsquo;il est toujours possible de discuter de th&eacute;orie du changement et de faire un bon travail d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation m&ecirc;me avec des ressources limit&eacute;es. La cl&eacute;, c&rsquo;est de d&eacute;finir clairement ce que vous voulez faire, de vous fixer des objectifs r&eacute;alistes, mesurables et pertinents pour le changement que vous recherchez.</p>','Développer une théorie du changement','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TIG_theory_of_change_flickr.jpg','image/jpeg',255129,'2013-09-06 22:32:53','TakingITGlobal: http://canada.tigweb.org/','TakingITGlobal: http://canada.tigweb.org/',NULL,NULL,NULL,'160',NULL,NULL),(76,NULL,'Embed monitoring & evaluation in each stage of your public engagement plan','<p>Organisations should have a clear understanding of why they are conducting evaluations. The question of why should be asked particularly in the planning stages of your public engagement campaign. Ask yourself: What do you hope to learn from the evaluation? How you will use the information? Keep in mind the spirit of the Istanbul Principles, which insist on an evaluation that empowers people and demonstrates multiple accountability.</p>\r\n<p>The following questions will help to determine the indicators, processes, tools and overall approach to use in your evaluation:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What do you want to know? (i.e. What is the change you hope your public engagement work will achieve? How is it affecting women and men?)</li>\r\n<li>How will you know it? (i.e. Which indicators will give you the information you want?)</li>\r\n<li>Where can this information be obtained? (i.e. What are your data sources?)</li>\r\n<li>How and when will this information be collected? (i.e. What tools and methods will be used to collect data? What resources are required?)</li>\r\n<li>How will you maintain rigour in your data collection and data reporting? (i.e. Are your methods and processes replicable? Is your data reliable and valid? Do your methods align with the specific scale of change you are working towards? Have you identified variables and considered external forces that impact your results?)</li>\r\n<li>How will you use this information? (i.e. program improvement, reporting to participants, donors or internal stakeholders, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>How can you engage your participants meaningfully and respectfully throughout the process?</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:40:00','2013-09-06 22:40:52',6,'wide','','',NULL,'<p>Les organisations doivent bien comprendre dans quel but elles font des &eacute;valuations. La question du pourquoi devrait se poser en particulier &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification de votre campagne d&rsquo;engagement du public. Demandez-vous : que voulons-nous apprendre de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation? Comment allons-nous utiliser cette information? Ayez &agrave; l&rsquo;esprit les Principes d&rsquo;Istanbul, qui insistent sur une &eacute;valuation qui permet aux gens de se prendre en mains et de se rendre des comptes &agrave; divers niveaux. Les questions que voici vont vous aider &agrave; choisir les indicateurs, les d&eacute;marches, les outils et l&rsquo;approche d&rsquo;ensemble &agrave; utiliser dans votre &eacute;valuation:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Que voulez-vous savoir? (Quel est le changement que vous voulez provoquer par votre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public? En quoi touchera-t-il les femmes et les hommes?)</li>\r\n<li>Comment le saurez-vous? (Quels sont les indicateurs qui vous donneront l&rsquo;information que vous voulez avoir?)</li>\r\n<li>O&ugrave; peut-on trouver cette information? (Quelles sont vos sources de donn&eacute;es?)</li>\r\n<li>Quand et comment cette information sera-t-elle recueillie? (Quels sont les outils et les m&eacute;thodes de cueillette de donn&eacute;es que vous utiliserez? De quelles ressources aurez-vous besoin?)</li>\r\n<li>Comment allez-vous assurer la rigueur dans la cueillette des donn&eacute;es et la production des rapports? (Vos m&eacute;thodes et vos processus peuvent-ils &ecirc;tre reproduits? Vos donn&eacute;es sont-elles fiables et valides? Vos m&eacute;thodes correspondent-elles aux bar&egrave;mes de changement particuliers sur lesquels vous travaillez? Avez-vous identifi&eacute; des variables et envisag&eacute; les facteurs externes qui peuvent influencer vos r&eacute;sultats?)</li>\r\n<li>Quel usage allez-vous faire de cette information? (am&eacute;liorer le programme, faire rapport aux participant-e-s, aux bailleurs de fonds, &agrave; des intervenant-e-s internes, etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Comment allez-vous impliquer vos participant-e-s dans ce processus d&rsquo;une mani&egrave;re &agrave; la fois s&eacute;rieuse (le sens) et respectueuse (la mani&egrave;re)?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','Intégrer le suivi-évaluation à chacune des étapes de votre plan d’engagement du public','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Program_Evaluation___Design_June_2013_Workshop_33.jpg','image/jpeg',4860196,'2013-09-06 22:39:32','Photo: Wilfredor','Photo: Wilfredor',NULL,NULL,NULL,'28',NULL,NULL),(77,NULL,'Ensure that sufficient resources are available to support monitoring and evaluation activities','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Keep the organization&rsquo;s resources in mind in the planning phase, such as people, money and time. When identifying your indicators and data sources, consider the resources required to actually collect and report on the data. Be mindful of the resources needed to implement evaluation at several points in a project, including mid-term and final.</li>\r\n<li>Remember that monitoring and evaluation is an ongoing process for your organization&rsquo;s learning, as well as measuring the organization&rsquo;s steps towards long-term goals. Considering how monitoring and evaluation extends beyond the life of a particular project (long-term impact) is also important in your resource allocation.</li>\r\n<li>Delineate roles for staff and volunteers in conducting monitoring and evaluation. Identify who will be responsible for data collection, analysis, reporting, etc. and allocate time for staff/volunteers accordingly. Someone needs to be in charge of evaluation to ensure that all the necessary pieces of work are happening. This lead person must also be able to count on the help of other key team members. These responsibilities should be made clear from the beginning, in the planning phase of a public engagement project, and should be valued by the organization as a whole on an ongoing basis.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t underestimate the time and resources required to conduct your monitoring and evaluation activities. If you don&rsquo;t plan realistically, the quantity and quality of your data will suffer.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t leave the responsibility for conducting monitoring and evaluation unassigned. Something that is everyone&rsquo;s job can sometimes become no one&rsquo;s job.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t give up on evaluation because you think the knowledge or resources aren&rsquo;t available to carry it out.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioners&rsquo; perspectives:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>\"I have been involved in evaluations with budgets ranging from under $1,000 to the hundreds of thousands. An evaluation with a smaller budget is not necessarily less valuable, but it does often require organizations to be very focused and specific about what they want to measure and how they can best measure it given the resources available. For example, rather than conducting a large-scale survey of all public engagement program participants, the organization may choose to do a smaller-scale focus group with a few participants to gather participant feedback.\"</em></p>\r\n<p>- Monitoring &amp; Evaluation Specialist</p>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;At the planning stage of each public engagement activity, we identify who is in charge of the coordination of the activity, and who will support this person. Together, the group agrees on the objectives, target audience, deadlines, evaluation methods and responsibilities. The Coordinator writes all of it in a Terms of Reference document for the activity, which becomes the reference document for all the people involved. He/she is in charge of making sure the activity is organized according to what has initially been decided, supporting the team members with what they need (often with reminders), and writing the final report, including compiling the evaluation data provided by everyone. This process works very well for us and ensures that nothing is left out.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Communications Specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 22:53:56','2013-09-06 22:54:42',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ayez &agrave; l&rsquo;esprit les ressources de l&rsquo;organisation d&egrave;s l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification (les personnes, l&rsquo;argent et le temps). En choisissant vos indicateurs et vos sources de donn&eacute;es, pensez aux ressources n&eacute;cessaires pour recueillir concr&egrave;tement ces donn&eacute;es et en tirer des rapports. N&rsquo;oubliez pas les ressources n&eacute;cessaires pour proc&eacute;der &agrave; des &eacute;valuations &agrave; diff&eacute;rentes &eacute;tapes du projet, notamment &agrave; mi-parcours et &agrave; la fin.</li>\r\n<li>Rappelez-vous que le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation sont un processus continu qui permet &agrave; votre organisation d&rsquo;apprendre en m&ecirc;me temps qu&rsquo;elle mesure les &eacute;tapes &agrave; franchir pour atteindre ses objectifs &agrave; long terme. Il importe &eacute;galement de songer, dans l&rsquo;allocation des ressources, que le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation se poursuivront apr&egrave;s qu&rsquo;un projet particulier sera termin&eacute; (impact &agrave; long terme).</li>\r\n<li>D&eacute;finissez les r&ocirc;les des membres du personnel et des b&eacute;n&eacute;voles dans la r&eacute;alisation du suivi et de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Pr&eacute;cisez qui sera responsable de la collecte des donn&eacute;es, de leur analyse, de la pr&eacute;paration des rapports, etc., et organisez en cons&eacute;quence le temps du personnel et des b&eacute;n&eacute;voles. Il faut que quelqu&rsquo;un soit responsable de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation pour veiller &agrave; ce que tout ce qui doit &ecirc;tre fait se fasse bien. Cette personne devra pouvoir compter sur l&rsquo;aide d&rsquo;autres membres importants de l&rsquo;&eacute;quipe. Ces responsabilit&eacute;s doivent &ecirc;tre d&eacute;finies clairement d&egrave;s le d&eacute;part, &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification du projet d&rsquo;engagement du public, et doivent &ecirc;tre reconnues et appr&eacute;ci&eacute;es r&eacute;guli&egrave;rement par l&rsquo;ensemble de l&rsquo;organisation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ne sous-estimez pas le temps et les ressources n&eacute;cessaires pour r&eacute;aliser vos activit&eacute;s de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Si vos plans ne sont pas r&eacute;alistes, la quantit&eacute; et la qualit&eacute; de vos donn&eacute;es vont en souffrir.</li>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;oubliez pas de confier &agrave; un-e responsable la direction du suivi et de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Ce qui est la responsabilit&eacute; d&rsquo;un peu tout le monde finit souvent par n&rsquo;&ecirc;tre fait par personne.</li>\r\n<li>Ne renoncez pas &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation parce que vous ne croyez pas avoir la comp&eacute;tence ou les ressources pour la r&eacute;aliser.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size: 10px;\">Point de vue pratique</span></strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; J&rsquo;ai particip&eacute; &agrave; des &eacute;valuations avec des budgets qui allaient de 1000 $ &agrave; plusieurs centaines de milliers de dollars. Une &eacute;valuation &agrave; petit budget n&rsquo;est pas n&eacute;cessairement moins utile, mais elle exige souvent que les organisations d&eacute;finissent pr&eacute;cis&eacute;ment ce qu&rsquo;elles veulent mesurer et la meilleure fa&ccedil;on pour elles de le mesurer compte tenu des ressources dont elles disposent. Par exemple, au lieu de proc&eacute;der &agrave; un sondage &agrave; grande &eacute;chelle de tous les participant-e-s au programme d&rsquo;engagement du public, l&rsquo;organisation peut choisir de tenir un groupe de discussion &agrave; plus petite &eacute;chelle avec quelque participant-e-s pour recueillir leurs r&eacute;actions. &raquo;</em><br /><br />- Sp&eacute;cialiste en suivi-&eacute;valuation</p>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; &Agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification de chaque activit&eacute; d&rsquo;engagement du public, nous pr&eacute;cisons qui est responsable de coordonner l&rsquo;activit&eacute; et qui va l&rsquo;appuyer. Ensemble, le groupe se met d&rsquo;accord sur les objectifs, le public cible, les &eacute;ch&eacute;ances, les m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation et les responsabilit&eacute;s. La personne coordonnatrice consigne le tout dans un &laquo; mandat &raquo; pour l&rsquo;activit&eacute;, et ce document devient la r&eacute;f&eacute;rence pour toutes les personnes concern&eacute;es. La m&ecirc;me personne veillera &agrave; ce que l&rsquo;activit&eacute; soit organis&eacute;e conform&eacute;ment &agrave; ce qui a &eacute;t&eacute; d&eacute;cid&eacute; au d&eacute;part, elle appuiera les membres de l&rsquo;&eacute;quipe dans ce qu&rsquo;ils ont &agrave; faire (souvent &agrave; l&rsquo;aide de rappels) et elle r&eacute;digera le rapport final, ce qui comprend la compilation des donn&eacute;es d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation que tout le monde lui aura fournies. Cette fa&ccedil;on de faire fonctionne tr&egrave;s bien pour nous et fait en sorte qu&rsquo;on n&rsquo;oublie rien. &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Sp&eacute;cialiste en communications pour une grosse ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Veiller à avoir suffisamment de ressources pour soutenir les activités de suivi et d’évaluation','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'resources_attribution_to_Ideaschema.jpg','image/jpeg',415291,'2013-09-06 22:53:47','Ideaschema http://www.flickr.com/photos/rustychainsaw/8367537673/','Ideaschema http://www.flickr.com/photos/rustychainsaw/8367537673/',NULL,NULL,NULL,'436',NULL,NULL),(78,NULL,'Ensure your whole organization supports and benefits from monitoring and evaluation','<p>The organizational context within which monitoring and evaluation for public engagement are conducted has an impact on the evaluation process and outcomes. Evaluation is valuable not only as a tool for responding to funders (i.e. funder-directed or mandated evaluation), but also as a way for the organization to reflect on and learn from its work internally and to determine if long-term goals and outcomes are being met. It is critical that monitoring and evaluation activities are properly resourced and supported, including both financial and human resources as well as attention from the organization&rsquo;s leadership.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Consider these questions:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>How does your organization view monitoring and evaluation? As a valuable tool from which you can learn? As a means of measuring your progress towards long-term change through public engagement? Or as strictly a funding requirement? Do you do it for yourselves? Or for others&rsquo; sake?</li>\r\n<li>Who is accountable for monitoring and evaluation in your organization? Is there buy-in on the importance of monitoring and evaluation from all levels of the organization? How is that exhibited?</li>\r\n<li>How does the organization plan to learn from its monitoring and evaluation?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Promote multiple accountability: Monitoring and evaluation activities should answer questions that are important to the organization and participants, as well as those identified by funders. It is helpful if there is an overall organizational plan or approach to monitoring and evaluation in place (i.e. one flowing from the organization&rsquo;s theory of change).</li>\r\n<li>As a learning organization, all relevant stakeholders (e.g. leadership, staff, project participants, funders, etc.) should be engaged as appropriate throughout the stages of monitoring and evaluation (planning, implementation, reporting). Stakeholders can then identify important evaluation questions (both for the specific public engagement project and for the organization as a whole) and ensure buy-in and support for monitoring and evaluation. When identifying stakeholders to engage in this process, be sure to consider the needs of participants using a gender/anti-oppressive lens.</li>\r\n<li>It may also be helpful to take a longer-term view than just the timeline of a public engagement project when evaluating outcomes for the organization as a whole.</li>\r\n<li>If the outcomes are unexpected or not positive, be sure to include a learning component to the evaluation for internal growth and development.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Too often, monitoring and evaluation are driven by the requirements of project funders. Organizations get stuck in the often-limited boxes provided by funders, causing a silo effect in their organizations and a missed opportunity for learning. While accountability to funders is an important function of monitoring and evaluation, ensuring accountability is only one of its many functions.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioners&rsquo; perspectives:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;We feel, and are, really accountable to the funders. So if they want the numbers of participants, that&rsquo;s sometimes all they&rsquo;re interested in seeing. One meeting with one funder was quite shocking, where we were basically told in no uncertain terms that the unintended results that we thought were amazing - they fundamentally altered how we were doing some things - were of no interest to them. As they pass these results up the line, the only thing that starts to matter is how many people attended this workshop and how many volunteers there were. This was difficult to hear, since we didn&rsquo;t see that as having as much of an impact. It is disempowering in terms of the work that we do, if it is reduced to just those numbers.&rdquo;</em><br /><br />-Project Coordinator for a small NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-06 23:05:17','2013-09-06 23:05:32',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p>Le contexte organisationnel dans lequel se font le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation du travail d&rsquo;engagement du public a un impact sur le processus d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation et sur ses r&eacute;sultats. L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation est pr&eacute;cieuse non seulement pour r&eacute;pondre aux bailleurs de fonds (&eacute;valuation destin&eacute;e aux bailleurs de fonds ou exig&eacute;e par eux) mais aussi pour permettre &agrave; l&rsquo;organisation de faire le point &agrave; l&rsquo;interne sur son travail, d&rsquo;en tirer des le&ccedil;ons et de v&eacute;rifier si elle a atteint les objectifs &agrave; long terme et les r&eacute;sultats qu&rsquo;elle s&rsquo;&eacute;tait fix&eacute;s. Il est essentiel que les activit&eacute;s de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation soient ad&eacute;quatement soutenues, notamment sur le plan des ressources humaines et financi&egrave;res, et qu&rsquo;elles retiennent l&rsquo;attention de la direction de l&rsquo;organisation.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Examinez les questions suivantes:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Comment votre organisation envisage-t-elle le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation? Comme un outil pr&eacute;cieux et &eacute;clairant? Comme un moyen de mesurer le progr&egrave;s accompli en vue d&rsquo;un changement &agrave; long terme, fruit de l&rsquo;engagement du public? Ou seulement comme une exigence li&eacute;e au financement? Le faites-vous pour vous? Ou pour d&rsquo;autres?</li>\r\n<li>Qui est responsable du suivi et de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation dans votre organisation? Est-ce que tout le monde reconna&icirc;t l&rsquo;importance du suivi et de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation &agrave; tous les niveaux de l&rsquo;organisation? Comment cela s&rsquo;exprime-t-il?</li>\r\n<li>Comment l&rsquo;organisation pr&eacute;voit-elle tirer les le&ccedil;ons de ses activit&eacute;s de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Promouvoir l&rsquo;imputabilit&eacute; multiple: les activit&eacute;s de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation doivent r&eacute;pondre aux questions qui sont importantes pour l&rsquo;organisation et les participant-e-s autant qu&rsquo;&agrave; celles que posent les bailleurs de fonds. Il est utile d&rsquo;avoir dans l&rsquo;organisation un plan ou une approche d&rsquo;ensemble du suivi et de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation (qui d&eacute;coule de la th&eacute;orie du changement adopt&eacute;e par l&rsquo;organisation).</li>\r\n<li>Dans une organisation intelligente, toutes les parties concern&eacute;es (la direction, le personnel, les participant-e-s aux projets, les bailleurs de fonds, etc.) doivent participer de mani&egrave;re ad&eacute;quate aux diff&eacute;rentes &eacute;tapes du suivi-&eacute;valuation (planification, mise en &oelig;uvre, rapport). Les parties pourront alors identifier des questions importantes &agrave; &eacute;valuer (tant pour tel projet particulier d&rsquo;engagement du public que pour l&rsquo;organisation dans son ensemble) et veiller &agrave; ce que le suivi-&eacute;valuation soit accept&eacute; et soutenu. Au moment d&rsquo;identifier les personnes qui participeront &agrave; cette d&eacute;marche, veillez &agrave; tenir compte des besoins des participant-e-s en utilisant une approche non sexiste et anti-oppressive.</li>\r\n<li>Il sera sans doute bon d&rsquo;adopter une approche &agrave; long terme plut&ocirc;t que de se limiter au calendrier d&rsquo;un projet d&rsquo;engagement du public, au moment d&rsquo;&eacute;valuer l&rsquo;efficacit&eacute; de l&rsquo;organisation dans son ensemble.</li>\r\n<li>Si les r&eacute;sultats sont inattendus ou s&rsquo;ils ne sont pas positifs, veillez &agrave; int&eacute;grer &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation un volet d&rsquo;apprentissage pour la croissance interne le perfectionnement.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Trop souvent, le suivi et l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation sont dict&eacute;s par les exigences des bailleurs de fonds. Les organisations sont coinc&eacute;es dans les cat&eacute;gories souvent &eacute;troites des bailleurs de fonds, ce qui entra&icirc;ne un &laquo; effet de silo &raquo; et fait rater des occasions d&rsquo;apprendre. La reddition de comptes aux bailleurs de fonds est certes une fonction importante du suivi-&eacute;valuation, mais ce n&rsquo;est l&agrave; qu&rsquo;une fonction parmi plusieurs autres.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Nous nous sentons et nous sommes redevables aux bailleurs de fonds. S&rsquo;ils veulent avoir le nombre des participant-e-s, il arrive que ce soit la seule chose qu&rsquo;ils veuillent voir. Une r&eacute;union avec un bailleur de fonds a &eacute;t&eacute; franchement consternante : on nous a dit tr&egrave;s clairement que les r&eacute;sultats non escompt&eacute;s que nous jugions extraordinaires &ndash; ils modifiaient fondamentalement certaines de nos fa&ccedil;ons de travailler &ndash; ne les int&eacute;ressaient absolument pas. Pour pr&eacute;senter ces r&eacute;sultats en haut lieu, la seule chose qui a un peu d&rsquo;importance, c&rsquo;est combien de personnes ont assist&eacute; &agrave; tel atelier, ou combien il y avait de b&eacute;n&eacute;voles. C&rsquo;&eacute;tait p&eacute;nible &agrave; entendre, parce que nous ne trouvions pas que ces chiffres-l&agrave; avaient vraiment beaucoup d&rsquo;impact. &Ccedil;a devient d&eacute;courageant, dans le travail que nous faisons, si tout se ram&egrave;ne &agrave; ces seuls chiffres. &raquo;<br /></em><br />-Coordonnatrice de projet pour une petite ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Veiller à ce que toute l’organisation soutienne le suivi-évaluation et en bénéficie','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'June_4_Member_Meeting_010.jpg','image/jpeg',764108,'2013-09-06 23:05:05','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'44',NULL,NULL),(79,NULL,'Evaluate your evaluation regularly','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Commit to midterm evaluations at a minimum to ensure that the correct indicators and methods are being used. A midterm evaluation also allows you to incorporate new learning for the remainder of your public engagement campaign or project.</li>\r\n<li>Consider iterative evaluation (ongoing evaluation which incorporates feedback in a cycle of learning, adjustment, monitoring, and evaluating during the project). Building on the point above, iterative evaluation would have several moments identified in the life of your public engagement project to incorporate lessons learned. Iterative evaluation is of great value in creating a responsive public engagement program and a learning culture in the organization.</li>\r\n<li>Ensure that your evaluation methods can be replicated and scaled up.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do not wait until the end of your project to conduct your evaluation, or the accuracy and credibility of the data and reporting will suffer. Your data will be less meaningful and less exact. Also, you might not have used the right indicators nor the right methods to efficiently measure your impact, thereby distorting your data. You will also have missed many opportunities for learning and improvement throughout the project.</li>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t collect data that is not meaningful or useful. If an audience is witness to pointless data collection, it can lead to disengagement or apathy. Be careful and mindful about why and when you collect data. Ask yourself: What are you promising people in return? What is the benefit for participants? Be transparent about what the data will be used for.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioner&rsquo;s perspectives:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;There is pressure to have quantitative results and quantitative indicators, such as number of pamphlets that we handed out or the number of participants that came to the workshop, as these things are easy and cheap to count. There are definitely funders who want to take that approach; this is challenging, as sometimes the indicators that are easy to get are not the ones that are really meaningful.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Monitoring &amp; Evaluation Specialist</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-07 02:01:20','2013-09-07 02:01:39',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Engagez-vous &agrave; faire au moins une &eacute;valuation &agrave; mi-parcours, pour vous assurer qu&rsquo;on utilise les bons indicateurs et les bonnes m&eacute;thodes. Une &eacute;valuation &agrave; mi-parcours vous permet aussi d&rsquo;int&eacute;grer de premi&egrave;res le&ccedil;ons &agrave; la suite de votre campagne ou de votre projet d&rsquo;engagement du public.</li>\r\n<li>Pensez &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation it&eacute;rative (&eacute;valuation continue qui incorpore la r&eacute;troaction &agrave; un cycle d&rsquo;apprentissage, d&rsquo;ajustement, de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation en cours de projet). Dans le prolongement de ce qu&rsquo;on a dit plus haut, l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation it&eacute;rative pr&eacute;voirait plusieurs moments, dans la vie de votre projet d&rsquo;engagement du public, o&ugrave; incorporer les le&ccedil;ons tir&eacute;es du suivi. L&rsquo;&eacute;valuation it&eacute;rative est tr&egrave;s utile pour mettre au point des programmes d&rsquo;EP efficaces et pour susciter une culture de l&rsquo;apprentissage au sein de l&rsquo;organisation.</li>\r\n<li>Veillez &agrave; ce que vos m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation puissent &ecirc;tre reproduites et appliqu&eacute;es &agrave; plus grande &eacute;chelle.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;attendez pas &agrave; la fin de votre projet pour faire l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation, car la pr&eacute;cision et la cr&eacute;dibilit&eacute; de vos donn&eacute;es en souffriront. Vos donn&eacute;es auront moins de sens et seront moins exactes. Et vous pourriez ne pas avoir utilis&eacute; les bons indicateurs ou les bonnes m&eacute;thodes pour mesurer ad&eacute;quatement votre impact, ce qui faussera vos donn&eacute;es. Vous aurez aussi laiss&eacute; passer plusieurs occasions d&rsquo;apprendre et d&rsquo;am&eacute;liorer le projet en cours de route.</li>\r\n<li>Ne recueillez pas de donn&eacute;es qui ne sont pas significatives ou qui ne sont pas utiles. Un public &agrave; qui on pr&eacute;sente une cueillette de donn&eacute;es non pertinentes deviendra facilement d&eacute;mobilis&eacute; ou apathique. Demandez-vous pourquoi et &agrave; quel moment recueillir les donn&eacute;es. Posez-vous la question. Que promettez-vous aux gens en &eacute;change ? Quel est l&rsquo;avantage pour les participant-e-s? Expliquez clairement &agrave; quoi serviront les donn&eacute;es (transparence).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Il y a de la pression pour produire des r&eacute;sultats et des indicateurs quantitatifs, comme le nombre de d&eacute;pliants distribu&eacute;s ou le nombre de participant-e-s &agrave; l&rsquo;atelier, parce que ce sont des donn&eacute;es faciles &agrave; traiter &agrave; petit prix. Il y a certainement des bailleurs de fonds qui veulent suivre cette approche; c&rsquo;est un probl&egrave;me, car il arrive que les indicateurs qui sont faciles &agrave; obtenir ne soient pas vraiment les plus &eacute;clairants. &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>-Sp&eacute;cialiste en suivi-&eacute;valuation</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Évaluer régulièrement votre évaluation','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'WMCONF_2013_-_Feedback_session_006.JPG','image/jpeg',1636485,'2013-09-07 02:01:06','Photo: Maor X','Photo: Maor X',NULL,NULL,NULL,'72',NULL,NULL),(80,NULL,'Identify your target audience','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Be clear as to who your audience is and whether they are online or offline. In order to measure the impact of your public engagement activities, it is necessary to have direct knowledge of and access to your audience. Different methods of interaction will also require different approaches and different definitions of &ldquo;target audience.&rdquo;</li>\r\n<li>Adopt a participatory approach as much as possible, and engage your stakeholders at all stages in the monitoring and evaluation process. Make your evaluation fun and empowering for participants. Close the loop with your participants by reporting back to them on your findings.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Do not use broad audience targets, such as &lsquo;the general public&rsquo; or &lsquo;Canadians&rsquo;. Measuring the engagement, knowledge, interests or behaviour changes of all Canadians is likely not realistic for your organization. This would need to be done through public polling. Instead, use existing research to situate your public engagement activities in the broader Canadian context; this will help your public engagement be credible and realistic, and will allow you to show more efficiently the impact of your activities in your reports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioners&rsquo; perspectives:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;In 2011, we received funding for a two-year project to engage youth on issues related to gender as well as to train volunteers as peer educators. One of the first steps that we undertook was to meet with an external evaluator to develop a comprehensive evaluation plan. In these initial planning stages, we identified our different participants &ndash; volunteer peer educators, workshop participants, community mentors, teachers and others &ndash; and identified the different outcomes and objectives that the project would lead to for each of them.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Once we had articulated and documented the targets, outcomes and objectives, we were able to create the evaluation tools that we needed to monitor the project&rsquo;s success in engaging these different audiences along the way. In the end, we developed short surveys for workshop participants and teachers, an interview guide for mentors, and a series of surveys, focus groups, and arts-based tools for the volunteer peer educators (the most engaged participants in the project).</em></p>\r\n<p><em>By having these discussions early on in the project and recognizing that we had different audiences for different activities, we were able to prepare the evaluation tools that we needed and were ready to hit the ground running regarding evaluation as soon as we started on the different project activities. Importantly, while this project had some funding dedicated to working with an external evaluator, we extensively documented our experiences working with her and used those lessons (e.g., starting early, developing diverse tools for diverse audiences, ensuring strong baseline data, etc.) and adapted those tools for other projects where we were not able to support an external evaluator.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>- Project Coordinator for a small NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-07 02:13:13','2013-09-07 02:26:43',6,'small','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire :</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sachez bien qui est votre public cible et s&rsquo;il est en ligne ou hors ligne. Pour mesurer l&rsquo;impact de vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public, il faut bien conna&icirc;tre votre public et y avoir acc&egrave;s directement. Diff&eacute;rentes m&eacute;thodes d&rsquo;interaction appelleront des approches diff&eacute;rentes et diff&eacute;rentes d&eacute;finitions du &laquo; public cible &raquo;.</li>\r\n<li>Adoptez autant que possible une approche participative et mobilisez les parties concern&eacute;es &agrave; toutes les &eacute;tapes du processus de suivi et d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation. Faites en sorte que votre &eacute;valuation soit amusante et responsabilisante pour les participant-e-s. Bouclez la bouche en informant les participant-e-s des r&eacute;sultats de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ne prenez pas de publics cibles trop larges, comme &laquo; le grand public &raquo; ou &laquo; la population canadienne &raquo;. Il n&rsquo;est probablement pas r&eacute;aliste pour votre organisation d&rsquo;entreprendre de mesurer le niveau d&rsquo;engagement, l&rsquo;int&eacute;r&ecirc;t ou les changements de comportement du public canadien. Cela exigerait de grands sondages. Tirez plut&ocirc;t parti de la recherche existante pour situer vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public &agrave; l&rsquo;int&eacute;rieur du contexte canadien; cela conf&eacute;rera de la cr&eacute;dibilit&eacute; et du r&eacute;alisme &agrave; votre travail d&rsquo;engagement du public, et vous permettra d&rsquo;exposer de mani&egrave;re plus efficace l&rsquo;impact de vos activit&eacute;s dans vos diff&eacute;rents rapports.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; En 2011, nous avons re&ccedil;u du financement pour un projet de deux ans visant &agrave; mobiliser les jeunes sur des enjeux reli&eacute;s &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; entre les femmes et les hommes et &agrave; former des b&eacute;n&eacute;voles comme &eacute;ducatrices et &eacute;ducateurs de leurs pairs. Une des premi&egrave;res choses que nous avons faites, c&rsquo;a &eacute;t&eacute; de rencontrer une &eacute;valuatrice externe pour mettre au point un plan d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation complet. &Agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;tape de la planification, nous avons identifi&eacute; nos diff&eacute;rents participants &ndash; &eacute;ducateurs et &eacute;ducatrices b&eacute;n&eacute;voles, participant-e-s aux ateliers, mentors dans la collectivit&eacute;, enseignant-e-s et autres &ndash; et nous avons pr&eacute;cis&eacute; les r&eacute;sultats et les objectifs du projet pour chacun de ces groupes.</em></p>\r\n<p><em>Une fois d&eacute;finis et document&eacute;s les cibles, les r&eacute;sultats et les objectifs, nous avons pu d&eacute;velopper les outils d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation qu&rsquo;il nous fallait pour observer le succ&egrave;s du projet aupr&egrave;s de ses diff&eacute;rents publics. En fin de compte, nous avons pr&eacute;par&eacute; de courts sondages pour les participant-e-s aux ateliers et pour les enseignant-e-s, un guide d&rsquo;entrevue pour les mentors, et une s&eacute;rie de sondages, de groupes de discussion et d&rsquo;outils ax&eacute;s sur les arts pour les &eacute;ducateurs et &eacute;ducatrices b&eacute;n&eacute;voles (les participants les plus engag&eacute;s dans le projet).</em></p>\r\n<p><em>En discutant de ces questions d&egrave;s le d&eacute;but du projet et en prenant acte du fait que nous devions traiter avec diff&eacute;rents publics pour diff&eacute;rentes activit&eacute;s, nous avons pu pr&eacute;parer les outils d&rsquo;&eacute;valuation qu&rsquo;il nous fallait et nous &eacute;tions fins pr&ecirc;ts, pour l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation, d&egrave;s que nous avons lanc&eacute; nos diff&eacute;rentes activit&eacute;s. &Agrave; noter : comme notre projet avait pr&eacute;vu du financement pour travailler avec une &eacute;valuatrice externe, nous avons document&eacute; abondamment tout le travail que nous avons fait avec elle et nous avons utilis&eacute; ce que nous avons appris (l&rsquo;importance de commencer t&ocirc;t, la pr&eacute;paration d&rsquo;outils diff&eacute;rents pour diff&eacute;rents publics, la cueillette minutieuse des donn&eacute;es de d&eacute;part, etc.) afin d&rsquo;adapter ces outils &agrave; d&rsquo;autres projets pour lesquels nous ne pouvions pas nous permettre de faire appel &agrave; une &eacute;valuatrice ou &agrave; un &eacute;valuateur externe.&raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>- Coordonnatrice de projet pour une petite ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Identifier votre public cible','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Online_survey_005.jpg','image/jpeg',1084526,'2013-09-07 02:12:57','','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'54',NULL,NULL),(81,NULL,'Involve a variety of stakeholders in articulating your beliefs about change','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Involve a variety of people, including staff, participants (members of your target audience), volunteers, alumni and others in your visioning work. The participants and alumni have directly experienced the change processes that you believe in; they can give you a very good perspective on your organization&rsquo;s beliefs about change.</li>\r\n<li>Use multiple methods of involvement in order to involve multiple stakeholders in your visioning. Participatory methods are especially powerful in engaging participants in discussions about change. Focus groups could help, as well as individual phone calls or an online survey sent to participants. Make sure to involve both men and women in the discussion and address the specificities of public engagement and change for both sexes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t discuss your beliefs about change only in a small closed group or with just your public engagement team. Your beliefs will become clearer as you share and discuss them with a variety of perspectives from different stakeholders. Wider stakeholder engagement also tests your internal perspective with your external target audience.</li>\r\n</ul>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-07 02:50:41','2013-09-07 02:51:57',6,'wide','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Faites participer diff&eacute;rentes cat&eacute;gories de personnes, notamment des membres de votre personnel, des participant-e-s (membres de votre public cible), des b&eacute;n&eacute;voles, des ancien-ne-s et d&rsquo;autres &agrave; votre travail de visualisation. Les participant-e-s et les ancien-ne-s ont v&eacute;cu les processus de changement auxquels vous croyez; ils peuvent vous donner une excellente perspective sur les croyances de votre organisation au sujet du changement.</li>\r\n<li>Recourez &agrave; diff&eacute;rentes m&eacute;thodes pour faire participer les gens afin de rejoindre diff&eacute;rents groupes concern&eacute;s par votre visualisation. Les m&eacute;thodes participatives sont particuli&egrave;rement efficaces pour faire entrer les gens dans des discussions sur le changement. Les groupes de discussion vous seront utiles de m&ecirc;me que les appels t&eacute;l&eacute;phoniques ou un sondage en ligne pour rejoindre les participant-e-s. Veillez &agrave; faire participer &agrave; la discussion et les hommes et les femmes, et abordez ce que l&rsquo;engagement du public et le changement peuvent avoir de sp&eacute;cifique pour les deux sexes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>N&rsquo;allez pas discuter de vos opinions sur le changement en petit groupe ferm&eacute; ou seulement avec votre &eacute;quipe d&rsquo;engagement du public. Vos croyances vont se pr&eacute;ciser si vous les partagez et les discutez avec diff&eacute;rents intervenants qui auront des points de vue diff&eacute;rents. En rejoignant diff&eacute;rents groupes concern&eacute;s, vous pourrez mieux comparer votre perspective interne avec votre public cible &agrave; l&rsquo;ext&eacute;rieur.</li>\r\n</ul>','Faire appel à différents intervenants pour articuler vos croyances sur le changement','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'CHM_December_2012_wikipedians.jpg','image/jpeg',134058,'2013-09-07 02:50:35','Photo: Fuzheado ','Photo: Fuzheado ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'30',NULL,NULL),(82,NULL,'Know your target audience’s current level of engagement','<p><strong>Do&rsquo;s:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ask yourself: Who are your public engagement activities targeting? At what point are they on your engagement continuum? Consider the agenda of your target audience. What changes or progress do you want to see from them? For instance, do you want the youth involved to move from receiving your emails to actually participating in your events, or even to organize events themselves? Return to your theory of change and the original project design and adjust accordingly.</li>\r\n<li>Close the loop with your participants and others by reporting evaluation back to them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;ts:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Don&rsquo;t assume each of your audiences should be engaged in the same way. Your previous reflection on your theory of change will help identify at what point each of your target audiences are and how to maintain that engagement or move them along the engagement continuum.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Practitioner perspective:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;We realized that to be able to monitor and evaluate people&rsquo;s level of commitment, and their change in commitment over time, we needed to decipher the different levels at which people can engage with our work. The exercise began with determining our audience, the actions they take, and sketching it out within a six-level pyramid framework. We later changed the pyramid framework into an engagement spectrum.&rdquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&ndash;Public engagement specialist for a large NGO</p>\r\n</blockquote>',NULL,0,1,NULL,'good-practices','2013-09-07 03:02:53','2013-09-07 03:04:29',6,'tall','','',NULL,'<p><strong>&Agrave; faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Posez-vous la question : Quel public veulent rejoindre vos activit&eacute;s d&rsquo;engagement du public? &Agrave; quel niveau est-il rendu sur votre &eacute;chelle d&rsquo;engagement? Pensez &agrave; ce que fait votre public cible. Quels changements ou quel progr&egrave;s souhaitez-vous lui voir faire? Par exemple, souhaitez-vous que les jeunes passent du niveau o&ugrave; ils re&ccedil;oivent des courriels &agrave; celui o&ugrave; ils participent aux &eacute;v&eacute;nements que vous organisez, ou qu&rsquo;ils en viennent m&ecirc;me &agrave; en organiser eux-m&ecirc;mes? Retournez &agrave; votre th&eacute;orie du changement et &agrave; la conception originale de votre projet et apportez les ajustements qui s&rsquo;imposent.</li>\r\n<li>Bouclez la boucle avec vos participant-e-s et avec les autres en les informant des r&eacute;sultats de l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>&Agrave; ne pas faire:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ne supposez pas que tous vos publics cibles doivent &ecirc;tre rejoints de la m&ecirc;me fa&ccedil;on. La r&eacute;flexion que vous avez faite sur votre th&eacute;orie du changement va vous aider &agrave; pr&eacute;ciser o&ugrave; en est rendu chacun de vos publics cibles et &agrave; choisir comment maintenir ce niveau d&rsquo;engagement ou comment le faire progresser sur sa lanc&eacute;e.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Point de vue pratique:</strong></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p><em>&laquo; Nous avons compris que pour suivre et pour &eacute;valuer le niveau d&rsquo;engagement des gens, et le changement dans leur engagement au fil du temps, il nous fallait d&eacute;chiffrer les diff&eacute;rents niveaux auxquels les gens peuvent s&rsquo;engager dans ce que nous faisons. Nous avons d&rsquo;abord d&eacute;fini notre public, les gestes qu&rsquo;il pose, puis nous avons dessin&eacute; une pyramide &agrave; six &eacute;tages pour encadrer les niveaux d&rsquo;engagement. Plus tard, nous avons transform&eacute; notre pyramide pour en faire un spectre des niveaux d&rsquo;engagement. &raquo;</em></p>\r\n<p>&ndash; Sp&eacute;cialiste en engagement du public pour une grosse ONG</p>\r\n</blockquote>','Connaître le niveau actuel d’engagement de votre public cible','principe','',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'FEMA_-_21700_-_Photograph_by_Robert_Kaufmann_taken_on_01-20-2006_in_Louisiana.jpg','image/jpeg',4347664,'2013-09-07 03:02:24','Photo: Robert Kaufmann','Photo: Robert Kaufmann',NULL,NULL,NULL,'20',NULL,NULL);
/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `items` ENABLE KEYS */;
UNLOCK TABLES;

